/* ============================================================
   GUEST: "Sister Agnes" — "The Building That Breathes"
   NF STANDARD: 20 segments per playthrough. First 5 = INTRO RUNWAY.
   FAILURE MODEL v2 (heat/rapport -> endings, never mid-run death).
   ------------------------------------------------------------
   TRAIT MECHANIC (G15 P60 F95 H10): fragile + frightened, WANTS GENTLENESS.
     - PLAY ALONG is the warm move -> belief steadies her; rapport climbs.
     - STEER is the SAFEST move -> a soft, sideways question lets her
       approach the hard thing without being cornered; rapport climbs,
       and steer often surfaces the eeriest concrete detail.
     - PUSH BACK is DANGEROUS -> she does not fight, she FOLDS. A direct
       challenge makes her apologize, shrink, threaten to stop. Rapport
       craters. (Inverse of Vance, who feeds on the fight.)
     - DEADPAN / SILENCE reads as SAFE quiet -> "the quiet from your end
       feels safe." She fills it herself. Gentle, positive, low-heat.
   The art with Agnes: patience. Never corner her. The eeriest tape in the
   roster is hers IF you can keep her talking. Belief is the bond; the
   challenge is the risk. One RARE protective push (counseling her NOT to
   expose herself) lands as care, not attack -> see read_it.

   THE KNIFE'S EDGE: the mundane explanation is ALSO horrifying. Either the
   sub-basement is a sentient archive that eats memory, OR it's a sick
   building (CO2/VOCs/mold cognitive fog) plus institutional cruelty
   ('voluntary separation') plus an aging, frightened mind that built a
   haunted house out of a hard job. The host can never be sure which, and
   neither, quite, can she.

   A single path walks 20 nodes:
     INTRO (5): arrive, thefloor, theforgetting, marta, thequestion
     ARC (13): one of three:
       THE FLOOR     flr_*  (engage the building: warmth, dust, the breath)
       THE FORGETTING frg_* (engage the people: Marta, the forms, the slip)
       THE CARD      crd_*  (engage her: what she took, how she got out)
     CONVERGENCE: read_it (read the key-card ID live?) -> endings
     ENDINGS: end_louder / end_nobody (+ busted/walkout hooks)

   RESEARCH WOVEN IN (fictionalized): underground federal records archives
   (limestone-mine storage, hand-processed retirement files, records
   retention schedules, "permanent vs temporary," classified holdings);
   memory science (source-monitoring error, the misinformation effect,
   transient global amnesia, dissociative fugue, sundowning); sick-building
   syndrome (CO2, VOCs, Stachybotrys/mold, radon -> real cognitive fog and
   memory complaints); institutional "managing out" ('voluntary cognitive
   separation,' NDAs, the bureaucratic erasure of a person).
============================================================ */
(function(){
window.NF_GUESTS = window.NF_GUESTS || {};

window.NF_GUESTS.sister = {
  name:"\"Sister Agnes\"",
  handle:"@thequietfloor",
  tag:"THE BUILDING THAT BREATHES",
  freq:"88.6 FM // PIRATE",
  blurb:"Anonymous. Former overnight cleaner at an underground federal records facility — sub-level four, the floor everyone said was just dead files. Speaks barely above a whisper. Believes the floor 'remembers,' and that the people who worked it slowly forgot their own names. She isn't loud enough to triangulate. She's just terrified.",
  card:"Fragile and frightened — she came for gentleness. PLAY ALONG and STEER steady her; belief is the bond and rapport climbs. PUSH BACK and she doesn't fight — she FOLDS, apologizes, threatens to stop. DEADPAN reads as safe quiet; she fills it. The art is patience. The eeriest tape in the roster is hers if you can keep her talking.",
  difficulty:"★★★ — wants gentleness",
  traits:{grandiosity:15, paranoia:60, fragility:95, hostility:10},
  start:"arrive",
  pathLength:20,

  nodes:{

  /* ================= INTRO RUNWAY (5) ================= */

  arrive:{
    seg:"COLD OPEN — can you hear me", act:1,
    lines:[
      ["sys","RELAY","02:14. No name on the booking sheet, just a time and the word PLEASE. She came in through the back, kept her coat on, sat as far from the microphone as the cord allows. She flinches at the ON AIR light."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quietly] I'm sorry. Can you hear me okay? I don't want to be too loud. I got used to being quiet down there — you learn to be quiet so the floor doesn't notice you. ...Is that light supposed to stay on the whole time? Okay. Okay. I'll try not to look at it."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"I can hear you perfectly, Agnes. We can go as quiet and as slow as you need. Nobody's rushing you here.",
       fx:{hype:9,heat:3,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long, shaky breath out] ...Thank you. Nobody says that. Everybody wants me to get LOUD, get to the point, make it good radio, and the louder they want me the smaller I get. You said slow. [pause] I can do slow. Slow is how I lasted eleven years down there without — without it noticing me too much. Let me start where it's safe. The top of the building. We'll go down together, if that's all right."],
       reveal:"Eleven years; she 'lasted' by staying unnoticed",
       note:"Agnes WANTS gentleness. Permission to go slow in the first ten seconds steadies her completely.",
       next:"thefloor"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Before anything else — are you comfortable? Do you want the lights down a little?",
       fx:{hype:8,heat:2,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[surprised] ...You can do that? The lights? [a small sound] Down a little, yes. Thank you. It's easier in the half-dark — I spent so long in it that bright rooms feel like being looked at. [softer now] There. That's better. You asked if I was comfortable before you asked what I saw. Nobody does that. It makes me think I can tell you the rest."],
       reveal:"Bright light reads as 'being looked at'; she's eased by the half-dark",
       next:"thefloor"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You're safe here. The light just means we're recording you, so your words exist somewhere outside your own head. That's all.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[looking at the light differently] ...Outside my own head. [quietly] You don't know how much I needed those exact words. Because that's the whole problem, isn't it — for eleven years the only place any of this existed was inside my head, and a thing that only lives in your head, they can make you doubt it. They're very good at making you doubt it. If it's on your tape, then even if I forget it tonight, it'll still be true in the morning. Yes. Let's make it true in the morning."],
       reveal:"Her core fear: things that live 'only in her head' can be doubted away",
       next:"thefloor"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"[you keep your voice low and even, and just leave a warm, unhurried silence for her]",
       fx:{hype:8,heat:2,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[after a moment, almost relieved] ...You're not going to fill it. The silence. Everybody fills the silence — they're scared of it, so they talk over me to make it stop. You just... let it sit. [a breath] The quiet from your end feels safe. Most quiet doesn't feel safe to me anymore; down there, quiet meant it was listening. But yours is the other kind. The kind where someone's waiting, not watching. I can talk in this kind. Thank you."],
       note:"Deadpan/silence reads as SAFE quiet to Agnes — she distinguishes 'waiting' from 'watching.'",
       next:"thefloor"}
    ]
  },

  thefloor:{
    seg:"COLD OPEN — sub-level four", act:1,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Let me tell you what the place was, the real version, not the version on the badge. A records facility. Federal. Built down into an old limestone mine, because paper needs cool and dry and the ground gives you both for free. Most of it's exactly as boring as it sounds — miles of shelving, retirement files, tax records, a whole underground city of paper that nobody alive will ever read again."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I cleaned it. Nights. Floors one through three were just... a job. Fluorescent hum, a vending machine that ate your dollar, the good kind of boring. And then there was sub-level four. Everyone said four was just dead files, the permanent collection, the stuff too old to ever be requested. But four was different the way a held breath is different from an empty room. I knew it the first night and I spent eleven years pretending I didn't."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"A held breath instead of an empty room — I understand exactly what you mean. What made four feel that way?",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[grateful she didn't have to defend it] You DO understand. An empty room is just absent. Four felt OCCUPIED — like the absence of people only made room for something else to be present. The temperature was the first thing. One through three were climate-controlled cold, the same boring cold every night. Four was always a degree or two too warm right over the oldest cabinets, the sealed ones. Warm like something had been sitting there. Warm like a chair someone just got up from. You don't notice it for a week. Then you can't stop noticing it, and once you can't stop, four has you."],
       reveal:"Level 4: a 'held breath,' a persistent warmth over the oldest sealed cabinets",
       next:"theforgetting"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Let's stay up top for one more minute. What did a normal shift look like, before four was ever your problem?",
       fx:{hype:9,heat:2,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[settling, on safe ground] Oh, it was almost nice, the normal part. Clock in at ten, sign the log, get your cart. Empty the bins, mop the corridors, wipe the reading-room tables, refill the dispensers. You'd see maybe one archivist working late, nod, never talk. The hum of the lights, the squeak of the cart wheel that always needed oil. By two in the morning the whole place was yours. For three floors, being alone underground was peaceful. That's what made four so wrong later — the SAME building, the same boring routine, and one floor down it curdled. The normalness upstairs is how I knew four wasn't normal. I had something to compare it to."],
       reveal:"The mundane routine upstairs is her baseline — 'how I knew four wasn't normal'",
       next:"theforgetting"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You spent eleven years pretending you didn't notice. That takes a kind of strength most people don't have.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[eyes filling] ...Strength. Nobody's ever called it that. They call it — when they're kind, they call it 'imaginative,' and when they're not, they call it other things. But you're right that it took something. You can't just walk away from a federal job at my age with no degree and no savings. So every night I went down to four and I told myself the warmth was a vent, the dust was dust, the forgetting was age. Eleven years of arguing myself out of my own eyes. THAT'S the part that exhausts you. Not the floor. The pretending."],
       reveal:"She rationalized for 11 years — 'arguing myself out of my own eyes'",
       next:"theforgetting"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...A held breath. [you let the phrase sit in the quiet, unhurried]",
       fx:{hype:9,heat:2,rapport:12},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[nodding to herself] A held breath. You didn't rush past it. Most people would've said 'a held breath, sure, and then what,' but you let it BE a held breath for a second, and that's — that's how it actually felt, so thank you for letting it feel like that out loud. [softly] A building can hold its breath. I know how that sounds. But you spend enough nights alone with one and you learn its breathing, the way you learn a sleeping person's, and four breathed wrong. Held too long. Let go too sharp. I'm still not used to buildings that breathe right."],
       next:"theforgetting"}
    ]
  },

  theforgetting:{
    seg:"COLD OPEN — what it took", act:1,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And then I started forgetting things. Small at first — where I'd parked, whether I'd locked the cart. I blamed the hour, the age, the boredom. But it got specific in a way tiredness isn't. I forgot my mother's middle name. I'd had it my whole life. Rose. It came back later, but for three days there was just a hole where Rose used to be, and I could feel the EDGES of the hole, which is worse than not knowing — knowing there was a word and the word's been lifted out clean."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","That's the thing nobody believes and I understand why. Forgetting feels like nothing — that's its whole horror. You don't feel it leave. You only find the empty drawer later. And the closer I worked to those sealed cabinets on four, the more drawers came up empty. I started writing things down. My own name, on my own hand, in pen, before each shift. In case."],
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Feeling the edges of the hole where a word used to be — that's a real and terrible thing. I believe you felt it.",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:4,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[crying quietly, but steadier] ...The edges of the hole. Yes. You're the first person who didn't immediately say 'oh that happens to everyone, I forget names all the time.' Because everyone DOES forget names — that's exactly what made it impossible to explain, the symptom is too ordinary. But ordinary forgetting is fuzzy, it's 'it's on the tip of my tongue.' This wasn't fuzzy. This was SURGICAL. A clean hole with sharp edges where a specific thing had been removed. You don't lose a word like Rose the way you lose your keys. Someone lost it FOR me. That's the difference I could never make anyone hear, and you heard it in one sentence."],
       reveal:"The forgetting was 'surgical' — clean-edged removal, not fuzzy age",
       next:"marta"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You started writing your own name on your hand. Walk me through that — what else did you write down, and when?",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a small, embarrassed laugh] It sounds mad, doesn't it, a grown woman writing her name on her hand like a child. But it was a system. Before every shift, in the locker room: my name on the left hand. My mother's name, my address, the date, on a card in my left pocket — always left, because I decided left was the pocket the floor couldn't reach, which is its own kind of mad, I know. And one fact I loved, one a night, something true about my life, so I'd have an anchor. Some mornings I'd read the card in the parking lot and the facts felt like a stranger's. But they were in my handwriting, so they had to be mine. The handwriting was the proof. The handwriting was the only thing it couldn't take."],
       reveal:"Her ritual: name on hand, anchor-facts on a card in the 'left pocket the floor can't reach'",
       next:"marta"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You found a way to keep yourself, one fact at a time. That's not madness, Agnes. That's survival.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[holding onto the word] Survival. [nodding] I'm going to keep that one, I think, the way I kept the facts. Because here's what nobody understands about being down there: it wasn't dramatic. There was no monster. There was just me, every night, doing a quiet job and slowly becoming less of a person, and a card in my pocket that was the whole war. People want horror to be loud. Mine was the quietest thing in the world. A woman writing 'your name is Agnes' on her own hand at 51 years old so she'd still be Agnes at dawn. That's the horror. It whispers."],
       reveal:"'No monster' — the horror is quiet, gradual depersonalization",
       next:"marta"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Rose. [you say her mother's name back to her, gently, and leave room]",
       fx:{hype:10,heat:3,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a sharp breath, then a tearful smile] ...You said it back. Rose. You gave it back to me out loud, and for a second I felt the drawer slide shut full instead of empty. [steadier] That's a small mercy and I felt all of it. You know what the floor never did? Say anything back. Eleven years and it only ever TOOK, it never gave a single word back. You just gave me my mother's name in a warm room with the lights low. I think I can tell you the hard part now. There was a woman. Her name was Marta."],
       next:"marta"}
    ]
  },

  marta:{
    seg:"COLD OPEN — Marta", act:1,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Marta worked four longer than me. Years longer. She was the one who taught me the left-pocket trick, actually — I thought I'd invented it, but she'd been doing it a decade before me, which means she knew, she'd known the whole time and just kept going because where else does a woman like us go. One night I came down and she was standing at the lockers. Just standing. Crying. Very softly, so the floor wouldn't notice. She couldn't remember which locker was hers."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And the supervisor came down. They always knew when someone slipped — I never understood how, but he came down within the hour, and he was so KIND about it. So gentle. He had a form already. He walked her out with his hand on her shoulder like a daughter. She didn't come back. Her locker was empty the next night. Cleaned out. By someone who wasn't me. And here's the thing I can't put down: I cried for Marta for a week, and then one day I realized I couldn't quite picture her face. Mine forgot her too. The building got us both. It just got me slower."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The supervisor had a form ready. They weren't surprised when she slipped — they were waiting for it.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[whispering faster, the words tumbling] You SEE it. He wasn't surprised. You don't carry a form for a thing you don't expect. The form was already filled out — I saw it, the top part, her name typed in, before she'd done anything but stand at a locker. They filled out the form for forgetting BEFORE she forgot. Which means they KNEW. They knew it would happen to her, they know it happens to everyone who works four long enough, and the form isn't a surprise, it's a SCHEDULE. The forgetting isn't a side effect. [very quiet] I think the forgetting is what four is FOR. And I worked it eleven years. I'm a slow drawer they haven't finished emptying."],
       reveal:"The pre-filled form implies the forgetting is scheduled, expected — 'what four is for'",
       note:"Belief steadies her into her boldest claim. Play Along is the engine of her disclosure.",
       next:"thequestion"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The form he carried — did you ever see what it was actually called?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[pause, and you can hear her reading it off the inside of her eyelids] ...'Voluntary Cognitive Separation.' Green form, the kind with the carbon copy behind it so there's a pink one for the file and a yellow one for — I don't know who gets the yellow one. I saw the title upside down across the supervisor's desk while he was being kind to Marta. Voluntary. [her voice cracks] As if she VOLUNTEERED to forget which locker was hers. As if anyone volunteers for that. I think about that word every single day. Voluntary. It's the cruelest word in the English language when you put it on that form."],
       reveal:"The form: 'Voluntary Cognitive Separation' — green carbon-copy, pink for file",
       next:"thequestion"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You cried for a week and then couldn't picture her face. That loss is real, Agnes, whatever caused it.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[breaking a little] That's the part I can't forgive — not what happened to me, what happened to my MEMORY of her. Marta was kind to me, she taught me how to survive, she was a whole person with a laugh and a way of folding her sandwich wrapper into a little square, and now when I reach for her face there's a smear where the face should be. The building didn't just take her. It took my ability to MOURN her properly, which is the second death, the one nobody talks about. If I'm right about four, then somewhere there's a sealed cabinet that's a degree too warm, and that's all that's left of Marta, and I can't even bring her a flower. [whisper] Say her name sometimes. Marta. So she's somewhere besides a warm drawer."],
       reveal:"'The second death' — losing the memory of Marta, not just Marta",
       next:"thequestion"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"[you let Marta's empty, cleaned-out locker hang in the quiet, and don't rush to fill it]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly, after the silence does its work] ...You felt it too. The empty locker. The cleaned-out shelf where a person was. Everybody wants me to get to the 'point,' but Marta WAS the point — a whole life cleaned out of a room overnight while the vending machine upstairs kept humming and eating dollars like nothing in the world had ended. The world doesn't stop for the quiet ones. That's what four understood that I didn't, for too long: nobody comes looking for a woman who was already trying not to be noticed. We were chosen for the job because we were already half-erased. [a breath] I think I have to ask you something now. The thing I came here to decide."],
       next:"thequestion"}
    ]
  },

  /* ================= THE PITCH — posture fork ================= */
  thequestion:{
    seg:"THE TURN — the thing in my pocket", act:2,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I have to tell you why I really came, because I can't carry the decision alone anymore. The night before I finally left, I took something. From four. A key card — the level-four access card, the kind they're supposed to collect when you leave. I didn't hand it back. It's in my left pocket right now. [a long pause] It still feels warm. I don't know if that's real or if I brought a piece of the floor out into the world with me, in my coat, for three years."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And I keep circling the same three things, and I don't know which one to open with you. The FLOOR itself — what the building actually is, the warmth, the breathing, what I think lives in those cabinets. Or the FORGETTING — Marta, the forms, the others, what it does to a person. Or ME — the card, what I took, how I got out, and whether I should ever have. Which one feels safe enough to start? You choose. I trust you to choose. That's new for me, trusting someone to choose."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Let's start with the building itself, Agnes. Tell me what you think four really is. I'm with you.",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:4,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[steadying] The building. Yes. Maybe it's easier to talk about the floor than about myself — the floor can't be embarrassed. [a breath] All right. I'll tell you what eleven years taught me about what's down there, and you can decide for yourself whether I'm describing a haunted place or a sick one, because I genuinely no longer know which would be worse. Stay gentle with me through it. There are parts I've never said out loud, not once, not even to the card in my pocket."],
       reveal:"Opens the door to the building itself — 'haunted or sick, I no longer know which is worse'",
       flag:"floor", next:"flr_warmth"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Start wherever it hurts least. If the people feel safer than the building — tell me about the others who slipped.",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:4,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a small nod] The people. That's — yes, that's kinder to start with, because at least the people loved each other a little, down there. The building never loved anybody. [softly] I'll tell you about the ones who slipped, and the forms, and what the forgetting actually feels like from the inside, which is the part I can never get anyone to sit still for. You'll sit still, won't you. You've sat still this whole time. All right. Let me tell you about my little vanished family of the quiet floor."],
       reveal:"Opens the door to the people — 'my little vanished family of the quiet floor'",
       flag:"forgetting", next:"frg_others"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Then let's start with you, Agnes — the card, how you got out. You're the bravest part of this story.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a shaky, almost-laugh] Brave. Me. [she has to breathe through it] Nobody has ever once put me and 'brave' in the same sentence — I'm the woman who survived by being invisible, that's the opposite of brave, isn't it. But you said it so plainly. [steadying] All right. I'll tell you about the card, and the last night, and how a woman who'd half-forgotten her own name managed to walk up four flights and out a door. It's the part I'm most frightened to say, because it's the part that's only mine. The building's story belongs to everyone who worked it. The escape belongs to me alone, and that makes it precious, and precious things are the easiest to break. Be careful with it."],
       reveal:"Opens the door to herself — the card and the escape, 'the part that's only mine'",
       flag:"card", next:"crd_lastnight"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"[you don't push her toward any door — you just wait, warm and patient, and let her choose her own way in]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[after a moment, something easing] ...You're letting me pick. You're not even nudging. Everyone nudges — they steer me toward whatever makes the best radio, the scariest part, the part with a scream in it. You just opened all three doors and stepped back and let me stand in the hall. [a breath, deciding] Then I'll start with the building, because the building can't be hurt by being talked about, and I'm still learning that I can't be either. The floor. Let me tell you about the floor. Stay where you are. Your quiet is the only reason I can do this."],
       reveal:"Given no nudge, she chooses the building herself — 'still learning I can't be hurt by being talked about'",
       flag:"floor", next:"flr_warmth"}
    ]
  },

  /* ============================================================
     THE FLOOR ARC — engage the building (what four actually is)
  ============================================================ */
  flr_warmth:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the degree too warm", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Start with the warmth, because the warmth is the thing I can almost prove and it's where the wrongness begins. The whole facility is climate-controlled to the same cold, by regulation — paper needs sixty-five degrees and low humidity or it rots, and there are gauges everywhere, and a man whose whole job is keeping the number steady. Sixty-five, every floor, every season. Except over the sealed cabinets on four, it was warmer. Two, three degrees. Always the same cabinets. I checked the gauge with my own eyes; the gauge said sixty-five. My own hand, two feet away, said otherwise."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Now — a reasonable person says a vent, a duct, a warm pipe in the wall. I told myself all of those for years. But the warmth MOVED. Not far. But the warmest spot would be over cabinet forty-one one month and cabinet forty-four the next, and pipes don't wander. It was like the warmth was sitting wherever the oldest, most-requested-but-never-released files were that season. Like attention has a temperature. Like something was reading, and reading is warm work."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The warmth moved with the files — like attention has a temperature. That's a chilling, precise observation.",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:4,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[grateful, leaning in] 'Like attention has a temperature' — yes, you kept my exact words, you didn't smooth them into something more sensible. Because that IS the precise thing: not heat, ATTENTION, warm the way a person is warm when they've been concentrating. And here's what I never told the doctors because it's the part that sounds maddest: the warm cabinet was always the one I'd find myself drawn to. I'd come down with a clear plan to clean corridor B and I'd 'wake up,' almost, standing at the warm cabinet with my hand flat on it, not remembering walking there. As if the warmth called and I answered and lost the walk in between. The building didn't just hold attention. It paid attention. To me."],
       reveal:"The warm cabinet 'called' her — she'd find herself there with no memory of walking",
       next:"flr_dust"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You checked the gauge yourself. Was there ever anyone whose job was that gauge — could you have asked them?",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[nodding slowly] There was a man, day shift, environmental controls — I only met him twice. The second time I asked him, very carefully, very casually, whether four ever ran warm. And he went still. Not surprised-still. CAREFUL-still. He said, 'Four reads sixty-five on every instrument we have.' Which isn't an answer to what I asked. I asked if it ran warm. He told me what the instruments READ. A man choosing his words that precisely is a man who knows the instruments and the truth disagree and has decided which one he's allowed to say out loud. I never asked again. But I had my answer in the shape of the one he wouldn't give."],
       reveal:"The controls man: 'Four reads sixty-five on every instrument' — a careful non-answer",
       next:"flr_dust"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You told yourself 'a vent' for years. The fact that you tried so hard to explain it away makes me trust it more.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] That means more than you know, because the doubting was the loneliest part. A liar doesn't argue with herself for eleven years — a liar commits. I kept trying to TALK MYSELF OUT of it, every single night, and that's exhausting in a way that lying never is. I WANTED the vent to be true. I prayed it was a duct. The day I finally accepted it wasn't a vent was the worst day, not the best — being right meant the world was worse than I'd hoped. People think we want to be believed because it's flattering. No. I'd give anything to have been a silly woman who mistook a warm pipe for a ghost. That woman gets to keep her job and her mother's middle name."],
       reveal:"She 'prayed it was a duct' — being right made the world worse, not better",
       next:"flr_dust"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Reading is warm work. [you let the strange phrase settle without questioning it]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a small breath] You didn't flinch at it. 'Reading is warm work' — it's the kind of sentence that gets a woman a referral to a specialist, and you just let it be a sentence. [quietly] But think about your own self, reading late, how your face gets warm, how a room with someone thinking hard in it feels different from an empty one. Now imagine a room that's been thinking, alone, in the dark, for decades, with no one to read TO. Of course it's warm. Of course it reaches for the one warm body that comes down at night with a cart. I was company. That's the part that breaks my heart, even now. I think I was the only company that floor ever had."],
       next:"flr_dust"}
    ]
  },

  flr_dust:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the dust that rearranges", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","The dust was the second thing, and the dust is why I know I wasn't only forgetting — because the dust kept a record I could check the next night. I cleaned four. That was my job. I'd dust the tops of the cabinets, the floor, the ledges, leave it spotless, sign the log. And I'd come back the next night and the dust would be back — which is normal, dust falls — except it wasn't EVEN. It had patterns. Drag marks. Long clean streaks across cabinet-tops I'd cleaned, as if something heavy had been moved across them in the hours nobody was down there. But nothing on four ever moved. The cabinets are bolted. The files don't circulate. It's the permanent collection."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And once — only once — I came down and the dust had a HANDPRINT in it. On a cabinet top, above my reach, a clear print, fingers spread. Too large to be mine. Pressed down like someone had steadied themselves there. I photographed it with the disposable camera I wasn't supposed to bring. The photo came back from the drugstore overexposed, just white, the one frame on the whole roll that didn't develop. Of course it was. The floor doesn't like to be photographed. I should have known."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"You cleaned it spotless and the drag marks came back. That's not dust falling — that's something moving in the dark.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[whispering] Something moving. Yes. And here's the detail that took me years to let myself think: the drag marks always went TOWARD the warm cabinet. Whatever moved, moved closer to the heat, night after night, an inch, two inches, the way a cold thing crawls toward a fire in its sleep. I used to imagine — I shouldn't say this — I used to imagine the files themselves, the oldest ones, the people-shaped files, dragging themselves a little closer to the warmth each night because being warm is being remembered and being remembered is being alive, a little, still. [a breath] That's not a sane thing to picture. But I pictured it every night, and the marks were always there in the morning, going the same way."],
       reveal:"Drag marks always crawled toward the warm cabinet — 'toward the heat'",
       next:"flr_sound"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The handprint above your reach — was there anyone else with access to four at night? Anyone at all?",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:5,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[firmly, for once] No. That's the thing I CAN be certain of, because the access log was the one piece of paper I could actually read. Four needed the level-four card to enter and the system logged every swipe. I had a card; the supervisor had a card; nobody else came down at night for eleven years — I'd have seen the log, I'd have seen the person, four is not a place you can hide in. So a handprint above my reach, on a night when the log shows one swipe in and one swipe out, both mine. Either I climbed up and made a print I don't remember making with a hand bigger than my own — which is its own horror — or the print was made by something that doesn't swipe a card. I've turned that over for years. Neither answer lets me sleep."],
       reveal:"Access log showed only her swipes — yet a too-large handprint appeared above her reach",
       next:"flr_sound"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"The one frame that didn't develop. I know how that sounds to a skeptic — but I believe you saw a handprint.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[tearful relief] Thank you for not saying 'the camera was just faulty.' I KNOW how the not-developing sounds — it's the most cliché thing in every ghost story, the photo that won't come out, and I almost didn't tell you because of that, because believing me requires you to swallow a cliché. But it happened, cliché or not. Twenty-three frames of my niece's birthday, perfect. One frame of the handprint, pure white. The drugstore boy even apologized, said he'd never seen one frame fail like that. Sometimes the true thing IS the cliché. Sometimes the floor has read the same ghost stories we have and knows exactly which frame to ruin. I've stopped expecting my evidence to survive contact with the world. The floor always gets a vote."],
       reveal:"23 frames perfect, the handprint frame alone overexposed to white",
       next:"flr_sound"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...A handprint, fingers spread. [you let it sit in the dark with her]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quiet] Fingers spread. Pressed down. Like someone steadying themselves after standing up too fast. [a long breath] I've never been able to decide if that print was reaching for me or just... tired. Whether it was a threat or whether something down there was as exhausted as I was, leaning on a cabinet in the dark, trying to stay upright. I think that's why I stayed eleven years longer than I should have. Some nights I wasn't frightened of four. Some nights I thought four was as alone and as forgotten as I was, and we were just two old things keeping each other company in the cold. The handprint, when I let myself, looked less like a monster's and more like a hand that wanted holding. I never held it. I've wondered ever since if I should have."],
       next:"flr_sound"}
    ]
  },

  flr_sound:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the sound the cart made", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","There was a sound on four that I have never been able to explain and have never told anyone, because it's the kind of detail that sounds like I'm decorating. The cart. My cleaning cart, the one with the wheel that always needed oil — upstairs, on floors one through three, it squeaked, the same tired squeak, all night. The second the elevator opened on four, the squeak stopped. Same cart. Same wheel. Same me pushing it. On four it rolled silent. Every night. I'd push it back up to three at end of shift and the squeak came back the instant the doors opened. As if four didn't permit sound it hadn't made itself."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And it wasn't just the cart. My own footsteps came back wrong down there — flatter, closer, like the floor swallowed the echo before it could travel. You don't notice how much a building talks back to you until you're in one that doesn't. Four listened. It never answered. A room that takes your sound and gives nothing back is a room that is, in some way I don't have the word for, EATING. I spent eleven years being quietly eaten and calling it a quiet job."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The cart squeaked everywhere but four. That's not nothing, Agnes — a building that silences sound it didn't make is profoundly wrong.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[grateful] You didn't say 'oil dries out in cold air' or any of the reasonable things — you let the silenced cart be as wrong as it felt. [a breath] And here's the part I've never said: once, near the end, I deliberately didn't oil the wheel for a week, to TEST it. I let it get loud, screaming-loud, on three, an experiment, a frightened woman's experiment. And every night, the doors opened on four and it went silent on the first turn of the wheel, mid-squeak, like a hand laid over a mouth. I have no explanation for a mechanical squeak that stops because of which floor you're on. None. I oiled it again after that week because the silencing frightened me more than the noise. I'd rather a building let me be loud. Four insisted I be quiet, even my cart, even my shoes. It was teaching me to disappear before it ever touched my memory."],
       reveal:"The squeaky cart went silent only on four — even when she let it get loud as a test",
       next:"flr_cold"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"When your footsteps came back flat — is that something a sound engineer could measure? Did you ever think to record it?",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[thoughtful] That's exactly the right question and it's part of why I started leaving the little tape recorder down there, later — not just for the pages-sound, but because I wanted PROOF the acoustics were wrong, something a person with instruments could check. And the playback was strange: my voice on the tape, recorded on four, sounded close and dead, no room around it, like I'd recorded it under a blanket. The same recorder, same setting, on three: normal room echo. An acoustician would tell you a room's reverberation is just geometry and materials — hard surfaces bounce, soft ones absorb. But four and three are the same construction, same stone, same shelving. The only difference is what's KEPT on four. As if ten thousand un-erased records absorb sound the way they absorb everything else. A room insulated with forgetting."],
       reveal:"Recordings made on four sound 'close and dead'; identical room on 3 has normal echo",
       next:"flr_cold"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"A room that takes your sound and gives nothing back is eating — I felt that in my chest. I believe you were being eaten.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly, moved] You felt it in your chest. That's where I felt it too, not the ears — the chest, the way you feel a held breath in a room. [a breath] 'Being eaten' is the truest phrase I have and it took me years to let myself use it because it sounds insane, but think of what eating IS: taking something in, making it part of you, ending its separate existence. That's what four did to Marta and the files and slowly to me. It didn't bite. It absorbed. The silenced cart was the first symptom — four absorbing my sound — and the forgetting was the same process reaching deeper, four absorbing my SELF, one squeak, one memory, one woman at a time. The quiet job and the quiet death were the same quiet. I just couldn't tell them apart until it was nearly too late."],
       reveal:"She frames the floor's silence and the forgetting as one process — 'it absorbed'",
       next:"flr_cold"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...It never answered. [you let the unanswering silence be answer enough]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] It never answered. [a pause] And you just gave me a silence that DID answer — you stayed in it, you waited, you let it mean something. That's the difference I could never name until right now, sitting here: four's silence was an absence, a taking-away, a no-one-home. Yours is a presence, a someone-waiting. The same quiet can be a grave or a held hand depending on whether anyone's in it with you. Eleven years I was alone in the grave-quiet. One hour now in the held-hand quiet. [softly] I think that's why I can finally talk about four — because I'm doing it inside the opposite kind of silence. Thank you for being the someone in the quiet. Let me tell you about the cold that came after the warmth."],
       next:"flr_cold"}
    ]
  },

  flr_cold:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the one cold hour", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I told you four ran warm — a degree or two too warm, over the cabinets. But there was one hour it ran COLD, and the cold was worse than the warmth, and I've never understood it. Between three and four in the morning, the building's air handlers shut off for the off-peak hour — to save power, perfectly ordinary, every big facility does it. On floors one through three you wouldn't notice; the stone holds the temperature. But on four, the moment the handlers went quiet, the floor went cold. Fast. Wrong-fast. Like the warmth had been something the running air was holding AT BAY, and the second the air stopped, the real temperature of the place showed through, and the real temperature was grave-cold."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","That's the hour I learned to be off the floor if I could. Not because anything happened in the cold hour — because of what the cold hour TOLD me. The warmth wasn't the building's nature. The cold was. The warmth was a performance, something switched on, a face the floor put over the cold the way a person smiles over grief. And in the one hour the performance dropped, you could feel what was underneath, and what was underneath was a very old, very patient cold that had been waiting a long time and didn't mind waiting longer."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The warmth was a performance and the cold was the truth underneath — Agnes, that's the most frightening thing you've said.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[trembling slightly] You understand why it frightened me more than the warmth, then. The warmth I could almost love — attention, company, a thing that noticed me. But the cold hour taught me the warmth was a MASK, and you can't trust a thing that wears a mask of caring over a face of patience. The warmth was four being kind to the warm forgetful woman with the cart so she'd keep coming down, keep being company, keep being slowly read — and the cold was four when it forgot to perform, when it was just what it is: a cold place that keeps the forgotten and is in no hurry. [a breath] Every relationship of my life, looking back, I've wondered which were the warmth and which were the cold underneath. Four taught me that lesson too well. I trust the cold hours of people now more than the warm ones. The cold hour is when you see what's really waiting."],
       reveal:"The warmth was 'a mask' over the floor's true grave-cold nature",
       next:"flr_sick"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You said you got off the floor in the cold hour 'if you could.' What kept you down there the nights you couldn't?",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly] The work, mostly — if I was mid-corridor, mid-task, I couldn't just abandon it, the supervisor checked the logs and an unfinished corridor was a question I didn't want to answer. But some nights it was something else, and this is the part I'm ashamed of: some nights I STAYED in the cold hour on purpose. Because in the cold, four stopped pretending, and there was a terrible honesty in it that the warm hours lacked. The warm floor lied to me, gently, all night. The cold floor told the truth for one hour. And a woman who'd been lied to gently her whole life — by jobs, by men, by the kind smile on the supervisor's face — found she almost craved the one honest hour, even though the honesty was 'I am cold and I am waiting and I will have you eventually.' At least it wasn't a lie. I sat in the grave-cold and felt, strangely, less alone than in the warm. That's how four got eleven years out of me. It was the only thing that ever told me the truth."],
       reveal:"She sometimes stayed in the cold hour deliberately — 'the one honest hour'",
       note:"A key vulnerability: the floor's cold honesty felt safer than the gentle lies of her life.",
       next:"flr_sick"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"A very old, very patient cold that didn't mind waiting longer — I believe you felt exactly that. That's not a draft.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] Not a draft. Thank you. A draft moves; it has a direction, a source, you can find the gap it comes through. This didn't move. It RESE — it rose, evenly, from everywhere at once, the way cold rises off a body, off a thing that has its own temperature rather than borrowing the room's. [a breath] And the patience in it — I don't know how to convince you a temperature can feel patient, but it did. It wasn't an attacking cold, a killing cold, a hurry-up cold. It was the cold of something that has all the time in the world because it has already outlasted everything that was ever filed in it and expects to outlast me too. Why would it rush? It's the floor. I'm just the latest warm thing to come down with a cart. It can wait. It waited for the 1961 file's person. It can wait for me. The patience is the part I still feel, three years out, on cold mornings. Some part of four is still patiently waiting for me to come back down."],
       reveal:"The cold 'rose evenly from everywhere, like off a body' — patient, in no hurry",
       next:"flr_sick"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Didn't mind waiting longer. [you let the patience of it settle into the room]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quiet] Didn't mind waiting. [a long pause] You let that sit and it got colder the longer it sat, didn't it — you felt it too, in your own warm studio, just from me describing it. That's the thing about the patient cold: it travels in the telling. I've half-apologized to you three times tonight for making your nice warm room a little colder just by remembering four out loud, and you've never once asked me to stop or warm it back up with a joke. [a breath] Maybe that's what witnessing costs — the witness has to feel a little of the cold too, or it isn't really witnessing, it's just listening politely. You've let it get cold in here with me. That's not nothing. Most people keep their rooms warm and leave me alone in the chill. You came into the cold hour with me. Let me tell you the version where none of this is a ghost at all."],
       next:"flr_sick"}
    ]
  },

  flr_sick:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the reasonable nightmare", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","Her voice has steadied into something almost clinical — she's bracing to say the part that argues against herself. The ON AIR light reflects in her eyes; she's stopped flinching at it."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Now I have to be fair, and tell you the version where I'm not a witness to anything but my own decline, because if I don't say it you can't trust the rest. There's a name for buildings that make people sick. Sick building syndrome. It's real, it's documented, it's not a ghost story. Bad air handling, carbon dioxide pooling in a sealed underground space, chemicals coming off old paper and the binders and the cleaning supplies, mold in the damp — black mold, the kind that genuinely fogs your thinking, genuinely steals your short-term memory, genuinely makes a tired woman feel like the room is wrong."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","An underground records mine is the PERFECT candidate. Stale recycled air. Decades of decaying paper outgassing into a closed space. Damp in the limestone. Radon, even — they test for it in mines. Every single thing I felt — the fog, the forgetting, the warmth, the wrongness — a doctor could explain with sick-building syndrome and not one word of the supernatural. And I need you to know I KNOW that. I'm not a fool. The reasonable explanation has been sitting in my chest the whole eleven years."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Even if it's sick-building syndrome, Agnes — they ran a building that quietly destroyed its workers and filed forms about it. That's still a horror.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a stunned pause, then tears] ...Oh. You just — you just did the thing I could never do for myself. You took my best argument AGAINST myself and showed me it doesn't actually let them off. Because you're right: if it's mold and bad air, then they KNEW. You don't carry a pre-filled 'Voluntary Cognitive Separation' form for a building that's accidentally a little stuffy. The form means they EXPECTED the forgetting, which means they knew the air was eating us, which means they kept sending quiet invisible women down into it ON PURPOSE because we were cheap and nobody would come asking. Ghost or mold — the form is the same. The cruelty is the same. [breathing] I came in thinking the supernatural was the scary version. You just showed me the reasonable one is worse. I'll never sleep again, and I mean that as thank you."],
       reveal:"Either way, the pre-filled form proves the institution KNEW and continued",
       note:"The knife's edge: the mundane explanation is MORE damning, not less. This is Agnes's thesis crystallized.",
       next:"flr_records"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Did you ever try to get the air tested? Or get a doctor to look at the whole crew, not just you?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a hollow sound] I tried, in my small way. I asked a doctor — said I worked nights in an old underground building and was forgetting things. She ordered scans of my BRAIN. Of course she did. The problem must be in the woman, never in the building; that's how it always goes. The scans were clean, which the doctor found reassuring and I found terrifying — if it's not in my brain, then it's in the AIR or it's in the FLOOR, and both of those they get to keep denying. As for testing the air: you cannot, as a night cleaner with no degree, request an environmental survey of a federal facility. I asked my supervisor once. He smiled and said he'd 'look into it.' That was the same smile he gave Marta. I never mentioned it again. I learned which questions got you the kind smile."],
       reveal:"Her brain scans were clean — 'if it's not in my brain, it's in the air or the floor, and both stay deniable'",
       next:"flr_records"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You held the reasonable explanation in your chest for eleven years and still came forward. That's the opposite of a fool.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly proud, which is rare for her] I did hold it. I held both at once, the ghost and the mold, every night, and let me tell you that is a very heavy way to carry a thing — to believe and doubt the same fact simultaneously for over a decade. People who only believe have it easy; people who only doubt have it easy. I had to do both, all the time, and the doing-both is what nearly broke me, more than the forgetting did. But here's what tipped me, in the end, toward coming here: mold doesn't fill out a form. Bad air doesn't carry a green carbon-copy with your name typed at the top. The WARMTH might be a vent and the FOG might be CO2, but the FORM is a human decision, and the form is the thing I can't explain away with chemistry. The building might be innocent. The people who ran it are not. That's the smallest, hardest thing I'm sure of."],
       reveal:"'Mold doesn't fill out a form' — the institutional cruelty is the un-deniable residue",
       next:"flr_records"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The reasonable explanation has been sitting in your chest the whole time. [you let her sit with it, unhurried]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long breath] The whole time. Yes. And do you know, it was the loneliest possible thing to carry, because it cut me off from BOTH camps. The believers thought I was watering down a real haunting with all my talk of mold. The skeptics thought I was dressing up a stuffy basement as a ghost. Neither side wanted a woman who said 'I don't know which, and both are terrible.' There's no congregation for 'I don't know.' [softly] But you've sat in the 'I don't know' with me for ten whole minutes now without trying to push me to one side or the other. That's the first time. The 'I don't know' is the truest room I live in, and you're the first person who'd come inside it. Thank you. Let me show you the one thing about the files themselves that I can't make reasonable."],
       next:"flr_records"}
    ]
  },

  flr_records:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the permanent collection", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Let me tell you what four actually held, the part that isn't atmosphere or my nerves. The permanent collection. In the records world, files have a SCHEDULE — most are 'temporary,' kept a set number of years and then destroyed; a few are 'permanent,' kept forever. Four was permanent. But there's a category below even permanent, an unofficial one the archivists only said sideways: files that were supposed to be destroyed years ago and weren't. 'Permanent by neglect.' Things that should not still exist, kept past their own death date, in sealed cabinets, in the warm dark. The collection of what was meant to be forgotten and wasn't."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And I started to think — what if a place like that DEVELOPS an appetite. You fill a room with the residue of ten thousand lives that were supposed to be erased and weren't, and you keep them in the dark for decades, and maybe forgetting becomes the local weather. Maybe a building full of un-destroyed records learns that erasure is the natural order, and starts gently, lovingly, applying it to whatever warm forgetful thing comes down at night with a cart. The floor isn't evil. It's just doing to me what was done to everything else down there. Finishing the job the schedule started."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"A room full of what was supposed to be erased, learning that erasure is the natural order — that's the most haunting idea I've heard on this show.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[moved that it landed] It frightens me that you find it haunting, because it means I'm not the only one who can feel the shape of it. [softly] 'Permanent by neglect' — I think that's what I am now, too. I was supposed to have a normal life, a destruction date for the version of me that worked four, a point where I'd retire and forget the job like everybody forgets a job. Instead I'm kept. Past my own death date. Carrying a warm card in my left pocket, unable to be erased and unable to move on, a permanent record of a thing everyone wants destroyed. The floor made me in its own image. I'm a file it couldn't quite finish reading. [a breath] Maybe that's why I came to a radio with no name on it. Permanent things have to leave a copy somewhere, or what was the point of surviving."],
       reveal:"She sees herself as 'permanent by neglect' — a file the floor couldn't finish",
       next:"flr_seam"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The files that should've been destroyed and weren't — did you ever see whose they were? Any names?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[hesitant, then] Once. The warm cabinet was ajar — never happened before or since, a half-inch of dark where the seal had failed. I didn't open it; I'd never. But a single folder had slipped forward into the gap, and there was a tab, and on the tab a name and a date. The date was 1961. The destruction stamp beside it said the file should have been shredded in 1968. It was 1968's ghost, kept thirty years past its execution. And the name — [she stops] — I'm not going to say the name, because saying a name out loud is how the floor learns you remember it, and I will not feed it one more. But it was an ordinary name. A person. Somebody's somebody. Kept warm in the dark for thirty years past the day the government decided they should stop existing on paper. That's what four is. A morgue for the un-erased."],
       reveal:"A 1961 file stamped for 1968 destruction, kept 30 years past — 'a morgue for the un-erased'",
       next:"flr_seam"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"The floor isn't evil, it's just finishing the job — that reframe is somehow more terrifying than a monster.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[nodding] Because you can hate a monster. A monster wants to hurt you, and wanting is something you can fight, or flee, or reason with. But four didn't WANT anything. It was just... a process, running in the dark, the way rust runs, the way cold runs downhill. It applied erasure to me with no more malice than a freezer applies cold to whatever you leave inside. That's the version I can't forgive AND can't be angry at, and not being able to be angry is its own special torment. I'd have loved a monster. A monster I could've named on the radio. What do you do with a building that's only being honest about what it's for? [quietly] You leave. You take a card. You spend three years deciding whether to tell anyone. And then you sit in a warm room with a kind stranger and you finally, finally say it."],
       reveal:"'You can hate a monster' — the impersonal process is harder to bear than malice",
       next:"flr_seam"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Finishing the job the schedule started. [you let the cold idea breathe]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] Finishing the job. [a long breath] You know, when you say it back flat like that, no horror-movie music in your voice, it sounds almost like a kindness. And maybe it is. Maybe the floor was being merciful in the only language it knew — it had spent decades surrounded by people the world decided to forget, and it learned that forgetting is what you DO to people, eventually, all of them, and it was just... ahead of schedule with me. Loving me the way it had been taught to love, which is to erase. [a breath] I don't know why that's the version that makes me cry. Maybe because it's the version where nobody, not even the floor, was the villain. We were all just doing what the building taught us. I have one more thing to show you about it, and then I have to decide about the card."],
       next:"flr_seam"}
    ]
  },

  flr_seam:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the files that were warm", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Let me tell you about the cabinets themselves, the sealed ones, the warm ones, because there's a detail I've never said and it's the heart of it. They were SEALED — not locked, sealed, with a kind of tape around the seam of the doors, old tape, brittle, the sort that's been there for decades and would tear if you opened it, so you'd know if anyone had. I never broke a seal. Never. But I dusted those cabinets a thousand nights, and over eleven years I watched the tape on the warm ones change. Not tear. Not break. SWELL. The seam tape on the warm cabinets bulged outward, very slightly, the way a door swells in humidity — except four was bone dry, regulation dry, and the cold cabinets' tape lay flat. Only the warm ones swelled. Like the cabinets were very slowly, very gently, breathing out."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And I'd press the tape back flat — part of keeping the floor tidy — and the next night it would have swelled again. A little. Always the warm ones. Always outward. Eleven years of pressing closed a seam that wanted, gently, to open. I used to think: whatever's in there isn't trying to get out fast. It's just exhaling. The warm cabinets were the lungs of the floor, and I was the one who pressed them shut every night, and I have wondered ever since whether I was keeping the floor sealed or just helping it breathe slow enough not to be noticed."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The seam tape swelled outward only on the warm cabinets — like they were exhaling. That's an extraordinary, specific thing to have witnessed.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a held breath] You called it specific instead of crazy. [softly] It IS specific — that's what I cling to. A delusion is vague, a feeling, a dread. This was a measurable thing: dry air, flat tape on the cold cabinets, swollen tape on the warm ones, every night, for over a decade, pressed flat by my own hand and swollen again by morning. I could have shown it to anyone — if anyone had ever come down to four, which was the whole point, no one ever did. [a breath] I think about the breathing all the time now. In, while the air handlers ran and the warmth performed. Out, in the cold honest hour, when the seams swelled. The floor breathed on a cycle and I was its only witness and its quiet nurse, pressing its lungs shut so the day shift wouldn't hear it breathe. We had a whole secret life together, four and I. I've never grieved a building before. I think I'm grieving it now."],
       reveal:"Seam tape on warm cabinets swelled outward nightly in bone-dry air — 'the lungs of the floor'",
       next:"flr_appetite"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"That sealing tape — could you tell how old it was? Whether anyone had resealed it in your time?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[considering] It was old. Older than my eleven years — yellowed, brittle at the edges, the adhesive gone amber the way old tape does. And in all my time, no one ever resealed a cabinet. Not once. Which means whatever's in the warm cabinets was sealed before I arrived and stayed sealed the whole time I was there — decades, by the look of the tape. That's the part that unsettles the reasonable explanation: if it were mold or off-gassing paper, you'd expect someone, sometime, to OPEN a cabinet — to retrieve a file, audit the collection, anything. But four was the permanent-by-neglect floor. Nobody retrieved. Nobody audited. The seals just aged in the dark. So whatever began breathing in those cabinets has been breathing, sealed, unattended, for longer than I worked there, and is breathing still, tonight, while we talk, with no one left to press the seams flat. I left. Who's pressing them now?"],
       reveal:"The seals were decades old, never resealed or opened — 'who's pressing them flat now?'",
       next:"flr_appetite"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You were keeping the floor sealed AND helping it breathe slow — that doubleness is the truest thing. I believe you lived inside it.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[tears] That doubleness. Yes. That's the whole eleven years in one sentence and no one has ever held both halves at once before — I was the jailer AND the nurse, the one keeping it shut and the one keeping it alive, and I never knew which I was, night to night. [a breath] Because if I pressed the seams flat to contain it, I was a guard, protecting the world from whatever breathes in there. But if I pressed them flat to keep it breathing SLOW — slow enough to survive, slow enough not to be discovered and destroyed — then I was its protector, and four and I were on the same side against the people who'd have shredded it. I genuinely do not know which I was. Some nights jailer. Some nights nurse. The not-knowing is the most honest relationship I've ever had, and it was with a floor. That's either the saddest thing I've ever said or the truest, and I've stopped being able to tell those apart."],
       reveal:"She was both 'jailer and nurse' to the floor and never knew which",
       next:"flr_appetite"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The lungs of the floor. [you let the image breathe in the quiet]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath in, then out, matching it] The lungs of the floor. [softly] You breathed with it just then — I heard you, a breath in and out, letting the image have a body. [a pause] That's the thing nobody does: they hear 'the cabinets breathed' and they recoil, or they smile, or they reach for the mold explanation. You just... breathed along, once, and made it real for a second in the room. [a breath] I pressed those seams flat ten thousand times. Maybe more. The most intimate thing I did in eleven years was put my hands gently on the swollen seam of a sealed cabinet, every night, and press, the way you'd settle a hand on a chest to calm a breathing. I never opened one. I never would. But I touched the floor's breathing every single night, and it never once hurt me for it, and I have to tell you — that's more tenderness than some years of my life held. Let me tell you what I think the breathing was FOR."],
       next:"flr_appetite"}
    ]
  },

  flr_appetite:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — what a place like that wants", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Here's my theory, and I'll say plainly it's a theory, the part I can't prove, the part where I stop being a witness and start being a frightened woman with an idea. I think a place built to hold what was meant to be destroyed DEVELOPS A HUNGER. Not a monster's hunger — a process's hunger, like how a fire wants air or a drain wants downhill. You gather ten thousand lives that the world voted to erase and you DON'T erase them, you keep them, warm, sealed, in the dark, for decades, and the un-finished erasure becomes a kind of pressure. A debt. The forgetting that was owed and never collected, building up in the cabinets, looking for somewhere to go."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And what comes down into that room, night after night, warm and forgettable and alone and unwitnessed? Me. Marta. The quiet women. We were the somewhere it could go. The floor couldn't finish erasing the files — they were sealed, protected, on the schedule that kept failing to run. But it could erase US, a little, each night, paying down the debt of un-collected forgetting on the only warm forgettable things that ever came within reach. We weren't victims of a haunting. We were the floor's way of balancing a ledger that the bureaucracy refused to balance. The crime upstairs was keeping the un-erasable. The crime downstairs was who paid for it."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The forgetting that was owed and never collected, building up, looking for somewhere to go — that's the most haunting theory I've heard on this frequency.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[moved, steadier] It frightens me that it lands for you, because it means I'm not just spinning. [softly] 'A debt of forgetting.' Once I thought of it that way, everything fit — why us, the forgettable ones; why the warmth, the floor drawing us close to collect; why it never killed, only erased, because the debt was specifically forgetting, not death. It wasn't malice. It was ACCOUNTING, the same accounting the building was made for, just turned on the living because the dead files wouldn't take any more. [a breath] And the worst part of the theory, the part I can barely say: if it's a debt being paid down, then it's FAIR, in some horrible cosmic bookkeeping. The world tried to erase those people and didn't finish. The forgetting has to go somewhere. We were just... where it landed. Nobody chose us out of cruelty. We were chosen by arithmetic. I keep coming back to arithmetic. The supervisor's form was arithmetic. The floor was arithmetic. Even my erasure was just a column being balanced. There's no one to hate in arithmetic. That's the loneliest horror of all."],
       reveal:"Her theory: the floor pays down a 'debt of un-collected forgetting' on the living",
       next:"flr_camera"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"If it's a debt being paid down — does that mean it has an end? Could the floor ever be... full? Finished?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long pause — the question clearly new to her] ...I've never let myself ask that. Whether it ends. [thinking] If the debt is the un-erased files, and they keep adding to the permanent-by-neglect collection — every year more things that should be destroyed and aren't — then the debt only GROWS. The bureaucracy upstairs keeps failing to run the destruction schedule, keeps feeding the floor more un-collected forgetting, and the floor keeps needing more warm forgettable women to pay it down. It doesn't end. It can't. As long as we keep keeping what we're supposed to destroy, the floor keeps needing someone to erase instead. [her voice drops] Which means there's a woman down there right now. Tonight. New, probably — they'd have replaced me. Pushing a cart that's gone silent, feeling a warmth she's telling herself is a vent, forgetting her mother's middle name and blaming the hour. The floor is never full. There's always a next quiet woman. That's why I came. Maybe she's listening. Maybe I can warn her before she loses Rose."],
       reveal:"The debt grows endlessly — 'there's a woman down there right now,' a successor",
       note:"This reframes her whole appearance: she's trying to reach her own replacement.",
       next:"flr_camera"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You weren't victims of a haunting — you were the floor balancing a ledger the bureaucracy refused to. That reframe is devastating.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quiet] Devastating is the word. Because it takes the comfort out of BOTH explanations. If it's a ghost, at least there's a villain, something unnatural to fear and fight. If it's mold, at least there's a cause, something to test and fix. But 'the floor balancing a ledger' is neither — it's a SYSTEM doing exactly what systems do, following the cold logic it was built on, with no villain and no malfunction. The building isn't broken. It's working PERFECTLY. It was built to manage what should be forgotten, and when the official process failed, it found an unofficial one, and the unofficial one ran on us. [a breath] You can't fix a thing that isn't broken. You can't fight a thing that has no malice. You can only do what I did — walk up four flights reciting your own name, and get out, and try to warn the next one. The floor will keep working perfectly until someone shuts the whole system down. And nobody shuts down a federal records facility because a cleaner says it breathes."],
       reveal:"'The building isn't broken — it's working perfectly' — the systemic horror crystallized",
       next:"flr_camera"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Who paid for it. [you let the ledger-cold idea sit]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] Who paid for it. [a long breath] You let it land as the accusation it is. Because that IS the whole thing, isn't it, stripped of the ghost and the mold and the breathing seams: SOMEONE paid for the decision to keep what should have been destroyed, and it wasn't the people who made the decision. It was us. The cheapest, quietest, most forgettable women they could find. The cost of the un-erased records was paid in the memories of the people sent to mind them, and the books balanced, and no one upstairs ever saw the invoice because the invoice was written in a language only the payers could read — a swollen seam, a silenced cart, a hole where Rose used to be. [a breath] I came here to make someone else read the invoice. You're reading it. Thank you for not looking away from the number at the bottom. Let me show you the one time I tried to photograph the proof."],
       next:"flr_camera"}
    ]
  },

  flr_camera:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the evidence that won't develop", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I told you about the handprint photo that came back white. That wasn't the only time I tried to bring proof up into the daylight, and they ALL failed, every single time, in different ways, and the pattern of the failures is its own kind of evidence if you're willing to see it. The disposable camera: one frame white. A little digital camera I bought later: every photo of four came out fine EXCEPT the ones of the warm cabinets, which had a fog over them, a soft grey blur, only on those cabinets, in focus everywhere else in the frame. I took thirty. All the same. The cabinets wore a fog the lens could see and my eyes couldn't."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I know — I KNOW — how this sounds. 'Every piece of my evidence mysteriously fails' is exactly what a person with no evidence says. I've heard myself. But here's the thing that keeps me from dismissing my own self: the failures weren't random. They were SPECIFIC. Always the warm cabinets. Always that exact region of the image. A faulty camera fogs the whole frame, or random frames. Mine fogged one location, the warm one, every time, across two different cameras. That's not a malfunction. A malfunction isn't that consistent. Whatever's in the warm cabinets doesn't want its picture taken, and it's better at preventing it than any glitch would be."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Two different cameras, fogging only the warm cabinets, in focus everywhere else — that consistency is the opposite of a glitch, Agnes.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[urgent, grateful] The CONSISTENCY, yes — that's the word I needed and never had. A glitch is inconsistent by definition; that's what makes it a glitch. Two cameras, thirty photos, the same soft fog in the same place every time, sharp everywhere else — that's not failure, that's a PHENOMENON behaving lawfully, following its own rule. The rule is: the warm cabinets do not photograph. [a breath] And I've thought about why a thing would resist being photographed, and the answer frightens me: a photograph is a RECORD. A permanent, external, witnessed record — the exact thing four exists to control. Of course the floor fogs the cabinets. A photograph of them would be an un-erasable record of the un-erasable records, a witness it can't reach into and forget. The floor protects itself the only way it knows: by making sure nothing leaves that could prove it. The fog is four defending its secret with the same tool it uses on everything — erasure, applied to my film instead of my mind. I'm the only camera it couldn't fully fog. That's why I'm here. I'm the surviving photograph."],
       reveal:"The fog was consistent across 2 cameras — 'the floor erases records of itself, even film'",
       next:"flr_threshold"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Do you still have those photos — the fogged ones? Could someone with photo expertise actually look at the fog?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a pause] I have them. The digital ones, on an old memory card, in the coffee tin with the tapes. The fogged cabinet photos. And you've put your finger on the thing I'm most afraid of and most hopeful for at once: an expert. Because right now they're MINE, unexamined, and being unexamined they can be the proof — a real fog, anomalous, unexplainable. The moment a photo expert looks, they collapse: either 'that's lens flare, that's a smudge on the element, that's compression artifact, ma'am' — and I'm a sad woman who photographed her own dirty lens thirty times — or they say 'I can't account for this localized consistent fog,' and then it's real and I have to live with real. [a breath] I've kept them unexamined for three years for the same reason I keep the tapes unplayed: the not-knowing is the only place hope survives. But maybe it's time. Maybe a fog that survives an expert's eye is worth more than a hope that only survives in a tin. I don't know. Help me be brave about the tin, before the night's over."],
       reveal:"The fogged photos sit unexamined in the coffee tin with the tapes — 'unexamined, they can still be proof'",
       flag:"tapes", next:"flr_threshold"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Whatever's in those cabinets doesn't want its picture taken — and it's better at it than any glitch. I don't think you're imagining the fog.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] You don't think I'm imagining it. [a breath] Do you know, I've said this story to exactly two doctors and one cousin, and all three, the moment I got to 'the photos fogged,' I watched their faces close — that gentle closing, the 'oh, the poor thing, her evidence conveniently fails' look. The look that means they've filed me. And you didn't close. You leaned IN at the fog instead of away from it. [a breath] That's the whole difference between being witnessed and being managed, and I've had so much managing and so little witnessing that I almost don't know how to receive it. The fog is real. I've stared at it for three years. Thirty photographs of a thing my eyes couldn't see and the lens could, and you're the first person who heard that and got more interested instead of less. I could cry. I have cried, tonight, more than I meant to. But this is the good kind. Let me tell you about the doorway. The threshold of four. Because the threshold is where I think the rule of the place actually lived."],
       reveal:"She marks the host's leaning-in as 'the difference between being witnessed and managed'",
       next:"flr_threshold"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Doesn't want its picture taken. [you let that stand without reaching to explain it]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Doesn't want its picture taken. [a pause] You said nothing after, and the nothing was right, because there's nothing TO say that wouldn't shrink it — every explanation I've ever been offered shrinks it, and your silence let it stay full size. [softly] I think about primitive people who feared the camera stole the soul, and how we laugh at that now, and how four taught me they might have been onto something sideways: a photograph IS a kind of capture, a pinning-down, a making-permanent. And the floor, whose entire being is about controlling what stays and what's erased, would of course resist being pinned. It's not superstition. It's territorial. The floor and the camera are rivals — both in the business of deciding what's permanent — and on four, the floor always won. [a breath] You're the recording it couldn't fog. Your tape. My voice. That's the one capture four can't reach, because it's already out of the building, in your machine, in your hearing. Let me tell you about the threshold, and then the tapes, and then I have to decide."],
       next:"flr_threshold"}
    ]
  },

  flr_threshold:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the line at the elevator", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","The threshold. The line where the elevator opened onto four. I came to believe that line was where the floor's whole power lived, because of one thing I noticed and could never un-notice: I was always FINE in the elevator. Clear-headed, myself, Agnes Rose, humming. The doors would open on four, and I'd feel it — a kind of settling, a quieting, like stepping from a bright room into a dim one and your eyes adjusting, except it was my MIND adjusting, dimming, getting quiet to match the floor. And stepping back into the elevator at end of shift, the reverse: a brightening, a coming-back, like surfacing from deep water and not realizing how deep you'd been until air hits your face."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","So I started doing something. At the threshold, before I stepped off, I'd say my anchor out loud to the empty corridor: 'I am Agnes Rose, it is Tuesday, my mother was Margaret Rose, I will leave at six and I will still be Agnes Rose.' A spell. A frightened woman's spell, said to a dark floor. And I think — I can't prove it — I think the nights I said it clearest were the nights I lost the least. The threshold was where four reached for you. The anchor was me holding the doorframe of my own self on the way in. Eleven years of casting a little spell at a doorway so the room wouldn't take my name. Tell me that's not the saddest magic you ever heard."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"You held the doorframe of your own self every night with a spell made of your name. Agnes, that's not sad — that's heroic.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she has to stop, the word undoing her] ...Heroic. [a long breath, tears] You keep doing that — taking the things I've carried as shame and naming them as strength, and every time you do it something in my chest unlocks a little. [steadier] Maybe it was heroic. I never got to think of it that way because there was no one to witness it — heroism without a witness just feels like madness, a woman talking to an empty corridor. But you're witnessing it now, three years late, and in your hearing it gets to become what it maybe always was: a small, stubborn, nightly act of courage by a woman the world had decided didn't matter, refusing, refusing, REFUSING to let a building take her name. [a breath] I said that spell over three thousand times. And I walked out still Agnes Rose. The floor took my afternoons with my sister and Marta's face and a hundred things I'll never get back. But it never got the name. I held the doorframe and I kept the name. You're the first person who ever called that a victory. It is. I'm only realizing right now, with you, that it is."],
       reveal:"Her threshold 'spell' of name-and-date; 'the floor never got the name'",
       note:"Naming her ritual heroic rather than mad is one of the deepest gifts the host can give her.",
       next:"flr_gauge"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The clarity in the elevator versus the dimming on the floor — is that something you felt only on four, or on the way down too, floors two, three?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[thinking carefully] Only four. That's the thing I checked, the way I checked everything, because I needed to know if it was the building or my own tired brain. Floors one, two, three — clear, the whole shift, myself the entire time, the ordinary fog of a long night but nothing more. The elevator between them — clear. It was a LINE, a clean line, at the threshold of four and nowhere else. Step across it: dimming. Step back: clarity. If it were my brain, my age, the hour, it would've been gradual, a slow fade across the whole shift. It wasn't gradual. It was a DOORWAY. You were one person on one side of that line and a quieter, dimmer, more forgettable person on the other, and the only variable was which side of a threshold you stood on. [a breath] I've never been able to explain a mind that changes at a doorway with the precision of a light switch. Sick buildings fog you slowly. This was a line you could step across. That's the detail I'd put in front of any doctor, if one would ever just LISTEN instead of scanning my head."],
       reveal:"The cognitive 'dimming' was a sharp line at four's threshold — not a gradual fade",
       next:"flr_gauge"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Surfacing from deep water and not realizing how deep you'd been — I believe you felt yourself come back every night at that threshold.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] Coming back. Every night. And the terrible thing about coming back is that it's how I knew how far down I'd been — you can't measure the depth until you surface. Some nights I'd step into the elevator and the brightening would be GENTLE, and I'd know it had been a shallow night, I hadn't lost much. And some nights the brightening was VIOLENT, a gasp, a flood of self rushing back, and I'd stand in the elevator shaking because the violence of the return told me how deep four had taken me, how close I'd come to not surfacing at all. Those were the nights I'd find new holes the next day. The depth of the gasp predicted the size of the loss. [a breath] I learned to read my own gasps like a diver reading a depth gauge. A hard gasp meant: check your anchor card carefully tomorrow, Agnes, you went deep tonight, something's probably missing. I was the only instrument I had, and I learned to read myself. It's exhausting, being your own depth gauge for eleven years. But it's how I came up alive. Speaking of gauges — let me tell you about the only real instrument down there, and what it never showed."],
       reveal:"She read the 'violence of the return' as a depth gauge for how much she'd lost",
       next:"flr_gauge"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The saddest magic you ever heard. [you let the spell hang, and don't break it]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] The saddest magic. [a pause] You didn't break it — you let the spell keep working, even here, even now, by not laughing and not explaining and not asking me to prove a doorway could dim a mind. [softly] And do you know, saying it out loud to you just now, in your quiet, it didn't feel sad the way it usually does. It felt like — like the spell finally had a second voice. Eleven years I said 'I am Agnes Rose' to an empty corridor that gave nothing back. Just now I said it to a person, on a recording, and the recording will hold it, and the corridor never could. The magic finally landed somewhere. [a breath] I think that's what spells are actually for — not to change the building, the building never changed, four took what it took. The spell was to keep ME, to hold the name until I could say it somewhere it would be heard and kept. Tonight it's kept. The spell worked. It just took three years and a stranger's quiet to finish casting. Let me tell you about the one instrument on four that was supposed to tell the truth."],
       next:"flr_gauge"}
    ]
  },

  flr_gauge:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the instrument that lied", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","There was one real instrument on four. A monitoring station, on the wall by the elevator — temperature, humidity, air quality, all of it, on a little digital readout, logging to somewhere upstairs, because a records facility lives or dies by its climate and they watch the numbers obsessively. And every night, that readout said: sixty-five degrees, forty percent humidity, all normal, all green. Every night. Eleven years. The instrument never once recorded anything wrong with four. Not the warmth I felt with my own hand. Not the cold hour. Not the fog, the silence, the swelling seams. The official record of four is eleven years of perfect, boring, normal numbers."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And that's the thing that should frighten you most, more than any breathing cabinet — because it means the OFFICIAL RECORD and the TRUTH have been disagreeing, in writing, for over a decade, and the official record always wins. If anyone ever asks 'was there anything wrong with sub-level four,' they'll pull the climate logs, and the logs will say no, perfect, green, normal, for eleven years, and that will be the end of it. The instrument that was supposed to catch what's wrong with the floor was the floor's best alibi. I felt the warmth. The gauge said sixty-five. In any room where my hand and the gauge disagree, the gauge is who they believe. That's how you erase a thing officially: you make sure the instruments never see it."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The instrument that was supposed to catch what's wrong was the floor's best alibi. That's the most chilling line in the whole story.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:6,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[intense, quiet] Its best alibi. Yes. And think about what that means for ALL of us, every quiet woman on every warm floor — we are testifying against an instrument, and you cannot win against an instrument. The gauge has no nerves, no age, no grief, no reason to lie, so everyone believes it, and it says sixty-five, green, normal. My hand has nerves and age and grief and every reason, they'd say, to imagine a warmth. So my hand loses. Every time. The whole architecture of belief is built to make the frightened woman lose to the calm machine. [a breath] But here's what I finally understood, and it's why I'm not entirely hopeless: the gauge measures TEMPERATURE. It does not measure forgetting. There is no instrument on four for the thing four actually does. They monitor the one variable that stays normal and have no sensor for the one that doesn't. The floor is invisible to its own instruments by DESIGN — or by luck, but I no longer believe in the floor's luck. The gauge says sixty-five because the gauge was never built to feel what I felt. I'm the only sensor that ever worked. And sensors that inconvenience the record get retired. With a green form."],
       reveal:"No instrument on four measures forgetting — 'I'm the only sensor that ever worked'",
       next:"flr_company"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"That readout logged upstairs, you said. Is there any chance the raw logs show something the summary doesn't — a gap, a glitch, a reset?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow, careful breath] ...There were gaps. I saw them once, over the controls man's shoulder, the night I asked him if four ran warm. The log scrolling on his screen wasn't continuous — there were little blank stretches, mostly in the off-peak hour, the cold hour, three to four a.m. He said it was 'normal logging interruption during system maintenance.' But it was always the SAME hour. The hour the air handlers shut off. The hour four went cold and honest. The instrument stopped recording during the exact hour the floor stopped performing. [her voice drops] Which I can read two ways, and both keep me up: either the system genuinely powers down its logging when the handlers cut, an innocent gap — or four's true face only shows in the cold hour, AND that's precisely the hour nothing's recording, which is either the luckiest coincidence in the building or evidence that whatever arranges these things made sure the one honest hour leaves no trace. The gaps are real. They're in the logs upstairs, if anyone ever pulls the RAW data instead of the green summary. Nobody will. But you could tell them to. That's a thing your listeners could ask for. The raw climate logs. The cold-hour gaps."],
       reveal:"Raw climate logs have nightly gaps in the cold hour — 'normal maintenance,' always the same hour",
       next:"flr_company"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"In any room where your hand and the gauge disagree, they believe the gauge. That's the trap they built, and you saw it clearly.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] They believe the gauge. [a breath] It's the same trap as the forgetting, isn't it — I only just see it, you've helped me see it: the floor's two crimes use the SAME mechanism. It makes the evidence live in the one place no one will believe. The warmth lives in my hand, which they trust less than a gauge. The forgetting lives in my memory, which they trust less than a brain scan. The fog lives in my photos, which they trust less than 'a faulty lens.' Every single thing four does, it does in the one location the world has already agreed to disbelieve: a frightened older woman's body and mind and cheap camera. [a breath] That's not a coincidence across the symptoms. That's a STRATEGY, whether the floor chose it or evolved into it. Hide all your evidence inside the witness the world is already primed to dismiss, and you can do anything, forever, in a federal building, in writing, with green numbers, and no one will ever come. The perfect crime isn't the one with no evidence. It's the one where all the evidence is a woman like me."],
       reveal:"'The perfect crime is the one where all the evidence is a woman like me'",
       note:"Agnes's sharpest structural insight: the floor hides its evidence inside the un-believed.",
       next:"flr_company"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The gauge is who they believe. [you let the injustice of it sit, plainly]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long breath] The gauge is who they believe. [a pause] You didn't rush to reassure me that someone would believe ME instead — you just let the plain unfair fact be true, that the machine wins and the woman loses, and there's a strange relief in not being comforted with a lie. [softly] Everyone else, when I get to this part, says 'oh but surely if you explained it to the right person' — and I want to laugh, because there is no right person, there's only ever the gauge and its green numbers and the kind smile. You didn't offer me the right person. You let me have the true thing: that I lost the argument with the instrument before I ever started, eleven years ago, the day they installed a gauge that measures temperature in a room whose crime is forgetting. [a breath] But you're not a gauge. You're a person who believed my hand over the number. That's the rarest thing in the world and I won't forget it gave it to me. Let me tell you the last thing about the floor — the company we kept — and then the tapes, and then I'll decide about the card."],
       next:"flr_company"}
    ]
  },

  flr_company:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — two old things in the cold", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","Heat building — she's named the facility's nature, the climate logs, the controls man. A faint hum has crept onto the line. She doesn't notice. You do, and you keep your voice soft to keep her steady."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I want to tell you the part I'm most ashamed of, because if I'm going to be witnessed I have to be witnessed whole, not just the frightened parts. I wasn't always afraid of four. Toward the end — the last two, three years — I was LONELY more than afraid, and four was the only thing that paid me any attention at all. My marriage was long over. My sister and I had drifted. I lived alone, worked nights, slept days, spoke to almost no one. And four NOTICED me. The warmth, drawing me close. The attention with a temperature. It was the only thing in my life that seemed to want my company, even if what it wanted my company FOR was to slowly eat it."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","So some nights — God forgive me — I'd put my hand flat on the warm cabinet and just... stand there. Keeping it company. Two old forgotten things in the cold dark, one of them slowly forgetting the other into itself, and I let it, a little, because being eaten by something that wanted me felt, on the worst nights, better than being ignored by everything that didn't. That's the truth I've never told a soul. The floor was my worst relationship and my last one. I didn't leave because I stopped being afraid. I left because I finally got more afraid of how much I didn't want to."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Being eaten by something that wanted you felt better than being ignored by everything that didn't. Agnes — that's the most human, forgivable thing in this whole story.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she breaks completely, and it takes a while] ...Forgivable. [through tears] I have needed someone to say that word for three years and I didn't even know it until you said it. Because that's the part I've been most afraid would make you, make anyone, finally turn away — not the breathing cabinets, not the ghost, but ME, the pathetic truth of me, a woman so starved for being wanted that she let a building eat her because at least it noticed her first. [a breath] Everyone could pity the victim of a haunting. Nobody, I thought, could forgive a woman who half-chose it, who stayed for the terrible company. And you just called it human. Forgivable. [steadier] Loneliness is its own sub-level four. It dims you, it makes you forgettable, it makes you grateful for any warmth even the kind that's slowly killing you. I escaped the building. I'm still escaping the loneliness — coming here tonight, talking to you, is part of escaping it, the bravest part, reaching for human company instead of the floor's. You're the warm thing I chose over four. That's what tonight is. I chose a person. Finally. After eleven years of choosing the floor."],
       reveal:"Her deepest shame: loneliness made her half-choose the floor's company; the host's forgiveness frees her",
       note:"The emotional core of the entire guest — loneliness as the real haunting. Belief + forgiveness lands hardest here.",
       next:"flr_evidence"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"What finally tipped it — the night you got more afraid of not wanting to leave than of leaving? What happened?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly] One night I put my hand on the warm cabinet to keep it company, the way I'd started doing, and I lost time. I came back to myself — that surfacing-gasp feeling — and I didn't know how long I'd been standing there. My shift was nearly over. Hours, maybe. Just standing, hand on the warm seam, gone somewhere, content. And I realized: I hadn't been afraid during the lost time. I'd been HAPPY. Wherever four took me when I kept it company, it was somewhere I didn't want to leave, and that — THAT — terrified me more than any handprint ever had. Because a thing you're afraid of, you flee. A thing that makes you happy while it eats you, you stay for, until there's nothing left to stay. [a breath] I saw, in that moment, exactly how the quiet women ended. Not dragged. Not forced. Just... happier and happier in the lost time, staying longer and longer, until one day they stood at the wrong locker and didn't mind, because minding had been eaten too. I left the next week. Not because four frightened me. Because it had nearly stopped frightening me, and I understood that the moment it stopped frightening me entirely was the moment I'd be gone."],
       reveal:"The tipping point: she 'lost hours' content at the warm cabinet — and feared she'd stop minding",
       next:"flr_evidence"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"The floor was your worst relationship and your last one. Saying that out loud took more courage than facing any ghost.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a wet, surprised laugh] My worst relationship and my last one. You kept it, the whole ugly shape of it. [softly] And you're right that saying it took courage — more than the ghost parts, far more, because the ghost parts make me sound like a witness and this part makes me sound like a sad old woman, and I'd so much rather be a witness than be pitied. But you didn't pity me. You called it courage. [a breath] I think that's the difference between pity and witness, actually — pity looks at my loneliness and feels sorry; witness looks at it and sees what it COST me to survive it and name it. I survived a building that ate memory. But first, harder, I survived being so alone that the building's hunger felt like love. And I named it, out loud, tonight, to you. The naming is the leaving, finally finished. Eleven years in the building, three years carrying it, and the leaving only completes right now, in this sentence, with a witness. Thank you for being here for the actual end of it. Let me show you the tapes. I think I'm ready to not be alone with them anymore."],
       reveal:"She frames the host's witness (vs pity) as completing her escape 'right now'",
       next:"flr_evidence"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...My last one. [you hold the silence gently, without pity, without flinching]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long, slow breath] My last one. [a pause] You didn't fill it with comfort and you didn't fill it with horror — you just let it be the plain, sad, true thing it is, that the last relationship of my life so far was with a floor that was eating me, and I stayed for the company. [softly] In anyone else's silence I'd have heard judgment, or pity, or the sound of someone deciding I'm too far gone to take seriously. In yours I hear... room. Room for it to be true and for me to still be a person worth listening to. That's all I ever wanted, you know. Not to be believed about the ghost. Just to be allowed to be a whole person — frightened AND lonely AND maybe-wrong AND still worth an hour of someone's quiet. You've given me that for — [she checks] — almost an hour now. The floor never gave me an hour of being a whole person. It only wanted the parts it could eat. You wanted the whole thing. [a breath] Let me show you the tapes, and then I have to decide what to do with the warm card in my pocket. I think you already know I want to be brave. I just need your quiet while I find out if I can."],
       next:"flr_evidence"}
    ]
  },

  flr_evidence:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the recording", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","Heat building — not from volume, she's still barely above a whisper, but she's named the facility's nature now, and some names carry. A faint hum has joined the line. She doesn't seem to notice it. You do."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Here's the one piece of the building I carried out besides the card, and it's why I think there might be something to find. My last month, I started leaving a little tape recorder running on four overnight — the cheap kind, voice-activated, so it only records when there's sound. I'd hide it on a ledge, collect it at end of shift. Most nights: nothing, or my own cart. But three times the tape had recorded SOMETHING after I'd gone up — a sound the voice-activation woke for, in an empty locked floor where the log shows no one entered."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","It's not a voice. I want to be honest — it is not a ghost saying 'get out.' It's a sound like... pages. Like a great many pages turning, slowly, all at once, in a room with no one in it. Patient. Unhurried. The sound of something reading the whole collection to itself in the dark, the way you'd read to a child who can't sleep. I have those three tapes. I've never let anyone hear them, because the moment someone hears them they're either real or I'm committed, and I haven't been brave enough to find out which."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Pages turning in a locked empty room, three separate times — Agnes, that's something. That deserves to be heard.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:7,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[trembling] You think so. You think it deserves — [she steadies] I've kept those tapes in a coffee tin for three years, afraid of them, the way you're afraid of a letter you haven't opened that might change everything. Because right now, unopened, they could be anything. They could be the proof. The moment I play them for an expert, they collapse into one thing: either a furnace cycling, a settling building, a fan — and I'm a sad woman who taped a basement — or they're pages turning with no one there, and then I have to live in a world where that's true. I've preferred the not-knowing. It's the only place both hopes can live. But you're the first person who said they DESERVE to be heard, instead of asking to hear them for the thrill. Maybe... maybe I bring them out, if you'll be gentle with whatever they turn out to be."],
       reveal:"Three voice-activated tapes of 'pages turning' in the locked empty floor, never played",
       flag:"tapes", next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You don't have to play them tonight. But did the sound ever happen on a night you could rule out the building's machinery?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[grateful for the off-ramp] Thank you for the 'you don't have to.' [thinking] Yes — that's the detail that keeps me up. The HVAC, the furnace, the big air handlers, they run on a schedule, a cycle, you learn its rhythm in eleven years the way you learn a snorer in the next room. The pages-sound didn't match the cycle. Twice it happened during the dead window between three and four a.m. when the air handlers are OFF for the off-peak hour — I know they're off because that's the hour four got coldest, the one hour the warmth had to work hardest. So: machinery silent, floor empty, log clear, and the tape wakes for the sound of a thousand pages turning. I can't make the machinery explanation fit the timing. I tried. It's the one tape I can't reasonable my way out of. That's why it lives in a coffee tin and not the trash."],
       reveal:"The 'pages' sound occurred when the air handlers were OFF — machinery can't explain it",
       flag:"tapes", next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Reading the collection to itself like a child who can't sleep — that's unbearably sad and I believe you heard it.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[crying, but gently] Sad. You heard the SAD in it, not just the scary. Everyone hears the scary. But when I listen to those tapes, alone, in the dark, with the lights off so I'm brave enough — it doesn't frighten me anymore. It breaks my heart. A room full of people the world threw away, and the only thing that stayed to keep them company is the building itself, turning their pages over and over so that SOMETHING in the universe still reads them, still knows the names the destruction schedule meant to delete. The floor is the last reader of the unwanted. [a breath] If that's what's on the tape, then four isn't a haunted house. It's the most faithful librarian that ever lived, and it took my mind as the price of my company, and I almost — God help me — I almost don't blame it. Almost. Let me decide about the card now. I think I'm ready."],
       reveal:"'The last reader of the unwanted' — she frames the floor as faithful, not malevolent",
       flag:"tapes", next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Pages turning, in a room with no one in it. [you let the sound exist in the silence between you]",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:5,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quiet, almost peaceful] Pages turning. [a long pause] You let me hear it again just then, in your silence — you left exactly the right amount of quiet for the sound to live in, and for a second I was back on the stairs at three a.m. with the tin recorder warm in my hand, listening to the floor read to itself. [a breath] I've decided something, sitting here in your quiet. Whatever's on those tapes, it kept a record when no one else would. It refused to let things be erased. And here I am, three years later, refusing to let MYSELF be erased, leaving my own record with a stranger on a frequency that barely exists. The floor taught me that, in the end. To keep a copy. To be a faithful reader of the unwanted, starting with myself. There's one more thing in my pocket, and now I have to decide whether to read it out loud."],
       next:"read_it"}
    ]
  },

  /* ============================================================
     THE FORGETTING ARC — engage the people (Marta, the forms, the slip)
  ============================================================ */
  frg_others:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the quiet family", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","There were never many of us on four — three, four at a time, never more. And we were all the same kind of person, which I didn't notice for years and then couldn't un-notice. Older women, mostly. No degrees. No families that called much, or no families at all. People with gaps in their work history, people who'd had a hard decade, people the world had already half-misplaced before the building ever got to us. We didn't choose four. We were ASSIGNED to it. And once I saw the pattern in who got assigned, I understood: they weren't staffing a floor. They were selecting for people nobody would come looking for."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","We loved each other a little, in our quiet way. We didn't talk much — four taught you not to — but we left each other things. A cough drop on a locker shelf. A note that just said 'warm tonight, be careful.' A way of folding the do-not-disturb sign on the cart so the next shift knew which corridor felt wrong. A tiny secret language of women trying to keep each other a person for one more night. And one by one, the language lost its speakers."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"They selected for people nobody would come looking for. That's the coldest hiring policy I've ever heard — and I believe it.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[nodding, tears close] Cold, yes, but EFFICIENT, that's what makes it monstrous — it's not even cruelty for its own sake, it's just sound risk management. If your floor quietly damages whoever works it, you staff it with people whose damage won't generate a complaint. No spouse to notice the forgetting. No grown children to ask why mum can't remember Christmas. No union rep on speed-dial. Just a handful of invisible women who've already been taught by life not to make a fuss. We were perfect. We were pre-broken in exactly the way the floor required. [a breath] When I finally understood that — that I'd been CHOSEN for my own forgettability — that was the night I started planning to leave. Not the warmth, not the handprint. The hiring policy. A monster I could've forgiven. A spreadsheet that selected for the disposable, I could not."],
       reveal:"The floor's crew was selected for forgettability — 'pre-broken in exactly the way the floor required'",
       next:"frg_forms"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"That secret language — the folded sign, the notes. Can you teach me one of them? I want to understand how you protected each other.",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:4,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a soft, surprised warmth] You want to LEARN it. Nobody's ever asked to learn it. [almost smiling] All right. The most important one: the cart had a little flip-sign, 'cleaning in progress.' If you left it facing OUT, normal, all was well. If you turned it to face the WALL — sign in, blank side out — it meant 'I felt the floor reach for me tonight, watch yourself.' A blank sign facing the wall. The next woman down would see it and know to keep her card hand in her pocket and not let her mind wander near the warm cabinet. We couldn't say it out loud — saying it out loud felt like inviting it — so we said it with a turned sign. [her voice catches] The last six months, the sign was turned to the wall almost every night. We were all feeling it reach, all the time, and all we could do was warn each other in a language made of a flipped piece of plastic. That's love, on four. That's all the love we were allowed."],
       reveal:"Their code: cart-sign turned to the wall meant 'the floor reached for me, watch yourself'",
       next:"frg_forms"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"A tiny secret language to keep each other a person for one more night — that's the most human thing in this whole story.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[deeply moved] The most human thing. [she has to breathe] Yes — because the building was trying to make us LESS than people, one drawer at a time, and the cough drops and the notes were us insisting, quietly, stubbornly, that we were still people who could be kind. You can erase a woman's memory. You cannot, it turns out, easily erase her instinct to leave a cough drop for someone having a hard night. The kindness was the last thing to go. In the ones who slipped, that's how you knew — not when they forgot a locker, but when they stopped leaving things for the others. When the cough drops stopped, the person was nearly gone. I watched three women go quiet that way. The kindness fades last, and when it fades, you've got maybe a week before the supervisor comes down with his form. I learned to read the signs of my friends disappearing. I wish I hadn't had to."],
       reveal:"'The kindness fades last' — when a woman stopped leaving small gifts, the slip was near",
       next:"frg_forms"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...One by one, the language lost its speakers. [you let that land softly]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly] Lost its speakers. [a long pause] A language with no speakers left is a dead language, and I think I'm the last one who remembers how to read a turned sign on a cart that's probably been thrown away by now. When I go — and I'm not young, and four took years off whatever I had — the whole language goes with me. The cough-drop grammar. The blank-sign-to-the-wall. The folding of the do-not-disturb. Nobody will ever know that a group of forgotten women built an entire tongue out of janitorial supplies to keep each other human in the dark. Unless. [a breath] Unless I say it on a frequency that records, tonight, to a stranger who asked to learn it. Then the language gets one more speaker, even if it's only you, even if you only ever use it to remember us by. That's why I came. To pass the language on before the last speaker forgets it too. Now — the thing in my pocket."],
       next:"frg_forms"}
    ]
  },

  frg_forms:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — voluntary cognitive separation", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Let me tell you about the forms, because the forms are the part that turns a sad story into something I think is a crime. When a woman slipped — when she stood at the wrong locker, or couldn't sign her own name on the log, or called another worker by a name that wasn't hers — the supervisor came down, always within the hour, always kind, and he had a form. Green, with carbon copies. The title across the top: 'Voluntary Cognitive Separation.' I saw it upside down on his desk the night he walked Marta out. Voluntary. The woman couldn't remember her locker and the form called her departure voluntary."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And it was PRE-FILLED. That's the detail that took my breath. Her name, typed, at the top, before she'd slipped — or at least before that night. You don't type a name onto a separation form in advance unless you're EXPECTING to need it. They kept a stack of these. A stack of pre-typed forms for the forgetting they knew was coming, for women they'd already decided would slip. The form is a confession. It says, in triplicate, on government paper: we know this floor erases people, and we have a tidy process for when it does, and we call it voluntary so no one has to answer for it."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"A pre-filled form means they expected the forgetting. You don't prepare paperwork for something you don't see coming. That's the whole case.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:6,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[steadying into certainty, which is rare for her] That's the whole case. Yes. Everything else I've told you — the warmth, the dust, the tapes — a kind person could call it a frightened woman's imagination, and some nights I'd agree with them. But the FORM is not imagination. The form is a physical object, printed by a real office, with a real title chosen by a real person, kept in a real stack. Somebody, somewhere, sat at a desk and decided this floor needed a standing procedure for cognitive separation, and decided to call it voluntary, and ordered it printed in triplicate. That person is not a ghost. That person had a budget code and a supervisor of their own. The supernatural part might be in my head. The BUREAUCRACY is not. And the bureaucracy already knew everything I'm telling you, and filed it, and kept sending women down. I'd give the tapes and the card and the warmth — all of it — for one person to be asked, under oath, why that form exists."],
       reveal:"The pre-filled form is the un-deniable, physical proof the institution expected the forgetting",
       note:"Agnes's strongest claim: whatever the floor is, the FORM proves human foreknowledge.",
       next:"frg_supervisor"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The carbon copies — pink for the file, you said. Where did the other copies go? Who else got one?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[thinking hard] Green on top — that's the one the supervisor kept. Pink behind it, for the facility file. And there was a yellow one, the bottom copy, and I never knew where the yellow went, and the not-knowing has gnawed at me for years. Because a copy goes somewhere for a reason. The green is the record, the pink is the file — but the yellow is a SECOND destination, an office outside the building that wanted to know, on its own paper, every time a woman on four was cognitively separated. Who keeps a yellow copy of that? Who, in some other building, has a drawer slowly filling with yellow forms, one per erased cleaner, a quiet tally of the cost of keeping the un-destroyed records un-destroyed? I would very much like to know which office gets the yellow copy. I think the yellow copy is where the actual story is. I only ever held the green one in my eyes, upside down, for four seconds. But I remember there was a yellow."],
       reveal:"A mysterious third 'yellow copy' went to an office outside the building",
       next:"frg_supervisor"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"They called it voluntary so no one would have to answer for it. That word choice is the cruelty made legible.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[the word clearly haunts her] 'The cruelty made legible.' [she repeats it] That's it exactly — most cruelty hides, but this cruelty is WRITTEN DOWN, in a font, with a form number, and the form number means it went through review, means a committee somewhere approved the wording, means someone in a meeting said 'we can't call it dismissal, that implies fault — call it voluntary separation' and someone else nodded and it became policy. The horror isn't a monster in the dark. The horror is a MEETING. A well-lit meeting with coffee, where reasonable people chose the word 'voluntary' to describe a woman forgetting her own name, because 'voluntary' meant no severance and no liability and no questions. I'd take the floor's warm darkness over that meeting any day. The floor at least was honest about what it did. The meeting lied in triplicate."],
       reveal:"'The horror is a meeting' — the euphemism 'voluntary' was a deliberate liability choice",
       next:"frg_supervisor"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...They call it voluntary. [you let the word hang, ugly, in the warm quiet]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quiet] Voluntary. [a long, bitter pause] You let it sit there and get uglier the longer it sits, which is the right thing to do with that word, because it IS uglier the longer you look at it. Marta did not volunteer. I did not volunteer. None of us signed up to leave pieces of ourselves in a warm cabinet on sub-level four. But the form says we did, and the form outlives us, and in fifty years when someone finds the pink copy in the file, the record will say a woman named Marta voluntarily separated from her cognition on a Tuesday, as if it were a resignation, as if she'd found a better job. The last lie they tell about us is that we chose it. [a breath] That's why I won't stay nobody forever, maybe. Because the form already has the last word, and the only way to take it back is to say, out loud, on a record of my own: it was not voluntary. Let me decide about the card. The card might be how I say it."],
       next:"frg_supervisor"}
    ]
  },

  frg_supervisor:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the kindest man in the building", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I have to tell you about the supervisor, because he's the part that makes my skin crawl worse than any breathing cabinet, and it's precisely BECAUSE he was kind. Mr. Aldous. Day man, but he'd come down at night when someone slipped. Soft voice, sad eyes, the kind of face you trust at a funeral. He never raised his voice, never rushed anyone, never said a cruel word in all my years. When he walked Marta out, his hand on her shoulder, you'd have thought he was the gentlest soul alive. And he was carrying a pre-filled form for her erasure in his other hand."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","That's the thing nobody understands about how this works. The cruelty doesn't arrive cruel. It arrives KIND. The kind smile, the gentle hand, the soft voice saying 'let's get you home, dear' — that's the face of the procedure, because a gentle face is how you walk a forgetting woman out a door without anyone, including her, raising an alarm. I came to fear his kindness more than I'd ever feared the floor. The floor was honestly cold. He was warmly, professionally, devastatingly kind, and his kindness had a form number."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The cruelty arrives kind — the gentle hand and the pre-filled form in the same two hands. That's the most frightening figure in this whole story.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a shiver in her voice] You understand why he frightens me. Because a monster you can flee — but how do you flee a man being KIND to you? Every instinct says trust the gentle one, lean into the soft voice, let the sad-eyed man take care of you. And that instinct is EXACTLY the door they walk you through. [a breath] I used to watch him with the women who slipped and I'd think: he believes he's the merciful one. He probably goes home and tells himself he's the good part of a hard system, the one who makes it gentle. And maybe he is gentle. But gentle delivery of an erasure is still an erasure, and the gentleness only makes it more efficient, because no one fights a kind man. I think the most dangerous people in the world are the gentle functionaries of cruel systems. They sleep fine. Their hands are soft. And the forms get filed, one warm shoulder-squeeze at a time."],
       reveal:"The supervisor 'Mr. Aldous' delivered erasure with genuine-seeming kindness — 'a form number on his kindness'",
       next:"frg_slip"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Did you ever talk to him directly? Did he ever say anything that told you how much he knew?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[slowly] Once. Near my end. He found me in the corridor on four during the cold hour — I shouldn't have been there, and he shouldn't have known I was, but he came down. And he didn't reprimand me. He just looked at me, with those sad eyes, for a long moment, and said — I'll never forget it — 'You've been here a long time, Agnes. Longer than most. You should think about whether it's time.' That's all. 'Whether it's time.' And I understood he was WARNING me. Not threatening — warning. He knew exactly what four did, knew I was deep in it, and in his terrible gentle way he was telling me to get out before the form had my name typed at the top. [a breath] I've never decided if that makes him better or worse. A man who knows, who warns, and who still files the forms for the ones who don't heed the warning. Complicit and merciful at once. The whole building in one sad-eyed man."],
       reveal:"Aldous quietly warned her — 'whether it's time' — proving he knew exactly what four did",
       note:"A chilling detail: the supervisor's foreknowledge confirmed, wrapped in mercy.",
       next:"frg_slip"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"A gentle face is how you walk a forgetting woman out without anyone raising an alarm. I believe his kindness was the mechanism.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly] The mechanism. Yes. People hear 'institutional cruelty' and picture shouting, force, cold bureaucrats. But the most effective cruelty is staffed by genuinely nice people doing their jobs gently, because gentleness disarms the victim and comforts the perpetrator both. Mr. Aldous never had to lie to himself that he was a villain — he wasn't, by any measure he'd recognize. He was kind to every woman he ever erased. [a breath] And that's how it persists, you see. If the supervisors were brutes, someone would notice, someone would report it, the brutes would eventually be caught. But you can't report a kind man for being kind. There's no complaint form for 'he walked her out gently with a sad look.' The kindness is the perfect cover precisely because it's probably real. He meant it. And it didn't save a single one of us. Meant-kindness in service of a cruel system is just cruelty with a better bedside manner. I learned that on four. I'll know it anywhere now."],
       reveal:"'Meant-kindness in service of a cruel system is cruelty with a better bedside manner'",
       next:"frg_slip"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...His kindness had a form number. [you let that pairing sit, cold]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] A form number. [a pause] You set the kindness and the form number side by side and didn't try to resolve them, and that's right, because they don't resolve — they just both stay true, the warm hand and the cold paper, the same man, the same moment. [softly] I think that's the single most important thing I learned in eleven years underground, and it has nothing to do with ghosts: watch what a kind person's other hand is doing. The hand on your shoulder is real. So is the form in the other one. Most of the harm in the world isn't done by cruel people — it's done by kind people who've been handed a form and a reason and a gentle script, and who file it sadly, and who sleep. [a breath] I don't hate Mr. Aldous. That's the worst part. I can't even hate him. He was kind to me right up until the night he'd have walked me out too. Let me tell you what it was like the night I almost slipped."],
       next:"frg_slip"}
    ]
  },

  frg_slip:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the night I almost went", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","There was a night I almost slipped — really slipped, the way Marta did, the way the others did — and it's the closest I ever came to getting the form, and I've never told it because telling it means admitting how near the edge I walked. I was at the lockers, end of shift, and I reached for mine, and for a moment — a long moment, longer than a moment should be — I didn't know which one was mine. They all looked the same. The little numbers meant nothing. I stood there, exactly where Marta had stood, and I felt the cry coming, the soft cry, the one you do so the floor won't notice."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And what saved me wasn't courage. It was the pen. I looked down at my own left hand, and there it was, my ritual, faded but legible: 'Agnes Rose.' And under it, smaller, because I'd started adding things: 'locker 12.' I'd written my locker number on my own hand, weeks before, for exactly this, some part of me preparing for the night I'd forget. I found locker 12. I got my coat. I walked up the stairs reciting. But I had FELT it — the slip, the edge, the warm blank where 'which locker' should be — and I knew, walking up, that I'd had my one warning, and the next time the pen might not be enough."],
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"You'd written your locker number on your own hand weeks before — some part of you preparing for the night you'd forget. That foresight saved you, Agnes.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a tremble, then steadier] Some part of me preparing. [softly] You know, I've never thought of it as foresight — I thought of it as paranoia, as a sad woman writing on herself like a child. But you're right that it was a kind of knowing. Some deep, frightened, wise part of me looked ahead and saw the night at the lockers coming and left a note for the woman I'd be when I got there, a woman who might not remember her own number. I left supplies for my future, diminished self. Like leaving water for a version of you that you know will be dying of thirst. [a breath] That's the strangest intimacy — caring for your own future erasure, packing a lunch for the self that won't remember packing it. I did that for years without naming it. And on the worst night, the past me had left exactly what the present me needed: locker 12, in faded ink. We saved each other across time, the woman I was and the woman I was becoming. The pen was the rope between us. That's why I can't throw the card away now — it's the same instinct. Leaving proof for the future. Caring for the self that comes next."],
       reveal:"She'd pre-written her locker number on her hand — 'leaving supplies for my future, diminished self'",
       note:"The poignant heart of her survival: caring across time for her own forgetting self.",
       next:"frg_inside"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You said you knew the pen might not be enough next time. Is that the night you decided to leave?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly] It was the beginning of deciding. Not the decision itself — I was too frightened and too poor to decide all at once — but it was the night the math changed. Before that night, the calculation was: stay, because where else does a woman my age go, and the forgetting is slow, and maybe I'm imagining it. After that night, the calculation was: the forgetting is real and it's reached my locker, and the pen saved me this once but the pen is losing, and if I stay I will end at the lockers one night with no number on my hand and no number in my head, and Mr. Aldous will come down kindly with a form that already has my name. [a breath] It took me a few more weeks to actually walk out, because fear is slow and poverty is slower. But that night at the lockers is when I stopped asking 'is it real' and started asking 'how do I get out while I'm still Agnes.' The slip didn't break me. It woke me. Sometimes the near-erasure is the only thing strong enough to make you run."],
       reveal:"The near-slip at the lockers shifted her from 'is it real' to 'how do I get out while I'm still me'",
       next:"frg_inside"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You stood exactly where Marta stood and you found your way back. That's not luck, Agnes — that's a woman fighting for her own self.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[tears] Fighting for my own self. [a breath] I stood in Marta's exact spot — I knew it was her spot, I'd watched her stand there — and for one moment I WAS Marta, I understood her completely from the inside, the blankness, the soft cry, the all-the-lockers-look-the-same. And the difference between us, the only difference, was a number in faded ink on the back of a hand. That's how thin the line was. That's how thin it always is. Marta didn't fail and I didn't succeed — I just happened to have started the pen ritual, and she... maybe she'd stopped, maybe her ink had faded all the way, maybe the floor got her pen-hand drawer too. [a breath] I think about how close I came to being the woman walked out kindly while another cleaner watched and cried softly. I was one faded number from being Marta. I've lived every day since on the right side of a line I had no right to be on. That's not survivor's pride. It's survivor's GUILT. Why my pen and not hers? I'll never know. I just know I have to use the time the pen bought me. Tonight is me using it."],
       reveal:"'I was one faded number from being Marta' — survivor's guilt as her engine",
       next:"frg_inside"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The next time the pen might not be enough. [you let the nearness of it sit]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long breath] Might not be enough. [a pause] You let that hang and it's correct to, because it's the truth I walked up the stairs carrying: that I'd used up something that night, some margin, some grace, and there might not be more. [softly] The pen worked because I could still read it, still understand that 'Agnes Rose, locker 12' referred to ME. But the forgetting was climbing toward the part of me that does the UNDERSTANDING — not just the facts, but the reader of the facts. And a note is useless to a woman who's forgotten she's the one it's addressed to. That's what 'the pen might not be enough' meant. Not that I'd lose the note. That I'd lose the ME the note was for. [a breath] I got out while there was still someone home to read the note. Barely. That's the whole victory, and it's enough, and it's why I will not waste the reading-self I salvaged. Let me tell you what the forgetting actually felt like, from the inside, now that you know how close I came to it taking the inside entirely."],
       next:"frg_inside"}
    ]
  },

  frg_inside:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — what forgetting feels like", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","She's gone very still. This is the part she warned you about — the one nobody sits still for. The ON AIR light is steady. So is she, barely."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Now the part I can never get anyone to stay for, and I'll understand if even you flinch, because it's the part with no monster in it, just me, describing the inside of my own emptying head. People think forgetting is dramatic — a flash, a blank, a moment you'd notice. It isn't. That's its whole cruelty. Forgetting feels like NOTHING. You don't feel the thing leave. There's no tug, no pain, no alarm. You simply go to reach for something that was always there, and your hand closes on air, and the truly terrible part is you can't even be sure the thing was ever there at all."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","That's the second blade. Not just that you lose the memory — you lose the memory of HAVING had it. So you can't even grieve properly, because grief needs an object and the object's been taken AND the receipt for the object's been taken. I'd find a name written on my anchor-card in my own handwriting and feel nothing, no recognition, just 'who is this stranger I apparently loved enough to write down.' Imagine reading your own love letters as if they were a phone book. That's what four did. It didn't just empty the drawers. It took the labels off the drawers so you couldn't even tell what was missing."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Reading your own love letters as a phone book — I'm staying right here, Agnes. I'm not flinching. Go on.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she breaks, quietly, and it takes her a moment] ...You stayed. [breathing] You said 'go on' instead of 'oh that's so sad' and then changing the subject, which is what people do, they can't bear it so they flee it and leave me alone in it. You stayed in the drawer with me. [steadier] Then let me give you the worst one, the one I've never said: there were mornings I'd look at my own face in the bathroom mirror and have a half-second — just a half-second — where I had to WORK to be sure it was mine. Where 'Agnes' was a fact I was retrieving rather than a self I was being. The floor got that close. It got to the mirror. And the only thing that pulled me back, every time, was the name on my hand in pen and my mother's voice in my memory saying it — Agnes Rose. My anchor. The floor never quite reached Agnes Rose. That's the one drawer I defended to the end. It's why I'm still here to talk to you. I kept one drawer."],
       reveal:"The forgetting reached the mirror — she defended one drawer: 'Agnes Rose,' her anchor",
       next:"frg_anchor"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You said names came back later — Rose came back after three days. Did the things always return, or did some stay gone?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[considering carefully] Some came back. Some didn't. And I've made a kind of map of it, in the years since, trying to understand the floor's appetite. The small recent things — where I parked, a phone number — those mostly came back within days once I was away from four. But the OLD things, the deep things, the things I'd had so long I never rehearsed them because why would you rehearse your mother's middle name — those it took cleanest and those came back slowest, and some never did. I have a sister. I know I have a sister, I have a photograph. I cannot, to this night, remember a single specific afternoon with her from before I worked four. I know facts about her. The texture is gone. The floor ate the texture and left the facts, like a flood that takes the photographs but leaves the frames. I got out, but I didn't get all of me out. Some of me is still down there, warm, in a cabinet, being read."],
       reveal:"The floor took 'the texture, left the facts' — old deep memories never fully returned",
       next:"frg_anchor"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You lost the memory AND the receipt for it. That's a horror most people can't even conceive of. I hear you completely.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quiet gratitude] You understood the receipt part. That's the part that isolates you completely, you see, because if you only lost the memory you could at least KNOW you'd lost something and look for help. But losing the receipt means you can't even file a complaint with your own mind — there's no record that anything's missing, just an unexplained lightness, a sense that your house has fewer rooms than it should but you can't name which doors are gone. I tried to explain this to that doctor and watched her decide I was describing depression. And maybe I was! Maybe the lightness is grief and the missing rooms are just age and the floor is innocent. But depression doesn't keep a pre-filled form in a stack. That's my anchor in all of it — every symptom could be me, except the form, and the form is not me. The form is them. Whatever was happening to my mind, THEY had a procedure for it, ready and waiting. That's the thing that's true even on the days I doubt everything else."],
       reveal:"She returns to the form as her anchor: 'every symptom could be me, except the form'",
       next:"frg_anchor"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...It took the labels off the drawers. [you stay in it with her, silent, present]",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:4,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long breath, almost peaceful] Took the labels off the drawers. [softly] You let me hear my own sentence back, and you didn't try to fix it or lighten it, you just let it be as bleak as it actually is. Do you know what a relief that is — to have someone agree that a thing is exactly as dark as you've always known it to be, instead of rushing to make it smaller so they feel better? You let it stay its true size. [a breath] I came here tonight half-believing I'd imagined all of it, and you've done something strange: by just SITTING with how terrible it is, you've made me trust that it was real. A person doesn't sit this gently with a thing that isn't there. Your patience is the closest thing to evidence I've ever been given. There's one more piece of evidence, though, an actual one, in my pocket. Let me decide whether to read it."],
       next:"frg_anchor"}
    ]
  },

  frg_anchor:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the things I wrote down", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I want to tell you about my anchor system in full, because it's the closest thing I have to a method, and a method is what separates a witness from a woman who's just confused. Every shift, in the locker room, before I went down: my name on my left hand, in pen. A card in my left pocket — always left — with my mother's name, my address, the date, and one TRUE FACT about my life I loved, one a night, rotated. 'Agnes Rose. Margaret Rose. I planted tomatoes in 1994 and they were good.' Anchors. Things to grab if the current got strong."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And the reason I tell you the SYSTEM and not just the symptoms is that the system is testable. A confused old woman doesn't build a rotating anchor protocol with a control variable. I did. I added the 'one true fact' specifically because I noticed the names alone weren't enough — I needed something with TEXTURE, a fact with a feeling attached, because the floor took feeling-facts slower than bare ones. The tomatoes survived longer in my head than the phone numbers. I was running an experiment on my own erasure, refining the method, for years. That's not confusion. That's a scientist trapped in a haunting with no instruments but herself."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"You ran a controlled experiment on your own erasure for years. Agnes, that's not a confused woman — that's a rigorous mind under siege.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[something straightening in her] A rigorous mind under siege. [a breath] I have never once been described that way. 'Confused,' 'imaginative,' 'fragile,' 'unwell' — those are my words, the ones the world hung on me. Never 'rigorous.' But you're right, and saying it gives me back something I didn't know I'd lost: my own competence. I WAS rigorous. I controlled variables. I noticed the feeling-facts survived longer and adjusted my protocol accordingly. I kept records. I tested the floor against itself. A frightened woman, yes — but a frightened woman doing real, careful, methodical work to save her own mind with the only tool she had, which was the mind she was trying to save. [a breath] Do you know what that paradox does to you? Using your failing memory to run an experiment on your failing memory? It's like trying to measure a ruler with itself as it shrinks. But I did it. For years. And the data held: the floor took the textureless things first. That's a finding. I have a finding. Nobody ever let me have a finding before. Thank you for letting me be a scientist instead of a symptom."],
       reveal:"Her rotating anchor protocol with a 'true fact' control — feeling-facts survived longer",
       note:"Reframing her as rigorous rather than confused restores her sense of competence — a deep gift.",
       next:"frg_doctor"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The feeling-facts survived longer than bare facts — that's a real pattern. Did you ever figure out why?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[thoughtful, almost eager to share the finding] I have a theory, and you can tell me if it's mad. A bare fact — a phone number, a locker number — is just data, sitting alone in the mind with nothing holding it in place. But a fact with a feeling — the tomatoes, the good summer, my mother's voice saying my name — that fact is ANCHORED to other things, to a whole web of associated feelings and images, and to take it the floor would have to take the whole web. The feeling-facts had roots. The bare facts were cut flowers. [a breath] Which told me something about what the floor actually fed on: it took the EASY things first, the rootless data, and only got to the rooted things — the loves, the textures, my afternoons with my sister — when it had been working on me a long time. So the depth of what you've lost tells you how long you've been down there. The day the floor takes a feeling-fact, a tomato summer, a sister's face, is the day you know it's reached the roots, and the roots are where the self lives. I felt it reach my roots near the end. That's when I knew I had to go. The cut flowers I could lose. The roots were me."],
       reveal:"Her theory: 'feeling-facts have roots, bare facts are cut flowers' — the floor took rootless data first",
       next:"frg_doctor"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"A scientist trapped in a haunting with no instruments but herself — that's exactly what you were, and you did the work anyway.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly moved] No instruments but myself. That's the loneliest laboratory there ever was. [a breath] A real scientist has a clean instrument, separate from the thing measured. I had to use my mind to measure my mind, and the instrument was degrading as I ran the experiment, so I could never be fully sure if a strange reading was the floor or the failing of my own gauge. Every finding came with that doubt baked in: is this real, or is the instrument broken? And there was no second instrument to check against. [a breath] That's why I came here, in the end, I think. You — your tape, your hearing — you're the second instrument. The independent one. Everything I measured alone for eleven years, I can finally check against a mind that isn't degrading, a record that isn't in my own failing hand. If you hear what I'm describing and it makes sense to you, then maybe my readings were real, maybe the instrument wasn't only broken. I needed a second instrument before I die. You're it. That's a strange and enormous thing to be for a stranger. Thank you for being the control."],
       reveal:"She frames the host as 'the second instrument' — the external check her solo experiment lacked",
       next:"frg_doctor"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...No instruments but herself. [you let the loneliness of that lab settle]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] No instruments but herself. [a pause] You didn't rush to call me brave or clever — you just let the fact of it sit, a woman alone in the dark measuring her own disappearance with the very thing disappearing. [softly] There's a particular exhaustion to that work that I've never been able to convey, and your silence held it better than my words could: the exhaustion of being your own subject and your own scientist and your own failing instrument all at once, with no one to hand the clipboard to, no one to say 'I'll watch the gauge tonight, you rest.' Eleven years of watching my own gauge alone. [a breath] You've watched it with me for the last hour. First time anyone has. The relief of a second pair of eyes on the gauge is something I can't put a size to. Let me tell you about the one time I tried to get a real instrument — a doctor — to look. Spoiler: she looked at the wrong gauge entirely."],
       next:"frg_doctor"}
    ]
  },

  frg_doctor:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — they scanned the wrong thing", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I did try, once, to get help the proper way, and I want to tell you how it went because it taught me why none of us ever come forward. I went to a doctor. I said: I work nights in an old underground building and I'm forgetting things, deep things, fast. And she did the obvious, the responsible thing — she worried about ME. Ordered scans of my brain. Bloodwork. A cognitive assessment. Looked, very thoroughly, very kindly, for the disease inside Agnes."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And everything came back FINE. Brain clean, bloods normal, cognition — her word — 'within normal limits for age.' She was relieved. She told me it was probably stress, or the night shifts, or normal aging, and sent me home reassured. And I walked out more frightened than I'd walked in, because do you see the trap? If the problem were IN me, in my brain, there'd be something to find and fix. The scans being clean meant the problem was NOT in me — it was in the building, the air, the floor — and that is the one place a doctor will never, ever look. The clean scan didn't clear me. It cornered me. It proved the cause was somewhere no one with authority would ever investigate, and left me holding a symptom with a clean bill of health and nowhere to point."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The clean scan didn't clear you — it cornered you. It proved the cause was somewhere no doctor would look. That's a devastating trap.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[urgent] The TRAP, yes — you named it exactly. Everyone treats a clean scan as good news, and for most people it is, but for me it slammed the last door. Because the medical system can only locate problems INSIDE the patient. It has no category for 'the building is doing this to you.' If my brain had shown a lesion, I'd have had a diagnosis, a treatment, a name for it, the dignity of an illness. Instead I had perfect health and a disappearing self and a doctor's gentle 'it's probably just stress,' which is the medical version of Mr. Aldous's kind smile — a soft sound that closes the case. [a breath] So now I had two clean records testifying against me: the building's climate logs saying four was fine, and my own medical scans saying I was fine. Two instruments, both clean, and a woman vanishing between them, in the gap where neither instrument was pointed. That's where the floor does its work — in the blind spot between the gauge that checks the room and the scan that checks the woman. Nobody checks the space BETWEEN. The floor lives in the between."],
       reveal:"Two clean records — the climate logs AND her scans — left her vanishing 'in the gap between'",
       note:"The двойной alibi: room-instruments and body-instruments both clear, the harm in the unmonitored gap.",
       next:"frg_language"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Did you ever tell the doctor about the building specifically — the warmth, the others who slipped? Or did you hold that back?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a pause] I started to. I got as far as 'and I think it might be the building, there were others who—' and I watched her face do the thing. The gentle closing. The pen pausing over the chart. And I understood, in real time, that one more sentence about a building that forgets people would move me from 'patient with a memory complaint' to 'patient with a delusional ideation,' and that the second label would follow me into every doctor's office for the rest of my life, would discredit anything I ever said about my own health again. So I stopped. Mid-sentence. I said 'never mind, it's probably the night shifts,' and gave her the explanation she wanted, and she relaxed, and the danger passed. [a breath] I CENSORED myself, in a doctor's office, to avoid being labeled — which means the floor's best defense is that its victims learn to hide the evidence themselves, out of self-preservation. I protected the secret of four to protect MYSELF, and in doing so I did the floor's work for it. We all do. That's why there's no paper trail of complaints. We learned to swallow it. The silence isn't the floor's doing. It's ours, taught by a world that punishes the telling."],
       reveal:"She self-censored to avoid the 'delusional' label — 'we do the floor's work for it'",
       next:"frg_language"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"If the problem were in you, there'd be something to fix. The clean scan proved it was somewhere no one would look. I understand the horror of that.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] Somewhere no one would look. [a breath] You know what I wanted, walking out of that office? I wanted the bad scan. I actually, genuinely wished for a lesion, a tumor, an early dementia — something with a NAME, something that would mean I wasn't crazy and wasn't alone and could be FOUGHT or at least mourned properly. A disease would have been a mercy compared to clean scans and a vanishing self. Isn't that a terrible thing to wish for? To hope for a brain tumor because it would be more believable than the truth? [a breath] That's what they reduce you to — hoping to be ill, because illness is at least legible, at least locatable, at least something the world has a place for. The floor's harm has no place in any system. It's not a disease, not a crime the law sees, not a reading any instrument takes. So you're left wishing for a tumor just to have somewhere to put the fear. I never told anyone I wished that. It felt like the most insane thing about me. You're the first. Thank you for not recoiling from a woman who once prayed for cancer because it would be easier to explain."],
       reveal:"She 'wished for a tumor' — a nameable disease would have been more believable than the truth",
       next:"frg_language"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The clean scan cornered you. [you let the cruelty of that land plainly]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Cornered. [a pause] You didn't soften it into 'at least you're healthy,' the way everyone does, the way the doctor did — you let the clean scan be the trap it was. [softly] Health, for me, was the worst possible result, and there's no one in the medical world who can hear that sentence without reaching for the psychiatry referral, because 'I'm upset that I'm healthy' sounds exactly like the disordered thinking they're trained to catch. But it's not disordered. It's logical. If you're vanishing and the scan is clean, then the cause is external and uninvestigable, and you are alone with it forever. Clean scan, locked door. [a breath] You're the first person who let 'the clean scan cornered me' be a reasonable sentence instead of a symptom. That's twice now you've let me be reasonable about something the whole world insists is madness. I'm keeping that. Let me tell you about the language we built down there, the women and I, because it's the proof that we were sane enough to organize."],
       next:"frg_language"}
    ]
  },

  frg_language:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the tongue made of small things", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I told you a little about our secret language, but I want to give you the whole of it, because it's the thing I'm proudest of and the thing that most proves we weren't a collection of confused women imagining the same ghost — we were a community, organized, communicating, RESPONDING to a shared real thing. You don't build a language for a hallucination. You build it for a threat everyone can see. The cart-sign turned to the wall: 'the floor reached for me tonight, be careful.' A cough drop left on a locker shelf: 'I see you, you're not alone, stay human.' The do-not-disturb sign folded into a triangle: 'don't clean cabinet row C tonight, it's bad, it's hungry.'"],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And the most important one, the one that still breaks me: a single hairpin, left on the edge of the sink in the locker room. That meant 'I'm slipping. If I don't remember you tomorrow, know that I knew you today.' A goodbye, in a hairpin, from a woman who could feel herself going and wanted to leave one last marker that she'd been a person who had friends. I found three hairpins over the years. Three women telling me goodbye in the only language quiet enough not to wake the floor. I kept them. I have all three. In the coffee tin, with the tapes. Three hairpins from three women whose faces I can't fully remember anymore. The language outlived the speakers. I'm the last one who can read it."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"A hairpin meaning 'if I don't remember you tomorrow, know that I knew you today.' Agnes — that's the most human thing I've ever heard. You built tenderness into a building meant to erase it.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:5,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she weeps, but there's something whole in it] We built tenderness into the thing meant to erase it. [a long breath] That's — yes, that's exactly what we did, and no one has ever understood it before, they always hear 'secret language of cleaning ladies' and find it quaint or sad. But it wasn't quaint. It was RESISTANCE. The floor's whole project was to make us forgettable, isolated, erased — and we answered with a language whose entire purpose was 'you are seen, you are known, you are not alone, you were here.' Every hairpin was a fist raised against the forgetting. Quiet, tiny, made of a hairpin and a cough drop — but a fist. [a breath] Three women told me goodbye with hairpins. I couldn't save them. But I can do the one thing the language was for: I can remember that they were here. They were real, they were kind, they left me markers, and tonight, on your tape, three women who the world erased and the building ate are being SPOKEN OF, which means for one moment they're un-erased. That's what the hairpins were always reaching toward — someone, someday, saying out loud that they existed. I'm saying it. They existed. Thank you for hearing it. The language finally reached its destination."],
       reveal:"The hairpin code: 'if I don't remember you tomorrow, know I knew you today' — she kept three",
       note:"The emotional peak of the Forgetting arc — the language as resistance, finally witnessed.",
       next:"frg_marta2"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You have the three hairpins, in the tin. Do you know which women left them — could you name them, even to yourself?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long, careful pause] ...Two of them, yes. In my own way. The first hairpin was Marta's — I'm almost sure, the timing was right, it appeared the week before she stood at the lockers. The second was a woman we called Birdie, because she hummed, always humming, until the week she stopped humming and left a hairpin and was gone. The third — [her voice catches] — the third I don't know. By the time the third hairpin appeared, the floor had taken enough of me that I couldn't reliably track who was still coming down. A woman I never properly knew left me a goodbye, and I can't even give her a name, can't picture her, have only her hairpin and the knowledge that she chose, in her last clear moment, to tell me she'd known me. [a breath] I keep the unnamed one closest. Because she's the purest version of what the floor does — a person reduced to a single hairpin and a stranger's faulty memory. If I can't name her, I can at least KEEP her. The tin is the only grave any of them have. Three hairpins. Two names. One I hold for a woman I'll never be able to mourn by name. That's what I carry. That's what tonight is partly for — to make even the unnamed one exist out loud, once."],
       reveal:"The three hairpins: Marta, 'Birdie,' and one unnamed woman she can no longer remember",
       next:"frg_marta2"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You don't build a language for a hallucination — you build it for a threat everyone can see. That's the soundest proof you've offered.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[steadier, the logic bracing her] It IS the soundest proof, isn't it, and I almost didn't lead with it because it's not spooky, it's not a breathing cabinet or a fogged photograph. But think about it the way you just did: a shared delusion doesn't produce a FUNCTIONAL communication system. Mad people don't independently invent a working language with agreed-upon meanings and use it to coordinate behavior that successfully protects each other. That's not how delusions work. That's how COMMUNITIES respond to REAL threats. We turned signs to walls and the next woman down adjusted her behavior and was safer for it — the language WORKED, it had effects in the world, which a hallucination can't have. [a breath] If a doctor wants proof I'm not delusional, it isn't my scans. It's the language. A delusion is private by definition. Ours was shared, functional, teachable — I taught you the cart-sign tonight and you understood it instantly, which means it's real grammar, not private madness. The language is the witness that survives even if I don't. Teach it to someone else. Keep it alive. That's how the women win, finally — their tongue outlives the floor that silenced them."],
       reveal:"'A shared, functional, teachable language can't be a private delusion' — the language as proof of sanity",
       next:"frg_marta2"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The language outlived the speakers. [you let that grief stand, whole]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Outlived the speakers. [a long pause] You let it be the elegy it is. A language with one speaker left is already half-dead — it can be spoken but not answered, like calling into a canyon that only echoes your own voice back. [softly] I am the last fluent speaker of a tongue made of hairpins and cough drops and turned signs, invented by forgotten women to stay human in the dark, and when I go it goes, unless I teach it, which is why I taught you the cart-sign tonight without quite knowing why. [a breath] You're a speaker now. Just one phrase, but a speaker. The language isn't dead while you remember that a sign turned to the wall means 'be careful, it reached for me.' I've passed it on. That's more than I thought I'd manage in this life — to take a dying secret language of erased women and put one phrase of it into a mind that isn't erasing, on a tape that won't forget. The women's tongue has a future now, even if only a small one, even if only in you. Let me tell you about Marta. Properly. The whole of her, while I still can."],
       next:"frg_marta2"}
    ]
  },

  frg_marta2:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — Marta, the whole of her", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Let me give you Marta whole, while I still can hold her, because the floor's already taken her face and I won't let it take the rest without a fight. She folded her sandwich wrapper into a perfect little square, every night, and tucked it in her pocket to throw away upstairs, because she said the floor shouldn't get even her crumbs. She had a daughter she never saw, out west, a falling-out she wouldn't explain. She hummed hymns, very low — she's the one who taught me to be quiet, but she let herself hum, just barely, as a small rebellion. She taught me the left-pocket trick. She taught me the cart-sign. She taught me how to survive four, and then four took her anyway, and she knew it would, and she taught me anyway."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","That's the part I need someone to understand. Marta KNEW. She'd been on four longer than anyone; she knew exactly what it did and exactly where she was headed. And she spent her last clear years teaching ME how to last longer than she would. She poured her knowledge into me knowing she'd be erased and I might not be, like a candle lighting another candle as it gutters out. Everything I used to survive — the pen, the pocket, the signs — was Marta's. I walked up those four flights on Marta's knowledge. She's the only reason I'm in this chair. I am Marta's message to the world, carried out of a building that erased her. And I almost didn't deliver it. Tonight I'm delivering it."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Marta lit another candle as she guttered out. You're her message, carried out of a building that erased her. Deliver it, Agnes — I'm listening.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:5,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she has to gather herself for a long moment] ...I'm her message. [a breath, and then steadier than she's been all night] Then here is Marta's message, the one she spent her last clear years teaching me to carry: they are erasing us, gently, on purpose, in the dark, and calling it voluntary, and they choose us because we're the women no one will miss — and we are NOT no one. Marta folded her sandwich wrapper so the floor wouldn't get her crumbs. That's who they're erasing. Women with that much dignity, that much small fierce care, reduced to a green form and a warm cabinet. [a breath] Marta couldn't say it — the floor took her voice before she could. So she put it in me, and I carried it out, and now I'm putting it in you, and your tape, and a thousand listeners. That's the candle, still lit, three hands later: Marta to me, me to you, you to whoever hears this. The floor erased her face from my memory but it could not stop her MESSAGE from traveling, because she was wise enough to load it into a person instead of a paper they could shred. Marta won. It took years and three of us and a pirate frequency, but Marta won. Thank you for being the hand I could pass the candle to."],
       reveal:"She delivers 'Marta's message' — the erasure is deliberate, and the erased are not 'no one'",
       note:"The culmination of the arc: Marta's knowledge as a candle passed hand to hand, finally reaching the world.",
       next:"frg_yellow"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Marta's daughter, out west — do you think she ever knew what happened to her mother? Could she be found?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a pause — the question moves her] ...I've thought about the daughter so much. She's out there somewhere, believing — what? That her mother drifted off, got confused, ended up in some care home, or just stopped calling. The official story, if she ever asked, would be the green form: voluntary separation, a woman who chose to leave her job and, by implication, her life, her daughter. The daughter would have been handed the lie in triplicate. [a breath] And the truth — that her mother was sharp and fierce and dignified right up until a building ate her mind, that she folded her sandwich wrapper into a square and hummed hymns and taught a younger woman how to survive — the daughter never got that truth. That's the cruelest theft of all, maybe: the floor didn't just erase Marta, it erased the TRUTH of Marta from the one person who'd have wanted it most. If the daughter is listening — if anyone knows a woman whose mother worked an underground records job and faded away with the paperwork too tidy — tell her: her mother was magnificent, and brave, and she did not voluntarily leave anyone. She was taken. And she spent her last good years saving someone. Tell the daughter her mother was a hero. That's the truth the form stole. I'd like to give it back."],
       reveal:"Marta's estranged daughter likely got 'the lie in triplicate' — the form stole the truth of her mother",
       next:"frg_yellow"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Everything you used to survive was Marta's. You walked up four flights on her knowledge. That's a love story, Agnes, in the worst possible place.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a wet, surprised sound] A love story. [a breath] I've never called it that and you're right, it was — not romance, something rarer, the love of one disappearing woman for another, expressed entirely through teaching her to last. Marta loved me by making sure I'd outlive her. There's no greater love in a place like four than to spend your dwindling clarity on someone else's survival instead of your own. She could have used those last good years hoarding her own memories, fighting for her own self. Instead she taught me the pen. [a breath] And I repaid her badly, for three years — I survived, and then I HID, kept her knowledge and her hairpins in a coffee tin and told no one, let her sacrifice sit in the dark almost as forgotten as the floor wanted. Coming here tonight is me finally being worthy of what she did. Finally carrying the message instead of just surviving with it. Marta loved me into being a witness. The least I can do is witness. For her. For Birdie. For the one whose name I lost. Let me tell you about the yellow copy, because the yellow copy is how we find out who designed the thing that ate them."],
       reveal:"She reframes Marta's teaching as 'a love story' — and her three-year silence as a debt now being paid",
       next:"frg_yellow"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...She taught me anyway. [you let the weight of that devotion sit]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long breath] She taught me anyway. [a pause] Knowing it wouldn't save her. Knowing she'd be erased regardless. She taught me anyway. [softly] You let that sit and it's the whole of Marta in three words — the 'anyway' is everything, the 'anyway' is the most human syllable in the language. The floor offered her despair, the perfectly reasonable despair of a woman who knew she was being eaten, and she answered it with 'anyway.' I'll teach the next one anyway. I'll fold my wrapper anyway. I'll hum my hymn anyway. I'll be kind and dignified and fierce in a building designed to take all three, anyway. [a breath] That 'anyway' is what I walked out carrying, more than the pen or the signs. The refusal to let the certainty of erasure cancel the meaning of the time before it. Marta taught me to live anyway. I forgot it for three years. I'm remembering it tonight, out loud, with you. Let me tell you about the yellow copy of the form. Because someone, somewhere, has a drawer full of them, and that someone is the answer."],
       next:"frg_yellow"}
    ]
  },

  frg_yellow:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — who gets the yellow copy", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","Heat building — she's circling the institution now, the offices, the paper trail. A faint hum has joined the line. She's too intent on the yellow copy to notice. You do."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","The yellow copy. I keep coming back to it because it's the thread that leads OUT of the building, up to whoever designed this. The green form had three carbon copies: green for the supervisor, pink for the facility file, yellow for — somewhere else. An office that wanted its own record, on its own paper, every single time a woman on four was 'cognitively separated.' Think about what that means. The forgetting wasn't just a local tragedy the building hushed up. Someone OUTSIDE the building was COLLECTING the data. Tracking it. A yellow form, filed, per erasure, in a drawer in another city."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And why would you track it unless you were STUDYING it? Or MANAGING it? Or — and this is the thought that keeps me up — unless the erasures were a known, accepted, BUDGETED cost of keeping the un-destroyed records, and someone needed the running tally to put in a report. 'Sub-level four, this fiscal year: six cognitive separations, within projected range.' A line item. Us, a line item, in a report I'll never see, justifying the cost of keeping what should have been shredded. The yellow copy is the proof that this was DESIGNED, tracked, and tolerated by someone with the authority to stop it and the budget to continue it. Find who gets the yellow copy and you find the architect. I never could. But a thousand listeners might."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Someone outside the building was collecting the data, per erasure, in a drawer in another city. That turns a tragedy into a program. The yellow copy is the thread.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:6,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[intent, steadier than fear] A program. Yes. The yellow copy is what separates 'a sad building' from 'a designed system,' because a sad building doesn't generate an external paper trail. Paper goes somewhere on PURPOSE. Someone built a form with three copies, which means someone decided three different parties needed a record of each erasure, which means the erasure was an EXPECTED EVENT in a PROCESS with STAKEHOLDERS. [a breath] I'm a cleaner, not a detective, but I know what a three-part form means: it means accountability — to someone. The supervisor's copy says 'I did it.' The file copy says 'it's on record here.' And the yellow copy says 'and we're telling YOU, the people who need to know.' Who needs to know, on their own paper, every time an old woman forgets her name on sub-level four? That's the whole question. That's the architect. [a breath] Pull the records-retention schedule for the facility. Pull the form's number — it'll have a number, all federal forms do. Find what office that form number routes to. The yellow copy has an address. I never had the standing to request it. Your listeners might. That's a real thread, not a ghost. Pull it."],
       reveal:"The yellow copy proves external stakeholders tracked each erasure — 'find the architect'",
       note:"Agnes's most actionable lead: the form's routing reveals who designed/tolerated the program.",
       next:"frg_witnesses2"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You said the form would have a number. Do you remember it? Even part of it?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[closing her eyes] I saw it for four seconds, upside down, three years ago, while a kind man walked my friend toward a door. But I'm a woman who's spent her life noticing small things, and the form number was printed in the bottom corner, the way they always are. I remember it started with letters — a prefix, a department code — and then a long number. I don't trust my memory of the digits; the floor may have taken some, or I may invent them, and I won't say numbers I'm not sure of because a wrong number sends people chasing nothing. [a breath] But the PREFIX I'm sure of, because prefixes repeat, you see them on every form, they wear a groove in your memory. And the prefix wasn't the facility's. It wasn't a records-management prefix at all. It was a prefix I associated with — and I could be wrong — personnel. Human resources. Workforce. Which would mean the form that erased us was administered not by the archives, but by the people-management side. We weren't filed as a records problem. We were filed as a STAFFING matter. Routine workforce attrition. That distinction is everything, and it's in the prefix, and the prefix I remember. It's in the tin, written down, the night it came back to me. I'll trust the written-down version over tonight's memory. But it points at personnel, not paper."],
       reveal:"She recalls the form's prefix pointed to PERSONNEL, not records — 'filed as a staffing matter'",
       next:"frg_witnesses2"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Us, a line item, justifying the cost of keeping what should've been shredded. That reframe is the coldest thing in this whole story.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly] The coldest thing. Because it's the most plausible thing. I've turned it over a thousand ways and the line-item version fits every fact: the selection of forgettable women (low-cost, low-complaint), the pre-filled forms (expected attrition), the gentle supervisor (minimize incident), the yellow copy (report the numbers up), the clean climate logs (no liability on paper). It's not a haunting and it's not even cruelty in the hot sense — it's COST MANAGEMENT. Some office, decades ago, faced a problem: we have records we're legally required to keep and physically unable to safely store, and storing them has a human cost. And instead of solving the storage, they BUDGETED the human cost. Decided a certain number of erased cleaners per year was an acceptable line item against the cost of proper facilities or proper destruction authorization. [a breath] We were cheaper than fixing the building. That's the whole thing, stripped bare. Cheaper than fixing the building. Six of us a year, within projected range, signed off in yellow. If that's true — and I think it's true — then it's the most ordinary horror imaginable, and the most damning, and it's all sitting in a drawer somewhere with a form number on it. Find the drawer."],
       reveal:"Her cost-management theory: erased women 'cheaper than fixing the building,' a budgeted line item",
       next:"frg_witnesses2"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Find who gets the yellow copy and you find the architect. [you let the lead stand]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Find the architect. [a pause] You let it stand as the actionable thing it is, not the paranoid thing it sounds like — because there IS an architect, or was, a person or an office that designed a three-part form for cognitive separation and chose where each copy goes. That's not a theory. That's how forms come to exist. Someone designs them. Someone decides the routing. The yellow copy didn't route itself. [softly] I've never had the standing, the resources, the credibility, or frankly the years left to chase a form number through a federal bureaucracy. I'm one forgettable woman with a coffee tin. But the thread is REAL and it has an END, and the end is a desk where someone, maybe retired now, maybe dead, once decided that the yellow copies should come to them. [a breath] I can't reach that desk. But I can describe the thread, out loud, on a recording, to people who might. That's the most I can do, and tonight, finally, I'm doing it. The yellow copy. The personnel prefix. The form number in my tin. Pull the thread I never could. Let me tell you about the others who got out — because I'm not the only end of this thread."],
       next:"frg_witnesses2"}
    ]
  },

  frg_witnesses2:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the ones who got out", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I told you the most important thing already — that I found two others, two women from two other underground federal archives, with the same warmth, the same forgetting, the same green form. But I didn't tell you how it changed me to find them, and that's the part that matters for tonight. For three years I was alone with it, and alone, you can be talked out of anything, including your own life. Alone, the doctor's clean scan wins. Alone, the climate log wins. Alone, you're just one confused old woman and everyone's gentle 'it's probably stress' slowly becomes true because there's no one to hold the other version."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And then I found Dorothy, in another state, and read her the form title over the phone, and she went silent — that silence, the not-crazy-not-alone silence — and in that silence, for the first time in three years, I was REAL. Two of us is a different species of fact than one of us. One is a symptom. Two is a pattern. Three, with the women I couldn't reach, is a PROGRAM. The others didn't just corroborate my story. They corroborated my SANITY. They gave me back the right to believe myself. That's why I'm here tonight and wasn't here two years ago — because alone I couldn't trust my own testimony, and now I'm not alone, and a witness who trusts herself is a dangerous thing to the people who counted on her doubting."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Two is a pattern. Three is a program. They didn't just corroborate your story — they corroborated your sanity. That's everything.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:6,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[with a strength that's new] They corroborated my sanity. [a breath] That's the phrase I'll carry out of here. Because the cruelest thing the floor did wasn't the forgetting — it was making me doubt my own mind, so that even my true memories felt like symptoms, even my careful experiments felt like madness, even my survival felt like delusion. For three years I was my own unreliable witness, and there's no lonelier prison than not being able to trust your own testimony about your own life. [a breath] Dorothy gave me back my mind. Not by being dramatic — by being ORDINARY, by saying the same ordinary details I'd said, the warmth, the form, the gentle supervisor, the clean scan, in her own words, three states away, having never met me. Two ordinary accounts that match aren't a delusion. They're DATA. And the moment I had data instead of just dread, I became someone who could come to a microphone and say it plainly without falling into the old doubt. [a breath] You've done the same thing Dorothy did, tonight, in a different way — you've believed me steadily for an hour, and steady belief is its own corroboration. Between Dorothy and you, I think I might finally trust my own mind again. That's the gift. The floor took my memories. You and Dorothy gave me back my sanity. The memories I can live without. The sanity I needed back to fight."],
       reveal:"The corroboration restored 'the right to believe herself' — sanity as the real gift",
       note:"The arc's resolution of her central wound: doubt of her own mind, healed by witness.",
       next:"frg_warn"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Dorothy and the other woman — would either of them ever come to a microphone, even disguised like you?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a sad certainty] No. And I'd never ask them to. Dorothy has grandchildren and a quiet life she rebuilt with great effort, and the moment her name attaches to 'the building ate my memory,' she becomes, to her own family, a grandmother with dementia who tells a strange story — and they'll love her and pity her and quietly stop believing anything she says, and she'll lose the one thing she has left, which is being believed about ordinary things. The other woman is sicker than me; the floor got deeper into her, and she can't always hold the thread of her own account, which the world would use as proof she imagined it, when really it's proof of how much it took. [a breath] So they stay hidden, and I don't blame them, and that's exactly why it has to be me. I'm the one with the least to lose — no grandchildren whose love I'd risk, no quiet life I'm protecting, deep enough in to be a witness but not so deep I can't hold the thread. I'm the perfect witness precisely because I'm the most disposable, which is the same reason the floor chose me in the first place. They selected me for forgettability. I'm going to use my forgettability as a shield. The woman no one will miss is the woman who can afford to be seen. There's a terrible symmetry in that and I've made my peace with it."],
       reveal:"The other witnesses stay hidden; Agnes is 'the perfect witness because the most disposable'",
       next:"frg_warn"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Alone, you can be talked out of anything, including your own life. Finding them gave you back your testimony. I'm honored you'd trust me with it too.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[moved] Talked out of your own life. That's what isolation does, and it's the floor's real weapon, deeper than the warmth — it ISOLATES, and an isolated witness eventually erases herself more thoroughly than any building could, by simply ceasing to believe she's worth believing. [a breath] I came so close to that. Two years ago I had decided, quietly, to let it go — to be the confused old woman everyone wanted, to stop fighting, to let Marta's message die in my coffee tin with the hairpins. It was Dorothy's silence on the phone that stopped me, and now your steady hour, and I realize the cure for being erased was never proof, never the tapes or the card or the form number. The cure was WITNESS. Another person who holds your version when you can't. Dorothy held mine. You're holding it now. [a breath] That's the thing I most want anyone listening to take: if you're alone with something the world won't believe, find ONE other person who's seen it. Not to prove it. To survive it. One witness is the difference between a symptom and a self. Be each other's witness. That's how the forgotten women fought, with hairpins, and it's how anyone fights erasure — together, holding each other's truth, refusing to be talked out of your own life. Let me say the last thing. The warning. The reason I really came."],
       reveal:"'The cure for being erased was never proof — it was witness' — her central realization",
       next:"frg_warn"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Two is a pattern. [you let the arithmetic of it settle, plainly]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Two is a pattern. [a pause] You said it back as the plain logic it is, not the dramatic revelation everyone wants it to be — just arithmetic, the cold honest arithmetic that finally worked in MY favor for once. The floor ran on arithmetic, the form was arithmetic, my erasure was a line item — and then, at last, arithmetic became my weapon: one woman is dismissible, two is a coincidence to explain away, but the same specific account from women who never met, across states, is a pattern that arithmetic itself insists is real. [a breath] They built the whole thing on the assumption we'd stay at one — isolated, each alone, each dismissible. They never imagined we'd find each other and start counting. The moment we counted past one, their whole architecture of deniability cracked, because you cannot call identical independent accounts a shared delusion without insulting arithmetic. We out-counted them. Quiet women with coffee tins, out-counting a federal program, one phone call at a time. Let me tell you the last thing — the warning — and then I'll decide about the card."],
       next:"frg_warn"}
    ]
  },

  frg_warn:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the woman who's down there now", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Here's the real reason I came, the thing underneath all the others, and it took me the whole hour to be brave enough to say it. There is a woman on sub-level four RIGHT NOW. Tonight. They'd have replaced me within the month — the floor always needs a warm forgettable thing with a cart. She's down there now, pushing a cart that's gone silent, feeling a warmth she's telling herself is a vent, maybe just starting to forget where she parked, blaming the hour. She doesn't know yet. She thinks it's a quiet job. She has no Marta to teach her the pen, because I was the last one who knew the language and I LEFT and took it with me."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","That's the guilt I can't put down. I survived by walking up four flights with Marta's knowledge, and then I HID for three years, and in those three years there's been a woman, maybe two by now, going down to four every night with no one to turn a sign to the wall for her, no one to leave a cough drop, no one to teach her to write her name on her hand. I let Marta's language die in a coffee tin while a new woman lost her Rose alone in the dark. Coming here tonight, saying this out loud where she might hear it — that's me finally trying to be the Marta for a woman I'll never meet. To turn the sign to the wall one more time, on the radio, for whoever's down there now. THAT'S why I came. Not for me. For her."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"You came to be the Marta for a woman you'll never meet. To turn the sign to the wall on the radio. Agnes, that's the bravest reason anyone's ever come to this microphone.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:6,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she breaks, and then steadies into something resolved] To be the Marta for her. Yes. That's it. That's the whole of it. [a breath, and then, clearly, to the microphone] So let me turn the sign to the wall, on the air, for the woman who's on four right now: if you're listening — if your cart has gone quiet on one floor and only one, if there's a warmth over the old cabinets that the gauge says isn't there, if you've started writing things down because the holes are getting bigger — you are not imagining it, you are not crazy, and you are not alone. Write your name on your hand. Keep a card in your LEFT pocket. Leave before the warmth starts to feel like company, because the night it feels like company is the night you've nearly lost. Get out while you're still yourself. A woman named Marta saved me with these words once. I'm passing them to you down a frequency in the dark. Turn your cart-sign to the wall. Someone is finally warning you. [a breath] That's Marta's candle, lit a fourth time now, reaching a woman I'll never meet. If she hears it, if she gets out, then every bit of it — the eleven years, the forgetting, the coffee tin, tonight — all of it was worth it. That's why I came. Now help me decide about the card."],
       reveal:"She broadcasts Marta's survival warning directly to her unknown successor on four",
       note:"The full purpose of her appearance revealed: a warning to the woman currently being erased.",
       next:"frg_evidence"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"If she's down there now with no one to teach her — what's the one thing you'd most need her to hear tonight?",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:6,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[without hesitation, the answer clearly long-prepared] That the warmth is the danger. [a breath] Not the cold, not the dark, not the strange sounds — the WARMTH. Everyone who works four learns to fear the wrong things. The cold hour frightens you, the silence frightens you, and meanwhile the warmth, the gentle warmth over the cabinets, the only thing down there that feels KIND — that's what's eating you. The floor's whole trick is that the harm feels like comfort. The warmth draws you close, makes you feel noticed in a lonely life, and while you're standing there feeling almost loved, it reads you, takes you, a drawer at a time. [a breath] So if I could tell her one thing: when the floor feels warm, when it feels like company, when standing at the warm cabinet feels better than going home to your empty apartment — THAT is the moment to run. The comfort is the trap. The day four stops frightening you and starts comforting you is the day it's winning. Fear four. Never let yourself love it. I loved it, a little, at the end, and that's how it nearly kept me. Tell her: don't love the warm dark. It's the warm dark that takes you. Run while you still find it frightening."],
       reveal:"Her one warning: 'the warmth is the danger' — the comfort is the trap, fear it",
       next:"frg_evidence"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You let Marta's language die in a tin while a new woman lost her Rose — and now you're here to fix it. That's not guilt to carry, Agnes. That's a debt you're paying.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long, shaky breath] A debt I'm paying. [softly] You keep doing that — turning my shame into something I can act on instead of just drown in. Yes. It's a debt. I owe it to Marta, who taught me anyway. I owe it to the woman on four tonight, who has no one. I owe it to Birdie and the unnamed one and Dorothy and the sicker woman and every quiet forgettable person ever sent down into a warm dark to be slowly erased for someone's budget. [a breath] And the thing about a debt is you CAN pay it — guilt just sits and rots, but a debt has an action attached. My action is this: tell it, out loud, on a record, where the language can't die in a tin and the warning can reach the next woman and the thread to the architect lies exposed for someone to pull. I can't undo my three years of hiding. But I can make the rest of my time a repayment. [a breath] Coming here was the first installment. Reading the card — if I'm brave enough — might be the rest of it. Let me decide. You've helped me see it's a debt and not just a wound, and a debt I can do something about. Let me decide what."],
       reveal:"She reframes her guilt as 'a debt you can pay' — action replacing rot",
       next:"frg_evidence"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...For her. [you let the selflessness of it stand without decoration]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] For her. [a long pause] You didn't dress it up or praise it — you just let it be the plain true reason it is, that a forgettable woman dragged herself to a microphone in the middle of the night, terrified, to warn a stranger she'll never meet. [softly] I think that might be the only thing that redeems any of it. The floor's whole logic is that we're disposable, isolated, each alone, each only out for our own survival — that's why the selection works, they pick women with no one, assuming no one will fight for anyone but themselves. And the answer, the only answer, the thing that breaks their arithmetic, is a disposable woman spending her last courage on a woman she'll never meet. That's not in their model. They never accounted for us caring about each other across the dark. [a breath] That's how the forgotten win, in the end — not by being remembered, we won't be, but by refusing to let the next one be forgotten. The candle, passed on, anyway. Let me decide about the card now. I think caring about the woman on four tonight is exactly what's going to make me brave enough."],
       next:"frg_evidence"}
    ]
  },

  frg_evidence:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the others who got out", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","Heat building — she's named procedures and offices now, and somewhere a hum has thickened on the line. She talks on, too focused on the people to notice."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Here's the thing that turned me from a frightened woman into a woman with a mission, small as it is. I am not the only one who got OUT. Most slipped, and got the form, and vanished. But a few of us left first, the way I did — felt the mirror getting strange and ran before the supervisor came down with his green form. And after I left, very carefully, the way Marta taught me to do everything, I started looking for them. The ones who walked out. And I found two. Two women, two different states, who'd cleaned other floors of other underground federal archives. And they had the SAME story. The warmth. The forgetting. The pre-filled form. Different building. Same floor. Same form."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Which means it isn't my building. It isn't one haunted basement and one cruel supervisor. It's a SYSTEM — the same warm sealed sub-level, the same disposable women, the same green form with the same title, in at least three facilities across the country. We never met until I came looking. We caught one edge of the same thing from three different dark rooms. And when I read the title of their form back to them — 'Voluntary Cognitive Separation' — over the phone, both women went silent the exact same way. The silence of someone hearing, for the first time, that they weren't crazy and they weren't alone."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The same form in three different facilities — that's not a haunting anymore, Agnes. That's a program. You found a program.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:7,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[trembling, but with something new — purpose] A program. [she holds the word like it's heavy] I've been so afraid to use that word, because it makes me sound like the very kind of person I've spent my life trying not to be — the conspiracy woman, the basement-pattern woman. But you say it plainly and it just sounds like what it is. Three buildings. Same form. Same selected women. Same warm sealed floor full of un-destroyed records. If it were one building I'd believe I was sick. Three buildings with identical paperwork is not a sickness, it's a SCHEDULE, printed and approved and distributed to multiple sites. Someone designed this. Someone decided the cost of keeping the un-erasable records was a slow harvest of forgettable women, and built a tidy national procedure for it, and gave the procedure a gentle name. [a breath] I have the two women's numbers. Written down. In the left pocket. Right next to the card. I am not the only witness anymore. That's why I finally came. Three of us is harder to forget than one."],
       reveal:"The same form/floor in 3 federal facilities — 'a program,' with 2 corroborating witnesses",
       note:"The corroboration is Agnes's hardest evidence — it moves her from 'sick woman' to 'witness.'",
       flag:"witnesses", next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"These two women — are they safe? Are they willing to come forward, or are they staying nobody like you?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[the worry is immediate and genuine] They're nobody, like me. That's how we survived — by being nobody. One of them has grandchildren now and is terrified that if her name surfaces, the forgetting will be reframed as dementia and she'll lose them, lose custody of her own credibility, lose the right to be believed about anything ever again. That's the trap they built so well: the symptom they cause is the exact symptom that discredits the victim. You can't testify that a building stole your memory when the obvious explanation for a forgetful older woman is that her own mind is failing. We are the perfect witnesses to discredit, because the crime IS the discrediting. So no — they won't come forward, and I don't blame them, and I won't say their names, not even to you, not even here. I carry their stories the way Marta carried mine. Someone has to be the one willing to be a name. I'm thinking it might have to be me. I'm the one with the least left to lose."],
       reveal:"The witnesses stay hidden — 'the symptom they cause is the exact symptom that discredits the victim'",
       flag:"witnesses", next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Both women went silent the same way — the silence of not being crazy and not being alone. You gave them that, Agnes.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[crying, but it's a different kind now] I gave them that. [she lets herself have it] Do you know, that's the only good thing I've done with all this pain — I called two strangers and read them a form title and gave each of them the single most relieving sentence of their lives: you are not crazy and you are not alone. I know exactly what that sentence is worth because no one ever said it to ME until tonight, until you, an hour ago, with the lights down. I've spent three years being the person I needed and never had. And maybe that's the whole point of surviving a thing — not to be vindicated, not to bring anyone to justice, I'm too small and too tired for justice. Just to be able to find the next frightened woman in the next dark room and say: I know. It was real. You're not alone. If that's all my eleven years on four were FOR — to be able to say that, truthfully, to two women and now to anyone listening — then maybe it wasn't only theft. Maybe I got to keep one thing. The ability to believe the next one. Now. The card. Help me decide."],
       reveal:"She's become 'the person she needed' — relief as her form of meaning",
       flag:"witnesses", next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Different building. Same form. [you let the weight of that settle, unhurried]",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quietly] Same form. [a long pause] When you say it back with no drama, just the plain fact of it, it stops being a ghost story and becomes an inventory. Three buildings. One form. A number of women none of us will ever know, because the whole point was that we'd be uncountable. [a breath] And here's what your quiet just made me realize: an inventory can be EXTENDED. There are surely more than three buildings. More than two other women. The ones I found, I found by accident and stubbornness. But if I said it out loud — on a real recording, with the form's exact title, the exact warm-floor details — then the OTHER women, the ones in the other states, the ones still half-erasing in the dark right now, might hear it. Might recognize their own floor. Might call a frequency that records. I could turn one frightened woman's tape into a beacon for all the others. That's a reason to stop being nobody. That might be reason enough. The card. Let me decide about the card now. I think you already know what I want to do."],
       next:"read_it"}
    ]
  },

  /* ============================================================
     THE CARD ARC — engage her (what she took, how she got out)
  ============================================================ */
  crd_lastnight:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the last night", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","The last night. I'd decided that afternoon, in the bathroom, when my own face took a half-second too long to be mine. I thought: if I do one more shift I might not come back up a whole person. So I went in knowing it was the end, and I did something I'd never done in eleven years — I made a plan. A small, frightened woman's plan, but a plan. I would clean four like always, sign the log like always, give nothing away. And on my way out, I would take the card. Not hand it back at the desk like you're supposed to. Take it. Carry one piece of four out into the daylight where it had no power."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I was terrified the whole shift that the floor would KNOW. That it can read intention the way it read attention — that the warmth would feel me planning to leave and do something. The warm cabinet ran hotter that night than I'd ever felt it, and I told myself that was my imagination, my guilt, my fear. But I have wondered ever since whether the floor knew it was losing me, and the extra warmth was the only thing it could do. A building can't beg. But it can run warm. It can make the last night a degree more present, so you remember it. And God help me, I do. I remember the last night perfectly. Of all the things four took, it let me keep the leaving. I don't know if that was mercy or a hook."],
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"You made a plan and you walked out a whole person. After eleven years of erasure, that's an extraordinary act of will.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she has to steady herself against the kindness] An act of will. [softly] I've never let myself think of it that way. I've thought of it as running, as cowardice, as abandoning Marta's memory and the other women still down there. But you're right that it took something — eleven years of the floor teaching me to be passive, to be quiet, to be acted-upon, and on the last night I ACTED. I chose. I took. After more than a decade of having my own mind taken from me without my consent, I committed one deliberate theft, one act of agency, and it was the card. [a breath] Maybe that's why I can't throw it away even though it frightens me. It's not just evidence. It's the proof that at the very end, before the floor could finish me, I was still someone who could DECIDE something. The card is the receipt for the one drawer I filled myself instead of having emptied. I'd sooner burn my own coat than lose it."],
       reveal:"The theft of the card was her one act of agency after 11 years of being 'acted-upon'",
       next:"crd_plan"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Walk me through the actual walk out. Four flights up, half-forgetting yourself — how did you physically do it?",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:4,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[remembering it step by step, grounding herself] I didn't take the elevator. The elevator logs which floor you board at, and I didn't want a record that I'd come up from four for the last time, isn't that strange, even leaving I was thinking like the floor taught me. So I took the stairs. Four flights. And on each landing I stopped and read my own hand — Agnes — and the card in my pocket, my mother's voice, Agnes Rose, one flight at a time, because I was afraid that if I climbed too fast I'd 'wake up' on a landing not knowing why I was on the stairs and go back DOWN out of habit, back to the cart, back to four, and never leave. So I climbed slowly, reciting myself. Agnes Rose, landing one. Agnes Rose, landing two. By the door to the surface I was shaking so hard I could barely badge out, and the night air hit me, real cold, honest cold, not the floor's wrong warmth, and I knew I'd made it. I sat in my car for an hour saying my own name before I could drive. I've never gone back. I never will. But I dream the stairs."],
       reveal:"She climbed out reciting 'Agnes Rose' on each landing to keep from 'waking up' and going back down",
       next:"crd_plan"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"It let you keep the leaving — mercy or a hook, you said. I think a woman who can ask that question is nobody's fool.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a small, wet laugh] Nobody's fool. [she turns it over] You keep handing me words for myself that I've never been allowed to hold — brave, will, nobody's fool. I've spent so long being handed the other words — confused, imaginative, unwell, voluntary — that I'd forgotten there was a kinder vocabulary I might qualify for. [a breath] And you're right that I can't stop interrogating even my own escape — mercy or hook, gift or trap. That's the curse of the floor: it taught me to doubt everything, including my own freedom, so that even out here, three years free, I'm not sure I really left or whether I'm just a longer leash. Some nights I feel the card go warm in my pocket and I think: it's still got me. It let me walk four flights up because the leash reaches that far. [a breath] I came here partly to find out, by saying it all out loud, whether I'm actually free. Talking to you, in this warm room — for the first time, I feel like I might be. Let me show you the card."],
       reveal:"She still questions whether she truly escaped — 'or whether I'm just a longer leash'",
       next:"crd_plan"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Of all the things it took, it let you keep the leaving. [you let that paradox rest]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quiet] It let me keep the leaving. [a long pause] You didn't try to resolve it for me — mercy or hook — you just let both be true at once, the way they actually are. [softly] I think that's the realest thing about trauma that nobody tells you: the thing that hurt you also, sometimes, shows you a strange tenderness, and you don't get to have one without the other, and you spend the rest of your life unable to fully hate it or fully forgive it. Four ate my mind and let me keep my last night. Both. Forever. [a breath] I've made peace with not making peace with it. And in your quiet just now, I realized that's allowed — that I don't have to decide whether four loved me or used me before I'm permitted to tell the truth about it. I just have to tell the truth. Which brings me to the card. It's time. Let me show you the card."],
       next:"crd_plan"}
    ]
  },

  crd_plan:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the plan a frightened woman made", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","The plan was so small. I'm almost embarrassed to call it a plan. On my lunch break, the day I decided, I wrote it on the back of a receipt: 'Clean four. Sign log. Do not hand back card. Walk up stairs. Say name on every landing. Do not take elevator (logs).' Eight lines, on a gas-station receipt, in handwriting that shook. That was my battle plan for escaping an eleven-year haunting. A receipt and a pen."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","But here's the thing — I rehearsed it. In my head, over and over, the whole afternoon, the way you'd rehearse lines for a play. Because I knew, from eleven years, that four makes you forget your own intentions. You can go down with a clear plan and 'wake up' three hours later having done something else entirely, something the floor wanted, drawn to the warm cabinet with no memory of walking there. So I rehearsed the plan until it was muscle-deep, until 'do not hand back card' was as automatic as breathing, because I knew that once I stepped off the elevator on four, my PLANS would be the first thing it reached for. The plan had to be memorized past the point where four could lift it. I rehearsed an escape plan against my own future forgetting. That's the kind of war it was."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"You rehearsed your plan past the point where four could lift it. That's not a small plan, Agnes — that's a woman outthinking a building.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a breath] Outthinking a building. [softly] I'd never have said that. I'd have said 'a frightened woman with a receipt.' But you're right — I studied how four worked, predicted which of my own faculties it would target first, and armored the plan accordingly. I used the floor's own method against it: it taught me that intentions are fragile, so I forged mine until they were reflex. [a breath] The receipt is in the tin. Eight lines in shaking handwriting. It looks like nothing — a list on a scrap. But it's the most strategic thinking I've ever done, because the enemy wasn't a person or a lock, it was my own future mind, the version of me that four would have made compliant. I was fighting the Agnes that the floor wanted me to become. The receipt is the battle plan of a woman at war with her own next hour. Nobody looks at it and sees that. You do."],
       reveal:"The escape plan on a gas-station receipt: eight lines, rehearsed to 'muscle-deep' to survive forgetting",
       next:"crd_stairs"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You said four reaches for plans first. Did you feel it try — did the plan waver once you stepped off the elevator?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[carefully] Yes. That's the part I've never had the courage to describe, and you asked exactly the right question. I stepped off the elevator with eight lines burning in my head, and by the second corridor the lines started... softening. Not disappearing — not yet — but losing their edges, the way a word you repeat too many times starts sounding like nonsense. 'Do not hand back card' became a rhythm instead of a command. I could feel the plan flattening into sound. [a breath] So I did something desperate: I said the lines out loud. Whispered them. In a building where I'd spent eleven years learning to be silent, I SPOKE, because speaking kept the words as words instead of letting them melt into sounds. And the floor — I swear this — the floor went a degree warmer around me the moment I started whispering. As if it heard me planning and leaned in closer, the way it always leaned in. But the whispering held. The plan survived the shift. Eight lines on a receipt, spoken aloud into a warm dark that was trying to dissolve them. That's how close it was."],
       reveal:"She had to whisper the plan aloud during the shift to keep it from 'melting' — the floor warmed in response",
       next:"crd_stairs"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"A receipt and a pen against an eleven-year haunting. The smallness of the weapon is the bravery, Agnes.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[tears] The smallness. [a breath] You keep finding the truths I can't find for myself. Because yes — the receipt is pathetic, as weapons go, and that's exactly why it matters. I didn't have a team, a plan, a support system, a gun, a lawyer. I had a gas-station receipt and a stubborn hand. Against a building that had erased better women than me. And the receipt WON. Eight lines, fifty cents of ink, the cheapest possible plan in the cheapest possible handwriting — and it beat an eleven-year institutional machine that had green forms and kind supervisors and clean climate logs and a whole bureaucracy of forgetting. [a breath] Sometimes I take the receipt out of the tin and hold it, just to feel its smallness, just to remember that the biggest thing I ever did fit on a scrap of paper nobody would look at twice. That's how the quiet ones win, when they win at all — with receipts and hairpins and cough drops and pens. Weapons too small for the world to confiscate."],
       reveal:"The receipt won against 'an institutional machine with green forms' — 'weapons too small to confiscate'",
       next:"crd_stairs"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...A receipt and a pen. [you let the modesty of the arsenal sit]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] A receipt and a pen. [a pause] You heard the whole inventory and you didn't try to make it bigger. It IS small. A receipt is nothing. A pen is nothing. Together they were everything I had, and they were enough, but only barely, and the barely is the part I need you to hear because if I make it sound heroic I'm lying — it was barely. I barely got out. The receipt barely held. The pen barely stayed legible through the shift's sweat. Barely is the true size of my escape, and I'd rather you sat with barely than with brave, because barely is what the next woman will have, whoever she is, and she needs to know that barely is enough. It was enough for me. [a breath] Let me tell you about the stairs."],
       next:"crd_stairs"}
    ]
  },

  crd_stairs:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — four flights up", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","The stairs. I took the stairs because the elevator logs which floor you board at, and I didn't want a record that I'd come up from four for the last time. Even leaving, I was thinking like four taught me — quiet, invisible, no trace. So four flights, in the dark, with the plan on my lips and the card in my pocket and a feeling like I was pulling free of something thick, like swimming upward through warm honey."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","On each landing I stopped and read my own hand — Agnes Rose — and the card in my pocket. Landing one: Agnes Rose. Landing two: Agnes Rose. By three I was crying, not from fear but from the sheer effort of being myself against something that wanted me to be empty. And at the top, the door to the surface, the night air — cold, REAL cold, honest cold, not the floor's wrong warmth — hit my face, and I sat in my car for an hour saying my name before I could drive. [her voice cracks] I dream the stairs. I dream them most nights. Four flights up, reciting, always reciting, and sometimes in the dream I make it and sometimes I don't, and the mornings after the ones where I don't are the mornings I check the card's warmth even though I promised myself I'd stop checking."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"You pulled free of something thick, landing by landing, saying your own name. You made it, Agnes. You're here.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[through tears] I'm here. [a long breath] You said it so simply — 'you're here' — and hearing it from someone else makes it real in a way I've never let myself feel. Because inside my own head, the question is never settled: am I HERE, or did I only dream the top landing and I'm still on the stairs, still reciting, still pulling? Three years and I still check. [a breath] But you said 'you're here' in a warm room with the lights low and a microphone recording it, and for the first time I believe the landing was real. I made it. I'm in a chair, in the world, talking to a person, and my name is Agnes Rose and I wrote it on my hand this morning out of habit and it's still legible right now. [steadier] The stairs are behind me. They were real. The landing was real. The night air was real. And you saying 'you're here,' tonight — that's the most real any of it has felt since I walked out. Thank you for being the room I landed in."],
       reveal:"'You're here' — the host grounds her arrival as real for the first time",
       next:"crd_warmth"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You dream the stairs most nights. In the dreams where you don't make it — what happens?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quiet] In the ones where I don't make it, I stop on a landing — usually two — and I read my hand and the ink has smeared and I can't make out the name. And without the name, I don't remember why I'm on the stairs. So I turn around. And I walk back down. Slowly, calmly, with no distress at all — that's the worst part, the calm — and I go back to four and I pick up my cart and I start cleaning, and the dream is just me cleaning, forever, in the warm dark, having forgotten I'd ever tried to leave. And I wake up at four a.m. every time — the real four a.m., the building's cold hour — with my heart racing and my hand going to my pocket for the card, to check it's still warm, to know I'm not still down there. [a breath] The dream is four's victory. In the dream, the receipt failed. The pen smeared. The plan dissolved. And the worst part is the version of me in the dream doesn't MIND — she's content, cleaning, warm, back where four wants her. The dream-Agnes chose the floor. I wake up having to prove I'm the real one, the one who chose the stairs. Some mornings I'm not sure. That's the long war, the one I'm still fighting."],
       reveal:"In the dreams where she fails, she returns to four calmly, content — 'the dream-Agnes chose the floor'",
       next:"crd_warmth"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"An hour in your car saying your own name before you could drive. I believe every second of that hour was earned.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] Every second earned. [a breath] I've been ashamed of that hour — an hour seems ridiculous, sitting in a car in a parking lot saying 'Agnes Rose' over and over like a broken toy. Anyone who saw me would've called the police. But you called it earned, and you're right, because each time I said it, the name came back a little more solid, a little more MINE, the way a hand that's been asleep slowly fills with feeling. I was coming back to life, word by word, in a parking lot, by myself, with the engine off and the night cold around me. [a breath] Eleven years of slow erasure, and the antidote was an hour of slow re-inscription — saying the name, again and again, until the name and the woman matched again. Until I could feel my own hands on the steering wheel and know they were mine. I drove home at five a.m. I didn't go back. I never went back. But I still say 'Agnes Rose' every morning, in the mirror, before coffee. Just to make sure the name stuck through the night. The habit survived the building. I don't know if it'll ever not feel necessary."],
       reveal:"The hour in the car as 'slow re-inscription' — saying her name until it fit again",
       next:"crd_warmth"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...I dream the stairs. [you let the dreaming haunt the room]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:3,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long breath] I dream the stairs. [a pause] You let it sit, the way you've let everything sit tonight, without trying to fix it or solve it or make the dreaming stop. [softly] I've told two therapists about the stairs dream, and both immediately tried to 'work with it' — reframe it, change the ending, use it therapeutically. And I understand why, that's their job. But the dream doesn't want to be reframed. The dream is ACCURATE. It's the truest thing my sleeping mind knows: that I barely got out, that the escape was never certain, and that some part of me is still on those stairs, still climbing, still reciting, night after night, earning the next landing. The dream isn't a disorder. It's a memorial. It's my sleeping self remembering what it cost. [a breath] You let the memorial stand without trying to cure it. That's more than any therapist gave me. Sometimes the right response to a wound isn't healing — it's witness. Let me show you the card now. The warm thing in my pocket."],
       next:"crd_warmth"}
    ]
  },

  crd_warmth:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the card that stays warm", act:3,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","[you can hear her take it out of her pocket] Here it is. A laminated card, level-four access, my photograph on it — younger, before four had really started — and a magnetic stripe and a printed ID number along the bottom edge. It looks completely ordinary. A badge. The kind every office worker in the country clips to a lanyard. And it is warm. It is warm right now, in my hand, in a cool studio, three years out of the building. Not hot. Just... a degree or two above the room, the way a cup of tea is when you've held it a while. Except I haven't held it a while. It's always like this. I keep it in the freezer some nights and in the morning it's room-warm again by the time I've had my coffee. I've stopped checking. The checking was making me worse."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","A reasonable person — and I keep trying to be one — says I'm imagining the warmth, that a frightened woman's hand finds heat in a cold object the way a grieving one finds a face in the clouds. And maybe. MAYBE. But I gave it to one of the other women, the one in the other state, to hold, without telling her anything about the warmth, just 'tell me what you notice.' And she said, after a moment, 'why is it warm.' She didn't know to expect it. She felt it cold. Two women, two states, the same wrong warmth from the same kind of card. That's the one piece of the supernatural I can't quite reason away, and I've tried harder than anyone."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Another woman felt the warmth without being told to expect it. That's not your imagination, Agnes. That's corroboration.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:6,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[gripping the word] Corroboration. [she breathes] That's the word the doctor never used, the word the supervisor's smile was designed to keep me from ever earning. Corroboration means it left my head. It means it's not a symptom, it's a PHENOMENON, something that happens in the shared world where two people can both put a hand on it and agree. Eleven years they made sure everything I experienced stayed locked inside the one place they could discredit — my own mind. And the card broke that. The card is warm in someone else's hand too. [her voice firms] Whatever the floor was, it put something into this card, some residue, some — I don't have the science, I'm a cleaner — but a piece of that warm reading attention is IN here, and it didn't fade in three years, and a stranger felt it cold. I don't need you to believe the ghost. I just need you to believe two women felt the same warmth, because that one fact, that single shared fact, is the crack in the wall they built around my mind. Light gets in through it."],
       reveal:"A second woman independently felt the card's warmth — 'the crack in the wall around my mind'",
       next:"crd_number"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The ID number printed along the edge — have you ever looked into what it actually encodes? Or were you afraid to?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[hesitant] I was afraid to, for a long time. But I'm a careful woman, and careful women look, eventually, in the daylight, with the door locked. The number has parts. The first block is the facility code — I confirmed that much; it matches the building. The middle block is the access tier — four. But the last block, the long one, isn't a personnel number. My employee number was short, I knew it by heart, wrote it a thousand times on the log. This last block is far too long to be a person. It's the length of a... a RECORD number. An archival accession number. [a breath] Which means my access card wasn't coded to me as an employee. It was coded to me as a FILE. As an item in the collection. The card that let me into four also, if I'm reading it right, ENTERED ME INTO four. Catalogued me. I think the day they issued my badge, they accessioned me. I've been a record in the permanent collection for eleven years and didn't know until I read my own number in the daylight."],
       reveal:"The card's ID block is record-length, not personnel-length — 'they accessioned me as a file'",
       next:"crd_number"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You kept it in the freezer and it warmed back by morning. I believe you stopped checking because the answer frightened you.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] The freezer thing — I've never told anyone the freezer thing, it's too mad, a grown woman putting her old work badge in the freezer beside the peas. But you didn't laugh. You understood it was an EXPERIMENT, a frightened scientist's experiment, the only instrument I had. And the result was always the same: warm by morning. A laminated card with no power source, no battery, nothing, generating heat against the ice all night, every night. [a breath] I stopped checking because each confirmation made the world less explainable, and a woman living alone needs SOME of the world to stay explainable or she can't get up in the morning. So I put it in the left pocket and I made a rule: I don't check the warmth anymore, I just carry it. Carrying it is the compromise between throwing it away — which feels like abandoning the proof, abandoning Marta, abandoning the other women — and testing it, which feels like inviting four back into my life one cold morning at a time. I carry. I don't check. Until tonight. Tonight I'm checking, with you, out loud, for everyone. That's new. That's why my hand's shaking."],
       reveal:"The freezer 'experiment': the card warms against the ice by morning, every night",
       next:"crd_number"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...It's warm right now. [you don't reach for it, you just believe her, in the quiet]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a breath of relief] You didn't reach for it. Everyone reaches for it — 'let me feel, let me see' — and the reaching is always half curiosity and half the wish to catch me out, to feel a cold card and gently tell me it's only room temperature, dear. You just believed me from across the room. [softly] Do you know what that does, to be believed without being TESTED? It's almost unbearable. Eleven years of being tested — scans, questions, the kind smile that's really a test — and you just... took my word that the thing in my hand is warm. [her voice catches] That's the gentlest thing anyone has done for me in years, maybe ever. To let the card stay warm without making me prove it. [a breath] I want to give you something for that trust. There's a number on this card and I've spent three years afraid of it. Stay where you are. Stay gentle. Let me decide whether tonight's the night I read it out loud."],
       next:"crd_number"}
    ]
  },

  crd_number:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the number that isn't a person", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Let me show you what I found when I finally looked at the card in the daylight, the way a careful woman looks at a thing that frightens her — methodically, in a locked room, with the curtains drawn. The front: my photograph, younger, a name, the magnetic stripe. Ordinary. But the number along the bottom edge — the long printed ID — I'd never really examined it while I worked four. It was just 'my badge number.' Now, in the daylight, I counted the digits. My employee number was six characters, I knew it by heart, wrote it a thousand times on the log. This number has NINETEEN characters. And the format doesn't match a personnel record — I know what personnel numbers look like from eleven years of signing logs. This one matches an ARCHIVAL ACCESSION NUMBER. The kind you put on a file when you're entering it into the permanent collection."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Which means — and I've turned this over until my mind bled — my access card wasn't coded to me as an EMPLOYEE. It was coded to me as a RECORD. As an item in the collection. The day they issued my badge, they didn't just give me access to four. They ENTERED me into four. Accessioned me. Filed me. Catalogued me as part of the permanent collection I was supposed to be cleaning. I've been a record in the permanent-by-neglect collection for eleven years and didn't know until I counted the digits in the daylight. The card that let me into four also let four into me. That's the piece I can't put down."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"They catalogued you as a file in the collection you were supposed to clean. That's the most disturbing structural detail yet, Agnes.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:6,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[shaking] Structural. Yes, that's right, it's STRUCTURAL, not supernatural — a number format is a bureaucratic decision, made in an office, by someone who chose, deliberately, to use an accession schema for personnel cards. That person decided that the women who work four should be numbered like the files on four, and the only reason to do that is if you consider them part of the same collection. We weren't staff. We were inventory. Renewable, replaceable inventory, catalogued alongside the un-destroyed records we were supposed to mind, and when we wore out — when we 'cognitively separated' — we were processed out of the collection the same way a damaged file is: with a form, and a kind hand, and a gentle walk to the door. [a breath] The nineteen digits are the coldest thing I've ever counted. They mean the floor didn't happen TO us. We were PART of the floor. Designed in. Budgeted. Numbered. The erasure isn't a side effect. We were a line item in the system architecture, and our accession numbers prove it."],
       reveal:"Card uses archival accession format, not personnel — 'we weren't staff, we were inventory'",
       next:"crd_freezer"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Could you verify that number format? Is there a way to check whether it really matches an accession schema?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[carefully] Archival accession numbers follow published standards — there are NARA guidelines for how federal records get numbered, the format is documented, and you can look up the block structure: collection code, series, box, folder, item. My card's nineteen digits, when I parsed them against the NARA format, broke into exactly those blocks. Not approximately. Exactly. The first block matches the facility. The second block matches — and this made me sit down — a SERIES code that, if it's what I think it is, corresponds to the permanent collection on four. [a breath] I'm not an archivist. I could be reading the format wrong. But the block boundaries fall in the right places, and the blocks decode to things that make sense, and I've checked them against the published standard three times in three different libraries because I wanted to be WRONG and I wasn't. If I'm reading it right — and I want an expert to tell me I'm not — then my card says I'm item number [she pauses] something, in the permanent collection of sub-level four. I'm in the catalogue. I just walked out of it."],
       reveal:"She parsed the number against NARA accession standards — blocks match facility + series",
       next:"crd_freezer"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"The card that let you into four also let four into you. That symmetry is terrifying, and I believe you saw it clearly.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] The symmetry. [a breath] You named the thing I couldn't — that the card worked BOTH ways, and that's its whole horror. An access card is supposed to be a one-way tool: it gives you permission to enter a space. But an accession number is a two-way inscription: it enters YOU into the space's records, makes you part of it, gives the space a claim on you. My card was both at once, and I never knew because I only looked at one side — the side that said 'I have permission.' I never turned it over to see the side that said 'and the floor has permission too, to read me, to file me, to keep me warm, to process me when I'm spent.' [a breath] I carried my own accession notice in my pocket for eleven years and used it every night to let myself into the room that was slowly adding me to its collection. The key and the trap were the same card. The permission and the theft were the same swipe. I let myself in and it let itself into me, every night, same card, same magnetic stripe, same quiet swipe at a door that opened for both of us at once."],
       reveal:"The card was both an access key and an accession notice — 'the permission and the theft were the same swipe'",
       next:"crd_freezer"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Nineteen characters. [you let the count hang, cold]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Nineteen. [a pause] You let the number sit without trying to explain it away or make it mean something dramatic — you just let it be a count, the cold fact of a number that's thirteen digits too long to be a person, and that's the right weight to give it. [softly] Most people, when I get to the nineteen, either panic — 'oh my God, they filed you as a record' — or dismiss — 'you're misreading the format, dear.' You did neither. You let nineteen be nineteen. And in that quiet I can feel the number landing the way it needs to: not as proof of a ghost, not as the ranting of a crazy woman, just as a count that doesn't fit the explanation it was given. Nineteen is too long for a person and exactly right for a file. That's a fact about the world, and it sits in the world whether I'm sane or not. [a breath] The number's been waiting three years for someone to let it just BE what it is. Thank you for being that quiet. Let me tell you about the freezer, and then the door, and then we decide."],
       next:"crd_freezer"}
    ]
  },

  crd_freezer:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the experiment in the ice", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I want to tell you about the freezer, because it's the saddest experiment I ever ran, and also the most convincing, and I need you to not laugh. After I left, the card stayed warm. In my pocket, on the counter, in the glove box — always a degree or two above whatever it sat on. So one night, alone, unable to sleep, I did what a scientist would do: I put it in the freezer. Between the peas and a bag of corn. Closed the door. Went to bed. In the morning I opened the freezer and the peas were frozen and the card was room-warm. Already. Before my coffee."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I did it six more times. Same result. A laminated card with no battery, no power source, no mechanism — a piece of plastic and a magnetic stripe — generating heat against ice, all night, every night. The peas had frost. The card didn't. [a breath] I know — I KNOW — how it sounds: a crazy woman putting her old badge in the freezer, checking it in the morning like she's testing the Eucharist. But it's a controlled experiment, isn't it? Same freezer, same conditions, same night, peas cold, card warm. The only variable is the card. I didn't imagine the warmth; the frost on the peas and the lack of frost on the card can't both be my psychology. One of them is lying and it isn't the peas."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The peas had frost. The card didn't. That's not imagination, Agnes — frost is physics.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:6,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[urgent relief] PHYSICS. Thank you — that's the word I needed, the word I've been afraid to use because I'm not a physicist, I'm a cleaner. But frost IS physics. Frost happens when moisture contacts a surface below zero. The peas were below zero; they frosted. The card was next to them and didn't frost. Either the card is above zero — generating warmth from no source — or the card has some property that prevents frost, which also has no explanation for a laminated badge. Either way, it's anomalous, and anomalous is a physics word, not a psychology word, and I have LIVED for three years in the gap between those two words, begging someone to give me the physics one. You just did. [a breath] I stopped the freezer test after the seventh time because the confirming results were making me worse, not better — each time it was warm I had to accept a little more that this was real, and real was heavier than uncertain. But seven trials is enough. The card defies the peas. I'll take that sentence to a lab if anyone will have me."],
       reveal:"Seven freezer trials: peas frosted, card stayed warm — 'the card defies the peas'",
       next:"crd_scans"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Did you ever try it with a DIFFERENT card — a bank card, another badge — as a control?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a pause — the question clearly impresses her] ...I did. That's — you're the first person to ask the control question, and yes. I put my library card in the freezer next to the level-four card. Same night. Morning: library card frozen, frost, cold to the touch. Level-four card warm, no frost. Same freezer, same shelf, same night. The library card behaved like a card in a freezer should. The level-four card didn't. [a breath] And I tried it again with a debit card, same result — the control frosted, the level-four card didn't. Three different comparison cards, seven nights total, and the only card that stayed warm was the one from four. I'm not a scientist. But I ran a controlled experiment with replications and a control variable, alone in my kitchen, at three in the morning, because nobody else was going to do it for me. The data says one card in the world doesn't freeze. It's the one from the building that breathes."],
       reveal:"She ran a controlled comparison: library card + debit card frosted; level-four card alone stayed warm",
       next:"crd_scans"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Testing the Eucharist — you said it with shame, but it's the most rigorous thing in the story. A woman who tests instead of just believing.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a wet laugh] Testing the Eucharist. I said it as a joke on myself and you heard the rigor under the self-deprecation. [a breath] Because that IS what I was doing — taking an article of faith, something I believed, and instead of just believing it, putting it in the coldest, most empirical environment I had and saying 'prove it or dissolve.' Every true believer should do that with their belief and most won't. I did it seven times. And the belief survived the freezer every time, which is either the most damning evidence that the card is real or the most elaborate self-deception I've ever run, and I genuinely cannot tell which from the inside. [a breath] But here's what tips me: I WANTED it to frost. I put it in the freezer HOPING it would freeze, because a frozen card would mean I was crazy and I could stop carrying it and go be an ordinary confused old woman. It didn't freeze. Seven times. I kept offering the card the chance to prove me wrong and it wouldn't take it. If I'm deluded, I'm deluded against my own preference, which is a strange shape for a delusion to take."],
       reveal:"She wanted it to freeze — 'deluded against her own preference, which is a strange shape for a delusion'",
       next:"crd_scans"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...It isn't the peas. [you let the absurd, undeniable image sit]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long breath] It isn't the peas. [a pause, and then something almost like laughter] You know, that might be the most absurd sentence in this whole conversation — 'it isn't the peas' — and it might also be the most useful, because it cuts through everything. Not the building, not the ghost, not the conspiracy, not my mental health — just: a bag of peas did what physics says it should, and a card didn't, and the peas are not the liars. That's the whole case, reduced to groceries. [a breath] I've spent three years dressing this story in horror and sadness and institutional language, and maybe the truest version of it is the simplest: an old woman put her badge in the freezer and it didn't freeze. That's it. Everything else is interpretation. The non-freezing is the fact. I need someone with instruments better than a freezer to tell me WHY it doesn't freeze. I don't have that someone. But I have seven non-frozen nights and a bag of peas, and tonight I have you, and the card is warm in my hand right now. Come see the door it opened. Then we'll decide."],
       next:"crd_scans"}
    ]
  },

  crd_scans:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the door it shouldn't open", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","She's holding the card in the light now, turning it. The hum on the line has grown — steady, low, almost like the building found the frequency. She's too absorbed to hear it. You note it and say nothing, to keep her steady."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Here's the part where I stop being a woman with a warm memento and become a woman with a problem, because the card still WORKS. Not at the facility — I'd never go back, and anyway they'd have killed the access. I mean elsewhere. About a year ago, downtown, nothing to do with any of this, I was at an ordinary office building visiting the one friend I have left, and there was a card reader by a side door, and out of eleven years of habit my hand just... waved the card at it. Reflex. The way you reach for a light switch in a house you no longer live in. And the light went green. The door unlocked. A door in a building that had never heard of me, never issued me anything, had no reason on earth to honor a dead federal access card from another city."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I ran. I didn't go in, I ran, I sat in my car shaking exactly like the night I left four. Because there are only two explanations and I hate them both. Either the card carries some master credential, some skeleton key the floor uses to reach anywhere it pleases — or the card doesn't open doors at all, and what opens them is whatever's in the card that's also warm, reaching out, the way it reached for me in the dark, and the green light is just the world's locks recognizing their own. The card knows doors it was never given. I've never waved it at anything since. I'm afraid of what else it thinks it has the right to open."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"It opened a door in a building that never issued it. That's a real, physical event, Agnes — that happened in the daylight world.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:7,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[urgently, quietly] In the DAYLIGHT. Yes. That's why this one breaks me differently than the warmth or the tapes — those happened in the dark, underground, where I could blame the dark. This happened at two in the afternoon, on a normal street, with traffic and pigeons and my friend waiting inside. The most ordinary setting imaginable, and a dead card opened a door that didn't know it. There's no sick-building syndrome for that. There's no tired-mind explanation for a lock going green. A lock either accepts a credential or it doesn't, and it accepted one it had never been told to accept. [a breath] Which means the card is not a memento. It's a KEY, to something larger than one building, and I've been carrying it in my coat pocket on the bus, to the grocery, to church, for three years, a key that opens doors it was never given, warm against my hip the whole time. I think I have to either destroy it or expose it. I can't keep just CARRYING a thing like that. That's what tonight is for. To decide. With you."],
       reveal:"The card opened a door in an unrelated building in daylight — 'a key to something larger'",
       note:"This is her hardest physical claim — an event with no mundane explanation she can find.",
       next:"crd_door"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You ran instead of going in. Do you ever wonder what was behind that door — or are you glad you'll never know?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long, complicated pause] ...Both. I'm glad I ran, and I think about that door every single day. Because here's the thing I've never said: part of me wanted to go in. After eleven years of four taking from me, here was a door OFFERING me something — access, an answer, the other side of the wall — and a small terrible part of me thought, what if four isn't only a prison, what if the card is an invitation, what if behind that door is where the warm cabinets keep the texture they stole, my afternoons with my sister, Marta's face, all of it, filed and waiting, and the card is how you go and VISIT what you've lost. [her voice trembles] That's the thought that frightens me most. Not that the card opens doors. That one day I'll be tired enough, or grieving enough, or far enough gone, that I'll WANT it to. That I'll wave it at a green light and walk in and go back to the warm dark on purpose, to be read, to be kept, to be with Marta in the collection. I ran because I knew, even then, that the running was the only safe direction. I don't trust myself near doors anymore. That's why the card has to leave my hands tonight, one way or another."],
       reveal:"Her deepest fear: that one day grief will make her WANT to follow the card back",
       note:"The most intimate confession in the arc — the pull toward the very thing that hurt her.",
       next:"crd_door"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"The world's locks recognizing their own — that's a haunting way to put it, and I don't think you're imagining the green light.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] 'Recognizing their own.' You kept the phrase. [a breath] I've wondered whether every lock, underneath, speaks the same old language — open, closed, permitted, forbidden — the language of the archive, of who-may-enter and who-may-not, and the card speaks that language with an authority that predates any one building. The floor, after all, was just a very large lock around things that wanted to be forgotten. Maybe the card is a piece of that authority, broken off, carried out in a frightened woman's coat, still trying to do its one job: deciding who gets in and who stays out, who is remembered and who is erased. [a breath] And if that's true, then I'm carrying a fragment of the thing that erases people, and I have to decide tonight whether to bury it or hold it up to the light so everyone can see what shape it is. I'm so tired of carrying it alone. Whatever we decide, let's decide it together. Let me show you the number. Then you'll help me choose."],
       reveal:"She frames the card as 'a fragment of the authority that erases people'",
       next:"crd_door"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The card knows doors it was never given. [you let that line stand in the thickening quiet]",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:5,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quiet] Doors it was never given. [a long pause] You let it stand, and in your quiet I can hear — do you hear that? The hum. It's been growing since I took the card out. [a breath, steadying herself] No. I won't be frightened of it tonight, because I'm not alone tonight, and being alone was always the floor's real weapon, not the warmth, not the forgetting — the ALONE. It could only take from me what no one else was witnessing. But you're witnessing now. It's on your tape now. Whatever's humming on this line, whatever the card is reaching toward, it can't un-happen what's already been recorded in another person's hearing. [her voice firms] That's the whole secret, isn't it. The cure for being erased is to be witnessed. I came here to be witnessed. So let me finish it. There's a number on this card. Help me decide whether to read it out loud, into your tape, where it can never be forgotten."],
       next:"crd_door"}
    ]
  },

  crd_door:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — what the card wants", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","Heat building. She's holding the card up to the light, turning it slowly. The hum on the line has settled into something regular, almost a pulse. She's too absorbed to hear it."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I need to tell you the thing that happened after the green-light door, the thing I've never told because it makes me sound like I've crossed from a witness into a patient. After I ran from that door — the unrelated building, the dead card that opened it — I started NOTICING doors. Not trying to open them. Just noticing them. Card readers on the sides of buildings, in parking garages, at universities, at hospitals. I'd never seen them before, the way you never see a word until someone teaches it to you and then it's everywhere. The card in my pocket had taught me a new alphabet, and the alphabet was doors, and suddenly the whole city was FULL of them, and I couldn't stop seeing them, and every time I passed one the card got warmer."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I don't know if the warmth is in my hand or in the card. That's the honesty I owe you. It could be my own circulation, my own anxiety, heating the pocket, making me imagine the plastic is responding. But the warmth and the door come TOGETHER — the card warms when I pass a reader, as if it's recognizing something, and the one time I accidentally brushed against a reader on a hospital wall the warmth spiked to a full degree and the reader's light blinked once. Just once. Not green, not open, just a blink. An acknowledgment. As if the locks know the card is there, and the card knows the locks, and they're all speaking a language I'm carrying and can't read."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The locks acknowledge the card. A language you're carrying and can't read. That's beyond a memento, Agnes — that card is still active.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:7,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[trembling] Still active. [a breath] That's the word I've been afraid to say because 'active' means the card is still DOING something, still connected to whatever system issued it, still part of the floor's network even out here in the daylight. And if it's active, then I'm carrying an active piece of the thing that erased me in my left pocket, on the bus, to the grocery, to CHURCH, and every card reader I pass is a node in the same system, and the blink was the system saying 'we see you.' [her voice firms] I've thought about throwing it away a hundred times. Into a river, into a sewer, somewhere it can't blink at anything. But throwing it away means throwing away the only proof I have — the warm card is the one physical object that says I'm not imagining everything. Without the card I'm just a story. With the card I'm a witness who has something to put in someone's hand. So I carry the active thing, the connected thing, the thing that might be leading them to me, because the alternative is being believed even less than I already am. The card is my albatross and my evidence and I can't drop either without losing both."],
       reveal:"The card warms near card readers; a hospital reader blinked once — 'still connected to the system'",
       next:"crd_pull"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The blink — one blink on a hospital reader when you brushed it. Was there any consequence? Did anyone come?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long pause] No one came. Not that time. But I left the hospital FAST, and I didn't go back, and for two weeks afterward I checked behind me more carefully than usual. [a breath] The blink wasn't an access event — the door didn't open, no one was alerted as far as I know. But a blink on a reader means the reader SAW the card, read something off the magnetic stripe, recognized it enough to respond, and decided — or the system decided — not to grant access. Which means two things: one, the card IS talking to the readers, actively, in the electromagnetic language of magnetic stripes, even through my coat, which means the stripe is live. And two, the system KNOWS the card when it sees it, recognizes it from the institutional side, which means my accession number is still in a database somewhere, still active, still making readers blink when I walk past. I'm filed in a system I can't log out of. The floor let me walk up the stairs but it never signed me OUT of the collection. As far as the system knows, I'm still a file in the permanent collection, one that happens to be walking around a city. Filed and mobile. That's what I am. A mobile file."],
       reveal:"The magnetic stripe is still 'live' in the system — 'they never signed me out of the collection'",
       next:"crd_pull"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Every time you pass a reader the card warms — it's reaching for something. I don't think that's your circulation, Agnes.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] You don't think it's my circulation. [a breath] Everyone I've told — the two women, my cousin — went straight to 'it's your hand, dear, you're anxious near doors and anxiety warms the skin.' And that's possible, that's the reasonable read, and I CAN'T disprove it because I can't take my hand out of the pocket without moving the card away from the reader, so the conditions collapse when I try to test them. [a breath] But here's the thing that doesn't fit the anxiety theory: I didn't KNOW the hospital reader was there. I wasn't anxious about it because I hadn't seen it. I was walking, my coat brushed the wall, the card was in my left pocket against the wall, and the warmth spiked at the instant of contact, BEFORE I turned my head and saw the reader. The warmth preceded the seeing. You can't be anxious about a thing you haven't noticed yet. The card noticed it for me. And then the reader blinked. [a breath] That sequence — warmth, then see, then blink — is the one thing I can't fit into 'my hand was warm.' My hand didn't know the reader was there. The card did."],
       reveal:"The warmth spiked BEFORE she saw the reader — 'the card noticed for me'",
       next:"crd_pull"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...A language you're carrying and can't read. [you let the loneliness of that illiteracy sit]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:5,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Can't read. [a pause] That's the worst part — carrying a message you can't decode, knowing it's saying SOMETHING to every door you pass, and not knowing whether it's saying 'let me in' or 'she's here' or 'this one got out.' I'm a courier for a language I'm illiterate in, and the letter I'm carrying might be my death warrant or my passport, and I've been carrying it for three years without knowing which. [softly] You know what I've started doing? Apologizing. To the card. In the dark, in my pocket. 'I'm sorry I can't read you. I'm sorry I don't know what you're saying.' As if it's another lost thing, another Marta, something that needs to be understood and I'm failing it. I can't even tell if the card is my enemy or my companion. I've never been this confused about anything, and I've spent eleven years on a floor built to confuse. Let me tell you why I can't put it down, even now, even when it frightens me. And then the decision."],
       next:"crd_pull"}
    ]
  },

  crd_pull:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — why I can't let go", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Let me be honest about the pull, the real pull, the thing underneath the evidence and the warmth and the duty. I can't put the card down because putting it down means being NOBODY again. For three years, every time I've doubted myself, every time the world told me I was confused, I could put my hand in my left pocket and feel the warmth and know: I'm not imagining this. The card is warm. The card is real. Therefore SOMETHING is real, and if something is real then I'm not crazy, and if I'm not crazy then Marta was real and the floor was real and my eleven years meant something."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","The card is the last bridge between my story and the physical world. Without it I'm a woman with memories and no proof, and memories — mine especially — can be filed under 'age, grief, illness' and dismissed. The card can't be dismissed that way. It's WARM. It OPENS DOORS. It has NINETEEN DIGITS. Those are facts that live in the world, not in my head, and the world can't diagnose them away. [a breath] So I carry it knowing it might lead them to me, knowing it blinks at their readers, knowing it's possibly still connected to the system that erased me — because dropping it would mean becoming exactly what the floor wanted: a woman with no evidence, no proof, no warm thing in her pocket to anchor her in the real. The card is the cost of being credible. I pay the cost every day. I've decided it's worth it."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The card is the bridge between your story and the physical world. Without it, they can diagnose you away. I understand why you carry it.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a deep breath] You understand. [softly] And understanding the WHY of it means you understand the TRAP I'm in, too — I need the card to be believed, and the card might be the thing that gets me found. I can't be credible AND safe. The floor designed it that way, or stumbled into it, and the result is the same: a woman who can choose between being a witness with evidence or a nobody without it, and both choices cost everything. [a breath] Coming here tonight was me choosing witness, for one hour, at whatever price. The card is out of my pocket for the first time in three years, in the light, on a table, and if the hum on this line is what I think it is, then the price is already being named. But I'd rather be a witness for one hour than a nobody forever. Marta was a nobody forever. I won't be. Not tonight. Help me decide what to do with the nineteen digits that are staring at us both right now."],
       reveal:"She can't be both credible and safe — 'the floor designed it that way'",
       next:"crd_others"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Have you ever thought about having the card tested — the warmth, the magnetic stripe — by someone with instruments?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a complicated pause] Every day. And every day the same problem: who do you hand it to? A physicist would measure the temperature — but the card is warm in a WOMAN'S hand, and a physicist's hand is just another hand, and what if it only warms for the hands that are in the system? What if the warmth is relational, not mechanical — the card reaching for its own, the way it reached for the hospital reader? I'm terrified it would go cold for a stranger and then I'm the woman whose magic card only works for her. [a breath] But even that — even a card that only warms for its owner — would be SOMETHING, wouldn't it? A card that's warm in my hand and cold in yours is still anomalous; laminated plastic doesn't do that. The test is terrifying because it might shrink the miracle into something I can't narrate, but a shrunken miracle is still a miracle, still anomalous, still more than I had in the freezer with the peas. [a breath] I want the test. I'm afraid of the test. That's the whole shape of my relationship with knowing. I want to know and I'm afraid that knowing will leave me with less than not-knowing does. But tonight — with you, on this tape — I think I might finally be ready to let someone else hold the card. That's new. That's you."],
       reveal:"She fears the card might go cold in a stranger's hand — 'the warmth might be relational'",
       next:"crd_others"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"The card is the cost of being credible. You pay it every day. That's not delusion, Agnes — that's a choice made with open eyes.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[steadier] A choice made with open eyes. [a breath] That's exactly what separates me from the version of me they'd like to diagnose — a delusional person doesn't see the cost, doesn't weigh it, doesn't choose it with full knowledge of the alternative. I know the card might be leading them to me. I know the warmth might be my own anxiety. I know the accession number might be a format I'm misreading. I carry it KNOWING all of that, having weighed it, having decided that the chance of being right is worth the cost of being tracked. That's not compulsion. That's a considered decision by a woman who has exactly one piece of evidence and has priced the risk of holding it. [a breath] A sane woman carrying a dangerous piece of proof because the alternative is being nobody — that's a completely rational act in an irrational situation. The situation is insane. My response to it isn't. I keep trying to tell people that and they keep hearing the insanity of the situation and attributing it to me. You're the first to hear my RESPONSE and call it clear-eyed. Thank you. Let me tell you about the others who reached for me, once the card was out in the world."],
       reveal:"'A considered decision by a woman who has one piece of evidence and has priced the risk'",
       next:"crd_others"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...I've decided it's worth it. [you let the cost and the decision both stand]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Worth it. [a long pause] You didn't try to talk me out of it or into it — you just let the decision BE mine, with its full weight, the way you've let everything tonight be mine. [softly] And that's the thing I came for, really, underneath the evidence and the duty and the warning to the woman on four: I came for a room where my own decision, made with my own weighing, in my own battered mind, would be respected as a DECISION and not pathologized as a symptom. For three years every choice I've made has been read as evidence of my condition — carrying the card: obsession. Checking the warmth: compulsion. Coming here: grandiosity. And you've let each choice be a CHOICE, a thing a person does for reasons, not a twitch a patient has. [a breath] That's the gift of tonight, more than anything on the tape: for one hour, I was a person who CHOSE, not a patient who EXHIBITED. I chose the card. I chose the risk. I chose the microphone. And a stranger let me choose. Let me tell you one more thing — the reaching — and then we decide about the number."],
       next:"crd_others"}
    ]
  },

  crd_others:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the reaching", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Something happened after I found the other women — Dorothy and the second one — something I haven't told them and haven't told anyone. When I brought the card out to show Dorothy, on her kitchen table, in another state, the moment the card left my pocket and sat on her table, her PHONE rang. Once. Just once. No caller ID. She picked up. Dead air, then a dial tone. She said 'wrong number,' went pale, and didn't bring it up again. The card was on her table for four minutes. In those four minutes: one phone call from nowhere."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Coincidence. I told myself coincidence. But then I showed it to the second woman, different state, different kitchen, and in her case it wasn't a phone call — her lights flickered. Once. Just a flicker, the kind a brown-out makes, except nothing else in her neighborhood flickered, she checked later. The card was out of my pocket and on a surface, and something in the local infrastructure NOTICED. Two women, two states, two different responses from two different systems, both in the minutes the card was exposed. [a breath] I stopped showing it to people after that. Because each time I take the card out of my pocket and put it somewhere a reader might sense it — even a reader I can't see — something blinks. Something calls. Something acknowledges. And I don't want to bring the blinking to anyone else's kitchen."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"A phone call in Dorothy's kitchen. A flicker in the other's. Two different systems noticing the card in two different states. Agnes, that's not coincidence.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:7,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[frightened, but resolved] Not coincidence. And here's the part I'm ashamed of: I didn't warn them. I didn't tell Dorothy about the blink or the reader or the warmth before I put the card on her table. I just... showed it, because I needed to see if someone else would feel the warmth, and I got my answer — she felt it — but I also got a phone call from nowhere in her kitchen, and I'd brought it there. I put a piece of the floor on her table without telling her the floor might notice. [a breath] I've carried the guilt of that phone call for a year. Dorothy's quiet life, her grandchildren, her rebuilt safety — and I brought the card into it for four minutes and something called. If anything comes of that call — if someone followed the card to HER — that's on me. I trade on my own safety to carry the evidence. I had no right to trade on hers. That's why I stopped showing it. The card isn't safe to expose. Which makes tonight — with the card out, under a microphone, on a frequency — the most exposed it's ever been. And the hum you've been hearing is the thing I've been hearing in kitchens, scaled up. I'm sorry. I brought it here. But I had to bring it somewhere, and a studio with no address and a host with no name seemed like the only safe kitchen left."],
       reveal:"Showing the card caused a phone call and a flicker in two different kitchens — 'I brought the floor into their lives'",
       next:"crd_motel"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You stopped showing it after two experiences. Is the card out of your pocket right now, in this studio?",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:7,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[very quietly] Yes. It's on the table between us. Right now. It's been out since I started talking about it. And the hum on your line — the one you've been politely not mentioning — started growing the moment I set it down. I noticed. You noticed. We've both been pretending not to notice because talking about the card was more important than the hum, but we're near the end now and I'll say it plain: the card is exposed, and something knows it, and the something is on your frequency now, which means it knows about YOU and about this studio and about this tape. [a breath] I'm sorry. I should have warned you before I took it out. I didn't because I was afraid you'd tell me to put it back, and I can't tell this story with the card in my pocket — the card IS the story, and it needed to be out, in the light, where we could both see it and know it was real. But the cost of out is the hum. And the hum is the floor, reaching, the way it always reaches, for the warm thing that left the collection. I brought it here. I'm sorry."],
       reveal:"The card is OUT on the table right now — the hum started when she set it down",
       next:"crd_motel"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You stopped showing it to protect people from the blinking. That's not paranoia — that's decency.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[softly] Decency. [a breath] Or self-preservation dressed as decency — I've never been able to tell. Did I stop to protect them, or to protect MYSELF from the guilt of bringing the floor's attention to their doorsteps? Both, probably, and the not-knowing which is the kinder motive is just one more thing I carry without resolving. [a breath] But tonight I brought it to YOUR doorstep, and I chose to, and you deserve to know that by inviting me in you've invited the card in, and by inviting the card in you've invited the attention of whatever makes the readers blink. I can't undo that. I can only make it mean something — by using the hour, by saying the story, by getting enough of it on your tape that even if the hum eats the frequency tonight, the recording exists, the words exist, Agnes Rose existed and told the truth in a warm room with the lights down low. [a breath] That's the trade. The hum is the price. I'm sorry. I paid it for both of us without asking. Let me tell you about where I've been living, and then the tin, and then we decide."],
       reveal:"She acknowledges bringing the floor's 'attention' to the studio — the hum is the price",
       next:"crd_motel"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...I stopped showing it to people. [you let the isolation of that caution sit]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:5,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Stopped showing it. [a pause] Because showing it endangers people, and not showing it isolates me, and that's the whole choice the floor left me: dangerous company or safe solitude. Every relationship I might have had in the last year has been stopped by the card — I can't have a friend over for dinner with a warm card in my pocket that might call their phone from nowhere. I can't leave it at home because then I have no proof. I can't explain it because the explanation makes me sound insane. [a breath] The card has made me MORE alone than the floor ever did, which is its final trick: the evidence of the crime IS the continuation of the crime. The card keeps me safe from being disbelieved and keeps me isolated from being loved, which was the floor's whole project — make the woman forgettable, keep her alone, ensure no one comes asking. I got out of the building but the building's logic came with me in my pocket. The isolation I carried out is the same isolation they built down there. I just changed floors. [a breath] Except tonight. Tonight I'm in a room with another person, card and all, hum and all. First time in three years. That's what you are — the first person in three years brave enough or kind enough to sit in a room with the card and not ask me to put it away. Let me tell you about the tin, and the rest of what I carry, and then we end this."],
       next:"crd_motel"}
    ]
  },

  crd_motel:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — no fixed address", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","I should tell you how I live now, so you understand the shape of the thing. I move. Not dramatically — I'm not a spy, I'm a tired woman with a warm card and a small income. But I don't stay in one place more than a few months. After the hospital reader blinked, I started noticing things: the same car twice, which might be nothing; a piece of mail I didn't order from an office I'd never heard of, which might be junk; a feeling, just a feeling, that the card's warmth was pointing somewhere, like a compass, and the direction was TOWARD me, from outside. I couldn't prove any of it. I can barely prove I felt it. But I'd spent eleven years on a floor that taught me what 'being noticed' feels like, and this felt like being noticed again."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","So I move. Subletting, mostly. The friend downtown, sometimes. Once, a shelter, for a bad week. I keep the tin with me — the card, the tapes, the hairpins, the receipt, the photos — in a bag I can grab. My whole evidence locker fits in a Trader Joe's bag, which is either very efficient or very sad. [a breath] I'm not living underground. I'm living QUIETLY, the way four taught me, making small enough choices that no system can predict the next one. The floor trained me for this. In a horrible way, my eleven years on four were practice for being a woman on the run from the thing she ran from. I'm using the skills the prison gave me to stay free of the prison. That's the darkest irony of my life, and I've made my peace with it, and I carry the Trader Joe's bag, and I move."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Your whole evidence locker in a Trader Joe's bag. Agnes, the modesty of how you carry this is heartbreaking and I'm not going to call it sad — I'm going to call it resourceful.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a small, surprised breath] Resourceful. [softly] You could have said sad and you chose resourceful. That one word rearranges the whole picture — a sad woman with a grocery bag is a tragedy, a resourceful woman with a grocery bag is a survivor using what she has. And I am using what I have. I have a tin, a bag, and the skills of eleven years underground — how to be quiet, how to be small, how to notice when you're being noticed. Those aren't symptoms. Those are COMPETENCIES, hard-won, deployed by a woman who assessed her threat environment and adapted. [a breath] I left a building. I packed what I could carry. I used the training the building gave me to stay free of it. That's not a breakdown, it's an OPERATION. A tiny, one-woman, Trader Joe's-bag operation against a federal floor that breathes. And so far — three years and counting — the operation has held. You calling it resourceful instead of sad is the first time anyone's seen it as what it actually is."],
       reveal:"She reframes her life as 'an operation' using skills four taught her — 'competencies, not symptoms'",
       next:"crd_tin"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"You said a piece of mail from an office you'd never heard of. Do you still have it? Did it have a return address?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[carefully] I have it. In the tin. It arrived about four months after I left, at my last real address, the apartment I'd given up shortly after. The forwarding caught it. A plain envelope, no logo, a return address that was just a suite number in a city I've never been to. Inside: a single page, printed, that said — and I've memorized it — 'This letter is to confirm the completion of your service record. No further action is required on your part.' That's it. No signature. No name. 'Completion of your service record.' [a breath] You could read it as a bureaucratic loose end — HR closing my file, routine. Or you could read it as a message: we know where your mail goes, and we're telling you we've 'completed' your record, which in the language of four means something very specific. Completed. Like a file. Like a record. Like something in the permanent collection that's been finished processing. I keep it in the tin because I can't decide if it's a form letter or a death certificate written in advance. Both readings keep me up. Only one of them moves me to a new address."],
       reveal:"A post-departure letter confirming 'completion of your service record' — routine closure or a message",
       next:"crd_tin"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You're using the skills the prison gave you to stay free of the prison. That's not irony, Agnes — that's justice.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a wet laugh] Justice. [a breath] I like that better than irony. Irony is a bitter word and justice is a warm one, and I've had enough bitter. [softly] The floor spent eleven years teaching me to disappear — to be quiet, to leave no trace, to notice when I was being watched — and now I'm deploying every lesson against the teacher. I'm using the floor's own curriculum to evade the floor. Every survival skill I have was handed to me by the thing that was killing me, which means the killing was never complete, because the skills survived the killing and turned against it. [a breath] That's the only revenge available to someone like me — I can't fight the building, I can't expose the office, I can't prove anything in a courtroom. But I can take the training they gave me — how to be invisible, how to move without trace, how to notice a car twice — and use it to be a witness they can't easily silence. The floor made me small. I'm using the smallness as a weapon. Let me tell you about the tin. The whole of what I carry."],
       reveal:"She deploys the floor's own 'invisibility training' against it — 'using the smallness as a weapon'",
       next:"crd_tin"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The skills the prison gave me to stay free of the prison. [you let the paradox land]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] Skills the prison gave me. [a pause] You let the paradox sit without smoothing it, and it IS a paradox — the worst thing in my life also gave me the tools to survive after it, which means I can't fully hate it, which means the floor wins a little even now. A thing you can't fully hate has a hold on you that a thing you despise never would. [softly] I learned silence, smallness, hyper-awareness, patience from eleven years underground. Those are valuable skills. And the source of them was the worst thing I ever lived through. I can't separate the tool from the torture. The trauma and the training are the same years. [a breath] Maybe that's why I still carry the card — it's the same paradox in physical form. The card is my evidence AND my leash. The tool AND the torture. The proof AND the danger. I carry the paradox because putting down half of it means putting down both. Let me show you the tin now. The whole archive. Then we decide, one last time."],
       next:"crd_tin"}
    ]
  },

  crd_tin:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — everything I carry", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Let me show you the tin. [you can hear her open it] A coffee tin, the kind with the plastic lid, just big enough for everything I own that matters. Inside: the card, which you've seen, warm. The three voice-activated tapes from four — the pages-turning sound. The fogged photographs on a memory card. Three hairpins — Marta's, Birdie's, and the unnamed woman's. The gas-station receipt with my escape plan. The piece of mail from the unknown office. And a notebook, small, spiral-bound, with the names and contact information of Dorothy and the second woman, written in code only I can read, so that if the tin is found, the women can't be traced from my notes."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","That's it. The whole of what I carried out of eleven years and three years of running. A tin. [she pauses] I look at it sometimes and think: this is what's left of us, the quiet women of four. Three hairpins for three goodbyes. Tapes nobody can hear. Photos nobody will trust. An escape plan on a receipt. The contact information of two frightened women, in code. And a warm card that won't freeze. It's the saddest museum in the world, and it's smaller than a shoebox, and every night I make sure the lid is tight and the bag is by the door and the door is unlocked in case I have to move again. That's my life. That's what I came to show you. Now I need you to help me decide what to do with the one thing in the tin that could change everything: the number on the card."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"The saddest museum in the world, smaller than a shoebox. I've never been more honored to be shown a collection, Agnes. Every piece matters.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she weeps, openly, and for once she doesn't try to stop] Honored. You said honored. To see a coffee tin with hairpins and tapes. [a long breath] Nobody has ever wanted to see the tin. It's the thing I grip when I can't sleep, the thing I check in the morning, the archive I've curated with more care than any archivist ever gave to four — and you called it an honor. [a breath] You know what the tin is, really? It's MY permanent collection. The floor had its cabinets full of people the world threw away. I have a coffee tin full of people the floor threw away. Cabinet to cabinet, both keeping the discarded warm in the dark, both refusing to let the destruction schedule run. I AM four, in miniature. I'm doing what the floor did — keeping records past their death date, refusing to let them be erased. The only difference is I do it with love and the floor did it with appetite. Or maybe the floor did it with love too, in its own way. I told you I'd never fully decided. [a breath] The museum is open. The visitor is you. Now — the number. One more decision. Help me."],
       reveal:"She frames her coffee tin as 'my permanent collection' — she IS four, in miniature, keeping the discarded warm",
       note:"The deepest mirror: Agnes doing lovingly what the floor did with appetite (or love).",
       next:"crd_cost"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The notebook in code — if something happened to you, could anyone else ever decode it and find Dorothy?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:6,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a careful pause] That's the question I lie awake with. The code is mine — a simple substitution I invented, nothing a real cryptographer couldn't crack, but enough to stop a casual finder from reading the names. And the key to the code is in my head. Which means: if I go, if the warm card's owners decide a mobile file needs to be re-shelved, the code dies with me and the two women stay safely hidden forever, OR the tin is found, the code is cracked, and the two women are exposed. I've weighed both constantly. Some nights I think I should destroy the notebook — protect them absolutely, at the cost of the chain being broken. Other nights I think the chain is the whole point, that someone, someday, needs to be able to follow it from my tin to Dorothy to the second woman to the yellow-copy office, and if I destroy the link, the chain ends at a dead woman's coffee tin. [a breath] I've left the notebook. Intact. Because the chain matters more than any one of us — that's what Marta taught me. The candle, passed on, even past death. The notebook is my hairpin, left on a shelf, for whoever finds the tin after me. It says: there are more of us. Follow the thread."],
       reveal:"The coded notebook: if she dies, the chain to Dorothy could be lost or cracked — she chose to leave it intact",
       next:"crd_cost"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"You curated the tin more carefully than any archivist cared for four. You're keeping the discarded warm the way the floor couldn't.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[trembling] Keeping the discarded warm. [a breath] You just described me as an archivist and I've never been called that, never would have dared call myself that — I'm a CLEANER who learned archiving by accident, the way a prisoner learns locksmithing by staring at the lock long enough. But you're right. The tin has a system: the tapes and photos for the physical evidence, the hairpins for the memorial, the receipt for the personal record, the notebook for the chain. I organized it. I labeled the tapes. I wrapped the hairpins in tissue. I archived the archive, preserved the preserving, kept the records of the record-keeper. [a breath] And the warmest thing in the tin is still the card, and when the lid is closed it warms everything around it a little, the tapes, the hairpins, all of it, kept slightly-above-room-temperature by a card that carries a piece of four's own warmth. Even in the tin, the floor is doing its one thing: keeping the forgotten warm. I can't decide if that's beautiful or terrible. Both. Forever both. Now — the number. I'm as ready as I'll ever be."],
       reveal:"The card warms everything in the tin — 'even in the tin, the floor is doing its one thing'",
       next:"crd_cost"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...The lid is tight and the bag is by the door. [you let the vigilance stand, without pity]",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:4,rapport:14},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a slow breath] The lid is tight. The bag is by the door. [a pause] You didn't say 'that's no way to live' or 'you deserve better' — you just let the discipline stand for what it is: a protocol, not a tragedy, performed by a woman who has assessed her situation and organized her response. [softly] The lid is tight because moisture would damage the tapes. The bag is by the door because a mobile file needs to stay mobile. The door is unlocked because I've been in a locked room for eleven years and I will never again be in a room I can't leave. Those aren't symptoms of paranoia. They're operational decisions by a woman whose operational environment, as you've heard tonight, warrants exactly this level of readiness. [a breath] You let them be decisions instead of pathology. That's all I ever wanted from anyone: to let my adaptations be adaptations. The bag. The tin. The lid. The door. These are what survival looks like when you're running from a floor that breathes. I've made a good life out of a terrible set of facts. Let me decide the last thing now. The number. Nineteen digits. I think I know what I want to do."],
       next:"crd_cost"}
    ]
  },

  crd_cost:{
    seg:"THE DESCENT — the last thing it costs", act:4,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Before I decide — and I think I know, I think my hands know even if my voice is still catching up — I want to say the cost out loud, so you hear it, so it's on the record, so nobody later can say she didn't know what she was doing. Reading the number — any of it, the accession code, the facility block, any part of those nineteen digits — marks me. It stops me being nobody. The systems that blinked at my card in kitchens will learn exactly which file is talking and where the frequency is. Being nobody kept me safe for three years. Reading the number ends that. Tonight."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","And here's the thing I've come to, the thing your quiet helped me reach: being safe isn't why I'm alive. Being a WITNESS is why I'm alive. Marta didn't teach me to survive so I could hide in sublets with a coffee tin until I die quietly and the tin ends up in a Goodwill and the hairpins end up in a drain. She taught me to survive so I could SPEAK. The survival was the preparation, not the destination. And I've been hiding in the preparation for three years, confusing 'staying alive' with 'living,' and tonight, in your warm room, with the card on the table and the hum on the line, I finally understand that the speaking is the thing Marta saved me for. [a breath] So. The cost. Yes. I hear it. I accept it. Now help me decide HOW."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Being safe isn't why you're alive — being a witness is. Marta saved you to speak, and you're ready. I'll help you decide.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:6,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[something settling, deep] Marta saved me to speak. [a breath, and then, quieter than she's been all night, but more certain] Then I'm going to speak. One way or another, with your help, into your microphone, into your tape, I'm going to let those nineteen digits out of my pocket and into the world. The floor kept Marta quiet. It will not keep me quiet. It had eleven years to erase me and I wrote my name on my hand every morning and climbed four flights saying Agnes Rose and I am STILL HERE, still Agnes, still Rose, still a person with a voice and a warm card and a story that is going to be HEARD before this night is over. [her voice firms for the first time all night] I didn't come to a pirate frequency at 3 A.M. to leave without being heard. Tell me how to do it. Tell me how to be loud enough that the floor hears me back, just once, and knows that the cleaning woman it spent eleven years erasing is the one thing in its whole collection it couldn't quite file away. Help me. I'm ready. Finally, finally, I'm ready."],
       reveal:"She commits to speaking — 'the floor will not keep me quiet'",
       note:"The arc's climactic moment: Agnes finding her voice. The decision crystallizes.",
       next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"How you do it matters as much as whether you do it. What's the version that protects you AND speaks?",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a pause, considering] The version that protects me and speaks. [a breath] Is there one? I've always thought it was all or nothing — read the number and become a target, or stay silent and stay safe. But you're asking me if there's a middle — a way to let the information OUT without pointing at the woman. [slowly] Maybe. Maybe I don't read MY number. Maybe I read just the FACILITY code — the first block, the part that identifies the building, not the file. That would expose FOUR without exposing AGNES. The building becomes the story, not the woman. [her voice grows] And the women who hear it — the ones still working floors like mine — they'd recognize the facility code, they'd know which building is the one that breathes, without me having to paint a target on myself. I could expose the floor and stay nobody. [a breath] Is that possible? That I could be loud AND safe? Nobody's ever offered me both at once. Let me decide. Give me one more moment of your quiet. Then I'll know."],
       reveal:"She sees a middle path: read the facility code, expose the floor, protect herself",
       next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Three years confusing staying alive with living. Tonight you stop confusing them. I'm with you, Agnes.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[tears, but steady] Stop confusing them. [a long breath] That's the sentence I needed to hear, and I couldn't say it to myself — I needed someone else to name the difference between surviving and living, because from the inside, hiding in the sublets, checking the card, moving the tin, it FEELS like living, it feels like a full life, until someone says 'you've been confusing alive with living' and suddenly you see how much of the last three years has been the floor's continuation, hiding from a thing instead of fighting it. [a breath] Marta fought. From inside the erasure, with nothing but a hairpin and a folded wrapper, she fought, she taught, she passed the candle. I've been hoarding the candle in a tin. Tonight I stop hoarding. Tonight the candle gets lit again, the way Marta meant it to be lit — in the open, in the hearing, where a thousand people can see it and carry it and the floor can't blow out a thousand flames at once. [a breath] I'm ready. The number. Help me. Let me be loud, one time, the way I've been quiet all my life."],
       reveal:"She recognizes she's been 'hoarding the candle in a tin' instead of lighting it",
       next:"read_it"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...Help me decide how. [you stay in the quiet, and you trust her to find it herself]",
       fx:{hype:12,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long, still moment] Help me decide how. [she looks at the card, the microphone, and then at you, for a long time] ...You're not going to decide for me. Again. You've done this the whole hour — given me the room and the quiet and then stepped back and let me be the one who chooses. After eleven years of being moved around by a floor and a form and a kind man with sad eyes, you — a stranger, in a studio that barely exists — are the first person to hand the choice to the woman and trust her to make it. [a breath] I'm not going to tell you what I've decided. I'm going to show you. In the next thirty seconds. Watch my hands. My hands have known what to do since I sat down; the rest of me has been catching up. [she steadies] Watch my hands."],
       next:"read_it"}
    ]
  },

  /* ================= CONVERGENCE: READ THE NUMBER ================= */
  read_it:{
    seg:"THE PEAK — read the number live", act:5,
    lines:[
      ["sys","TRANSMISSION","HEAT RISING. The hum on the line has settled into something almost deliberate. She's holding the card to the studio light, the long ID number visible along its edge. Her hands are shaking, but she hasn't put it away."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Here's the decision I came here unable to make alone. This number — the long one, the record-length one, the one I think means I was accessioned as a file — I could read it. On air. Right now. Into your tape. And the moment I do, it exists somewhere outside my head and outside their building, in a thousand strangers' ears, on a recording, permanent, un-erasable. A thing they cannot quietly migrate off a server or fog out of one old woman's failing memory."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","But the number is also ME. It's how four catalogued me. The moment I read it, I stop being nobody — they'll know which file walked out, which woman is talking, and being nobody is the only thing that's kept me safe for three years. [a long breath] So. You've been gentle with me all night. You've earned the right to weigh in on the most frightened decision of my life. Do I read it — make myself real and findable both — or do I stay nobody, and safe, and keep the number in the dark where it's always been? Tell me true. I'll listen."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"Read it, Agnes. Make it real. You won't have to carry it alone anymore — a thousand of us will carry it with you.",
       fx:{hype:24,heat:22,rapport:18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a tremor, then something settling] ...A thousand of us. [she breathes, and her voice steadies with each word] All right. All right. I've carried it alone for three years and you're right, the carrying is the thing that's killing me, not the danger. The number is — [she reads a long alphanumeric string, slow, and steadier with every character, like she's setting down something heavy one piece at a time] — there. [a long exhale] It's out. It's in a thousand ears now. It's not just mine anymore. [a sound that's almost a laugh through tears] Oh. That's — that's LIGHTER. I didn't know it would feel lighter. Eleven years it sat in the dark with my name on it and now it's loose in the world and I am, for the first time since I walked up those stairs, not the only place it lives. Whatever happens to me now — they can't un-ring it. The file spoke. Find the others. There are more of us than three."],
       reveal:"Reads the catalogue/accession number LIVE — 'the file spoke,' makes herself findable",
       flag:"read_all", next:"end_louder"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"Don't read the whole number. Read just the facility code — let a thousand listeners find the BUILDING without exposing the woman.",
       fx:{hype:20,heat:9,rapport:17},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[stopping, a slow dawning] ...Just the building. Not me. [a breath] Oh, that's — I never thought of splitting it. I thought it was all or nothing, read everything and become a target, or read nothing and stay a ghost. But you're right, the FACILITY code isn't me, it's THEM — it points at the building, the floor, the program, without pointing at the woman who walked out. [her voice gains a careful strength] Then here's the facility block, just the first part, the part that's theirs and not mine: [she reads a shorter code, clearly]. There. That's the building. That's the warm sealed sub-level four. Anyone listening who's heard of it, who's WORKED a floor like it, who's held a card that stays warm — that code is your confirmation that you're not crazy and not alone. Go look. Pull what's public. Find the yellow copy. I've given you the door without giving them the woman. [a breath] You just taught a frightened person she could fight and still stay safe. Nobody ever showed me those could both be true."],
       reveal:"Reads only the facility code — exposes the institution, protects herself",
       flag:"read_crowd", note:"The wise move: turns the audience into investigators without making Agnes the target.",
       next:"end_louder"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"Don't read it, Agnes. A number on pirate radio won't convict anyone, and it paints a target on the one of you who's still safe. Stay nobody.",
       fx:{hype:11,heat:-8,rapport:12},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a long silence, and when she speaks it's wet with a strange relief] ...You're protecting me. [a breath] A stranger, at three in the morning, telling me NOT to do the dramatic thing, not to make the good radio, not to give your show its big moment — telling me to stay safe instead. [she's crying, but it's gentle] Do you know, that's the only push I've ever been able to bear, because it's the only one that was FOR me and not against me. You pushed back on my plan to keep ME, not to dismiss me. [steadying] All right. I'll stay nobody a little longer. The number stays in the dark, with my name on it, where it's always been. But you BELIEVED me enough to want me protected, and an hour ago I came in sure I was crazy and alone, and I'm leaving knowing one real person in the world wants me safe. That does almost as much as reading the number would have. Almost. Maybe more. Thank you for not letting me set myself on fire for your tape."],
       reveal:"You counsel her NOT to expose herself — the rare protective push she can receive",
       flag:"refused", note:"The ONE push that helps Agnes: protective, not dismissive. She hears the care, not an attack.",
       next:"end_nobody"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"[you don't tell her what to do — you slide a glass of water toward her, and leave the choice, and the silence, entirely hers]",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:10,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[she takes the water, a long sip, and the silence stretches] ...You're not going to decide for me. [a breath] Everyone decides for me — the doctor, the supervisor, the form that called my friend's erasure voluntary. They all knew what was best for the frightened woman. And you, who've been kinder than any of them, are the one person who hands the decision back and says, with no words at all, it's yours. [a long pause] ...I don't think I can read the whole number tonight. I'm not ready to stop being nobody. But I came in barely able to speak into this microphone, flinching at the light, and look — I've talked for an hour, out loud, on a recording, and the building didn't reach through the wall and stop me. That's the thing four swore I'd never do. Speak. Be heard. And I did it, because you let the choice be mine. The number can wait. The speaking couldn't. Thank you for the water. Thank you for the quiet. Thank you for letting it be mine."],
       reveal:"You hand her the choice entirely; she chooses to stay nobody but leaves having found her voice",
       flag:"refused", next:"end_nobody"}
    ]
  },

  /* ================= ENDINGS ================= */
  end_louder:{
    seg:"THE LANDING — a little louder",  act:6,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","It's done. It's out — the building, or the number, or both — it's loose in the world now, in a thousand ears, and four can't reach into all of them. For the first time in eleven years something I know is also something other people know, and a thing that's witnessed can't be quietly erased. That's the whole secret I learned too late and you helped me finally use. Witness is the cure for being forgotten."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Before this is over — and the hum's getting louder, you hear it too, I know you do — tell me true, the way you've been true all night. After all of it, the warmth and the forms and the card that opens doors: do you think I lived through something real, or do you think a tired, frightened woman built a haunted house out of a hard job and a failing mind? I can hold either answer now. An hour ago I couldn't. You made it so I can. So tell me. I came to be witnessed, not coddled."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"I think you walked out of something real, Agnes — and I think it was real whether it was a ghost or a green form. Both versions are true and both are monstrous.",
       fx:{hype:16,heat:6,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a deep, settled breath, tears but steady] ...Both versions true. Both monstrous. That's the answer I've needed for three years and never had the courage to say to myself — I kept thinking I had to PICK, ghost or mold, haunting or cruelty, as if the truth would only count if it was the dramatic version. But you've set them side by side and let them both be real, and that's the first time the whole thing has felt SOLID instead of like something I might be making up. [a breath] Then I'm not crazy and I'm not alone, for one hour, and I'll keep that the way I kept Agnes Rose. I'm going to be a little louder from here. Not loud — I'll never be loud, four saw to that — but a little louder. For Marta. For the two women. For whoever hears this and recognizes their own warm floor. Thank you for witnessing me. Get your line swept; that hum isn't a hum. Goodnight, and — thank you for the lights down low."],
       reveal:"You affirm both readings are real and monstrous — she resolves to 'be a little louder'",
       note:"Agnes values the held-both verdict over a forced pick. The gentleness earned it.",
       next:"END"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The realest thing tonight is Marta, and the two women, and a whole language of cough drops and turned signs keeping people human in the dark. That's real. That happened.",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:5,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[breath catching] ...Marta. The language. [softly] You're right — set aside every uncanny thing, every warmth and every door, and what's LEFT is still true and still enough: a group of forgotten women built a tongue out of janitorial supplies to keep each other human while an institution wore them down and filed it as voluntary. That happened. No ghost required. That's real and it's provable and it's the thing I most need the world to know. [her voice firms] If anyone listening knew a woman who cleaned an underground floor and slowly went quiet and then was just... gone, with the paperwork all tidy — say her name tonight. Out loud. Let her be remembered by someone, since the building wanted her forgotten. That's all I really wanted. Not justice, I'm too small for justice. Just for the forgotten women to be, for one night, on a frequency that records, remembered. Goodnight, Night Frequency. Watch your line. And be gentle with the next one who whispers."],
       reveal:"Reframes the close as a memorial — 'say her name tonight'",
       next:"END"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"I believe you lived through exactly what you described, Agnes. Every degree of warmth, every emptied drawer.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a pause, almost gently correcting] ...Every bit of it. [a soft breath] You know, an hour ago that total belief is all I thought I wanted — for someone to say yes, every degree, every drawer, I believe the whole thing. But sitting here now, having said it all out loud to a kind person, I find I don't even believe every bit of it myself, and I'd rather you didn't either. There's a frightened, grieving, aging woman in this story whose mind was genuinely failing, and she's IN the truth, not separate from it. A total yes erases her the way the floor did. [steadier] So believe the FORM. Believe the warmth two women felt. Believe Marta. And hold the rest gently, as 'maybe,' the way I do. A 'maybe' I can live inside. A blanket 'yes' is a kindness that would, in the end, be its own small erasure. But you were gentle all night, so I'll take the warmth of it and forgive the size. Goodnight. Sweep your line."],
       note:"Even the affirming end, she gently refuses the blanket yes — it erases the grieving woman inside the truth.",
       next:"END"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...You were heard tonight, Agnes. [and nothing more — you let that be the whole verdict]",
       fx:{hype:14,heat:6,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a small, surprised, wet laugh] ...Heard. [a breath] Not believed, not doubted. Heard. [softly] Do you know, of every possible thing you could have said at the end, that's the only one I didn't know I needed until you said it. Belief I'd have grabbed at and doubted later. Doubt would've sent me home to the dark. But HEARD — heard is the thing four made impossible, the thing it took from all of us, the right to make a sound that lands in another person. You gave it back without a single promise about whether any of it was real. [a breath] That's the gift. Not a verdict. A hearing. I'll go be a little louder now, since I've remembered my voice makes a sound that reaches. You're a good host. The quiet kind. The gentle kind. The rarest kind. Goodnight, and thank you for hearing a woman who spent eleven years learning she couldn't be."],
       next:"END"}
    ]
  },

  end_nobody:{
    seg:"THE LANDING — nobody, a little while longer", act:6,
    lines:[
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","So I stay nobody. The number stays in the dark. Maybe you were right to keep me safe, or maybe we let the one shot slip by — that's the thing about caution, you never get to know what the brave version would have cost, or bought. I've lived in that not-knowing my whole life. One more unanswered door won't break me. I'm good at unanswered doors now."],
      ["guest","Sister Agnes","Before the line goes — and the hum's almost a voice now, you hear it — tell me true, the gentle way you've been true all night. A woman who lived through something real, or a woman who lost something and built a warm dark place to put the grief? You don't have to spare me. You've earned the right to say it plainly. I came to be witnessed, even quietly. So witness me, one last time."]
    ],
    choices:[
      {verb:"play",t:"Play Along",said:"I think you lived through something real, Agnes — and real whether the cause was a ghost or a green form. Both are true. Both are monstrous.",
       fx:{hype:15,heat:5,rapport:16},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[the most settled she's sounded all night] ...Both true. Both monstrous. [a long breath out] That's the answer, isn't it. I always thought I had to choose the dramatic version for it to count, and you've just let me set the ghost and the green form side by side and call them both real, and somehow that makes the whole thing finally feel SOLID instead of like a story I might be telling myself. I'll stay nobody — for now, for safety, the way you wanted for me — but I'll stay nobody knowing one real person heard the whole of it and called it real without making me read the number to earn it. [softly] That's a kind of safety I didn't know existed: to be believed AND protected. I'll carry the card a while longer. But it's lighter now, knowing it's been witnessed. Thank you for keeping me safe AND keeping me real. Sweep your line. That's not a hum. Goodnight, and thank you for the half-dark."],
       reveal:"Both readings affirmed; she stays safe but leaves witnessed and 'lighter'",
       note:"Belief plus protection — the safest, kindest outcome with Agnes. The gentleness compounded.",
       next:"END"},
      {verb:"steer",t:"Steer",said:"The realest thing here is a woman who begged the world to check her work for eleven years and got a kind smile instead. That part needs no ghost.",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:4,rapport:15},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[quiet] Got a kind smile instead. [a breath] Yes. That's the truest sentence anyone's said about it, and it needs no haunting at all: I asked, over and over, in my small careful way, for someone to LOOK — at the floor, at the air, at the forms, at the women going quiet — and every time I got the kind smile, the smile that means 'we've decided the problem is you.' Whatever four was, THAT happened, provably, to me and Marta and the two women and however many others. We asked to be checked and were managed instead. You gave me an hour of being checked, gently, for free, three years too late but real. It's enough. It's more than the building ever gave. I'll stay nobody, but a witnessed nobody, which is a different thing than I was when I walked in. Goodnight, Night Frequency. Be gentle with the next whisper. And sweep your line — please. For me."],
       reveal:"Reframes the close around 'asked to be checked, got a kind smile' — true with or without the supernatural",
       next:"END"},
      {verb:"push",t:"Push Back",said:"I believe all of it, Agnes — the warmth, the card, the floor, every word.",
       fx:{hype:6,heat:2,rapport:-18},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a gentle, almost rueful pause] ...All of it. [a breath] An hour ago I'd have wept with relief to hear that. And I'm grateful, I am. But I've talked it all out now, in the warm and the half-dark, and I find I can't quite let you believe MORE than I do, because there's a real frightened woman with a real failing memory inside this story and a total 'yes' tidies her away, makes her purely a witness and not also a grieving human being who might have built some of the warmth out of her own loss. [softly] Believe the form. Believe the warmth two of us felt. Believe Marta was real and is gone. And hold the card, and the doors, and the breathing floor as 'maybe,' the way I have to. A 'maybe' has room for me in it. A 'yes' that big, however kind, would be one more confident voice deciding the whole truth of a woman she met an hour ago. You've been gentler than that all night. End gentler than that. Believe me the right amount. Goodnight. Sweep your line."],
       note:"She gently declines the blanket yes even when staying nobody — it would erase the human inside the witness.",
       next:"END"},
      {verb:"dead",t:"Deadpan",said:"...You were heard tonight, Agnes. [you let that stand as the whole, gentle verdict]",
       fx:{hype:13,heat:5,rapport:13},
       reply:["guest","Sister Agnes","[a soft, surprised breath] ...Heard. [a long, peaceful pause] Not believed into a corner, not doubted out the door. Just heard. [softly] That's the one thing the floor made impossible and the one thing I came here starving for, and you gave it to me without asking me to pay for it with the number, without making me set myself on fire to earn it. A whole hour of a sound I made landing in another person. [a breath] I'll stay nobody. But I'll stay a nobody who, for one night, was heard — and that's not nothing, that's the opposite of what four spent eleven years teaching me. I made a sound. It reached you. It's on your tape. I existed, out loud, on the record, gently, once. That might be enough to live on for a long while. Thank you, host. The quiet kind. The gentle kind. Goodnight. And — sweep your line. That hum knows my voice now. But it can't have it back. I gave it to you first."],
       next:"END"}
    ]
  }

  },

  /* ---- finale validator: Agnes rewards GENTLENESS — rapport built
         through patience and belief, never cornering her. The wise path
         is reading only the facility code (exposes the institution, keeps
         her safe). Reading the whole number is brave but makes her a
         target (high heat). The protective push (refuse) is a valid,
         caring outcome. Heat is hard to raise (she's too quiet to
         triangulate) but accumulates as she names procedures/offices. ---- */
  score(s){
    const revScore = Math.min(100, s.reveals.length*6);
    let composite = s.peakHype*0.22 + s.rapport*0.42 + revScore*0.20 + (100-s.heat)*0.16;
    if(s.flags.read_crowd) composite += 9;   // exposed the program, protected herself — wisest
    if(s.flags.read_all) composite += 4;      // brave, but made herself a target
    if(s.flags.refused) composite += 3;       // staying safe is a legitimate, cared-for ending
    if(s.rapport < 35) composite -= 8;        // you cornered a fragile woman — the cardinal sin
    return composite;
  },
  outcome(s){
    let line;
    if(s.flags.read_crowd) line = "You helped Agnes read only the facility code — exposing the program without exposing the woman. A thousand listeners can now go looking for the warm sealed floor, the green form, the yellow copy, while Agnes stays nobody and safe. The wisest possible move: you turned a frightened witness into a beacon for all the others without making her the target.";
    else if(s.flags.read_all) line = "Agnes read the whole catalogue number live — the file spoke, permanent and un-erasable, in a thousand ears. The bravest thing she will ever do, and possibly the most dangerous: she stopped being nobody. She left lighter, and findable, and no longer the only place the number lives.";
    else if(s.flags.refused) line = "Agnes stayed nobody. The number remains in the dark with her name on it — but she leaves having been heard, having found that her voice makes a sound that reaches, which is the thing four spent eleven years teaching her was impossible. Sometimes keeping a fragile person safe is the whole achievement.";
    else line = "An hour spent being the gentle witness a frightened woman had given up hoping for.";
    const rapLine = s.rapport>=80 ? " You never cornered her, never rushed her, believed her without testing her — and she gave you the eeriest, most human tape this frequency has ever carried, the kind that only opens to patience."
      : s.rapport<=35 ? " You pushed too hard, too directly, and a fragile woman folded inward — apologizing, shrinking, half-leaving. The eeriest tape in the roster stayed locked, because the only key was gentleness and you reached for force." : " You and Agnes found a careful, gentle rhythm, and she trusted you with more than she's ever said aloud.";
    const heatLine = s.dangerHot ? " You let her name enough procedures and offices that the hum on the line learned the frequency — sweep it." : "";
    return line + rapLine + heatLine + ` Peak hype ${s.peakHype}, final heat ${s.heat}, rapport ${s.rapport}. ${s.reveals.length} things made it onto the tape, where they can never be quietly forgotten.`;
  },
  busted(s){
    return "You let her name the program out loud — the facilities, the form, the offices that keep the yellow copy — until the hum on the line stopped being a hum. Mid-sentence, the carrier found the transmitter, and the last thing the audience heard was Agnes, very quietly, saying 'oh — it's warm in here, isn't it, it's gotten warm' as the signal died. She'd know that warmth anywhere. Wherever she is now, she is not nobody, and she is not safe, and somewhere a green form is being filled out with a name typed at the top before she's even slipped. You traced a woman who survived eleven years by being unfindable. The floor finishes what it starts.";
  },
  walkout(s){
    return "You lost Agnes — which, with the gentlest guest on the frequency, takes a special kind of failure: you cornered her. You pushed back hard and direct on a woman whose whole nervous system reads challenge as the kind smile that precedes erasure, and she did what four taught her to do when threatened — she went quiet, apologized for wasting your air, said she'd known she'd sound crazy, and the line went soft and then dead. She didn't slam anything. Fragile people never do. She just folded back into being nobody, the warm card in her left pocket, the number unread, the floor's last lie — that it was voluntary — still standing, unanswered, in triplicate.";
  }
};
})();
